<FIRST>r w PM-TaxBill     07-21 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Eyes Catastrophic Coverage, Capital Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: May stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catastrophic health coverage for older
Americans, under heavy attack by some of its beneficiaries, is
facing new challenges from House tax-writers despite a tentative
vote to keep it alive.
   Awaiting action before the Ways and Means Committee is a
proposal to sharply reduce catastrophic coverage of prescription
drugs and use the money to cut the surtax that pays most of the
cost of the program. Also pending is an amendment that would allow
Medicare recipients to accept or reject catastrophic coverage.
   Another hot issue _ whether to cut the tax on capital gains _
remains unresolved. Supporters of the cut claim enough votes for
victory despite the opposition of Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., and House Speaker Thomas S. Foley. President Bush wants a
reduction.
   Aides said Rostenkowski is unlikely to allow a vote until after
he and Foley get a last chance to make their case before the caucus
of all House Democrats next week. The two leaders oppose a cut
because three-quarters of the benefits would go to those with
incomes over $100,000 a year.
   By a 23-13 margin, the committee rejected a motion that would
have put the committee on record for repeal of the year-old program
that helps older Americans bear the expense of catastrophic
illness. Most Democrats voted against repeal and most Republicans
favored repeal. Five from each party voted with the other side.
   Some of the 23 votes against repeal came from those who think
the program should be continued as it is. Others were cast by those
who want to end the program but know that would raise the federal
deficit by about $6 billion next year. That is because the
catastrophic tax is bringing in money faster than benefits are
being paid.
   Although the vote was on a procedural motion, committee aides
said it showed the panel is unlikely to recommend repeal.
   ``I just don't see how you can fix it to the satisfaction of the
beneficiaries,'' said Rep. Brian Donnelly, D-Mass., chief sponsor
of the repeal amendment. ``I don't think the status quo can survive
politically.''
   Catastrophic coverage is financed principally by a 15 percent
surtax on retirees who owe at least $150 in income tax. The maximum
surtax this year is $800 per person eligible for Medicare benefits.
   Those who have to pay that surtax have complained loudly and
demanded that Congress change the financing method so that the
program is funded by taxpayers of all ages.
   The committee is debating catastrophic and capital gains as part
of a bill whose chief aim is to raise $5.3 billion in new revenues
for deficit reduction next year.
   On Thursday, the committee added to the bill provisions
extending eight tax benefits that have expired or will expire at
year's end. With a total cost of $13.5 billion over five years,
they are:
   _Renewing through 1991 a tax exclusion of up to $5,250 a year in
employer-financed education assistance.
   _A two-year extension of the targeted-jobs tax credit, which
goes to employers who hire disadvantaged young adults.
   _A two-year extension of mortgage revenue bonds, which benefit
lower-income families buying their first home.
   _A two-year extension of a tax exemption for small issues of
bonds benefiting manufacturing plants and farmers.
   _Two-year renewal of a special credit for business purchase of
geothermal-energy equipment. The committee voted to end the credit
for solar energy.
   _Permanent extension of a credit for investments in low-income
rental housing.
   _Permanent extension of a credit for increased investment in
research and experimentation.
   _Making permanent a rule giving corporations a tax cut by
allowing them, within limits, to select how to write off research
expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
