<DOCNO> AP890721-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0259EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Fed-Economy     07-21 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Economy,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists See Fed Moving With Caution</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chairman Alan Greenspan confirms the Federal
Reserve reversed its yearlong campaign of pushing interest rates
higher, but that doesn't mean the central bank is soft on
inflation, economists say.
   Greenspan said in his twice-a-year report to Congress Thursday
that ``the balance of risks may have shifted somewhat away from
greater inflation'' and ``what we seek to avoid is an unnecessary
and destructive recession.''
   But, in the same breath, Greenspan told the House Banking
subcommittee on domestic monetary policy, ``inflation remains high
_ clearly above our objective.''
   Private economists are interpreting his remarks as a signal that
the central bank, which controls the nation's money supply and thus
the direction of its economy, will continue cautiously nudging
interest rates lower.
   ``The tilt in policy will be toward ease, but his easing moves
will come later rather than sooner and they will continue to be
small moves,'' said economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp;
Co., a government securities dealer in New York.
   Greenspan would not respond directly when asked by panel members
whether interest rates would continue to decline, but he indicated
he did not foresee another shift in policy soon.
   ``It is not desirable to do too many wiggles,'' he said.
   He confirmed the Fed loosened its grip on credit twice _ once in
early June and again early in July _ and that the effects of lower
interest rates are just now beginning to be felt.
   Greenspan said the Fed was gratified by the government's two
most recent inflation reports, for June, showing a modest 0.2
percent rise in the Consumer Price Index and a 0.1 percent decline
in wholesale prices.
   But, he cautioned, ``It's clearly premature, with one month's
data, to suggest that inflation pressures are behind us. Certainly
they are not.''
   Fed policymakers are ``not quite sure that inflation is as dead
as it looks now. As long as they're not, they're going to move as
slowly as they can get away with,'' said economist David Wyss of
Data Resources Inc., a Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm.
   Meanwhile, Michael Boskin, President Bush's chief economic
adviser, praised the Fed's recent action to lower interest rates,
but declined to say what he thought the central bank's next move
should be.
   ``I don't like to preach to the Fed in public,'' he told the
Joint Economic Committee.
   Greenspan also released a revised economic forecast which showed
the central bank still hopes to achieve a so-called soft landing in
which growth will slow enough to cool inflationary pressures but
not decline so much that the country is thrown into a recession.
   The Fed predicted modest economic growth, as measured by the
gross national product, of between 2 percent and 2.5 percent this
year, slowing to 1.5 percent to 2 percent in 1990. That compares
with the Bush administration's more optimistic projection of 2.7
percent in 1989 and 2.6 percent in 1990.
   The Congressional Budget Office on Thursday forecast a 2.4
percent rate of growth this year, slowing to 2 percent in 1990.
   The central bank forecast that consumer prices would rise by
between 5 percent and 5.5 percent this year, up from last year's
4.4 percent increase, and slowing to between 4.5 percent and 5
percent in 1990.
   The administration, meanwhile, is looking for a 5 percent rise
in consumer prices this year and 4.1 percent next year. The CBO is
looking for inflation a half point higher than the administration,
in the upper range of the Fed's 1989 projection.
</TEXT>
