<HEAD>Alleged Drug Trafficker Recommended For Extradition To Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A London court recommended the extradition to
Australia of an antiques dealer accused of giving drugs to heroin
addicts so they would steal valuables for him.
   Norman Cocks, 47, faces a total of 12 charges in Australia.
   Ten involve alleged trafficking in heroin between January 1984
and December 1985. The other two accuse him of handling stolen
goods in Australia in November 1985.
   He awaits a final extradition ruling by Home Secretary Douglas
Hurd. No date was given for that ruling.
   Prosecutor Michael Birnbaum, appearing on behalf of the
Australian government, told the court Thursday that Cocks was
involved in antiques dealing and ran a pawn shop in Victoria,
Australia.
   Birnbaum said that Cocks, a Melbourne native, met two heroin
addicts and hired them to steal to provide him with stock. He said
Cocks received the stolen goods and paid the men in heroin.
