<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSReservoir Bjt   07-21 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Reservoir, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say AIDS Virus Infects Many More Cells Than Previously
Believed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS patients may have up to 1,000 times more
diseased blood cells than previously believed, making it even
harder to stamp out the virus that causes the fatal disease,
according to a National Institutes of Health study published today.
   In a study led by Steven M. Schnittman of the National Institute
of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, researchers discovered that in
a patient with active AIDS the virus that causes the disease can
infect up to 1 percent _ 1 of every 100 _ of a blood cell known as
the T4 lymphocyte.
   Schnittman said in an interview that previous studies, which
used indirect measurements of the infection rate, had calculated
that only 1 in every 10,000 to 100,000 of the T4 lymphocytes in
such a patient were infected.
   The higher rate of infection, a factor that doctors call ``virus
load,'' suggests that it will be more difficult to develop a
therapy to find and eliminate each and every pocket of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) which causes AIDS.
   ``The quantity of the virus (found in the study) was a lot
higher than previously expected,'' Schnittman. ``There are more
cells infected, a greater proportion, than we knew before.''
   Schnittman said the study showed that a new research procedure,
called polymerase chain reaction, or PCR, may be used to monitor
the level of AIDS infection as a patient progresses from a point of
showing no symptoms to where the disease becomes life-threatening.
   With PCR, he said, researchers could measure precisely the
effects of drugs being tested to control or kill the AIDS virus.
   A research report authored by Schnittman and eight other
scientists was published today in the journal Science.
   Schnittman said he and his colleagues used blood samples from
patients with active AIDS to conduct the PCR search for the virus.
   Researchers first separated from the samples the T4 lymphocytes.
These immunity cells are thought to be the primary target of the
HIV virus.
   Blood studies in the past counted the number of cells infected
with the AIDS virus by measuring proteins triggered by an active
HIV virus. Thus, the level of infection was inferred instead of
directly measured.
   But Schnittman said the PCR technique detects the genetic
pattern of the AIDS virus while it is within a cell. In this way,
he said, the researchers could find infected cells even when the
AIDS virus is inactive.
   The PCR survey, which was developed only about a year ago, he
said, is an important new tool to help scientists understand the
life cycle of the highly complex AIDS virus, and perhaps find a
weak point where the killer disease could be attacked with drugs.
   Schnittman said the PCR study also showed that the AIDS virus
does not readily infect another type of immunity cell, the
monocyte, which also circulates in the blood. This finding is a
surprise, he said, because a monocyte matures into an immune cell
called macrophage. Studies have shown that macrophages in the
brain, liver and lymph nodes can be heavily loaded with AIDS.
   ``The real Trojan horse in the body is the T4 cells and not the
monocytes,'' said Schnittman. ``This shows the importance of
focusing therapies on the (T4 lymphocyte) cells.''
   AIDS is a contagious disease that attacks immune cells in the
body and renders them unable to resist disease. The HIV virus,
which causes AIDs, is spread most often through sexual intercourse
with infected persons or through needles shared by intravenous drug
users.
   As of May 31, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 97,193 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 56,468, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to
have recovered from AIDS.
   Schnittman's coauthors in the study were H. Clifford Lane,
Ferdinand Massari, Cecil H. Fox and Tony Fauci, all of NIH;
Miltiades C. Psallidopoulos, Louis Thompson and Normal P. Salzman
of Georgetown University School of Medicine in Washington; and
Michael Baseler of Program Resources, Inc.
   Science is the journal of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Newspapers-JOA     07-21 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspapers-JOA,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Joint Operating Agreements Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law that allows rival newspapers to share
business operations is weakening American journalism and should be
repealed, critics say.
   ``Never have so many given so much to so few for no good reason
at all,'' Bruce B. Brugmann, editor and publisher of the
70,000-circulation weekly San Francisco Bay Guardian, told a House
Judiciary subcommittee hearing Thursday.
   Brugmann's testimony came 20 years after he first opposed the
Newspaper Preservation Act. He said Thursday that the only people
who have benefited from joint operating agreements are rich
publishers who have become richer.
   The agreement between the two San Francisco dailies, the
Examiner and the Chronicle, Brugmann said, has led to less
competitive journalism.
   ``Non-competitive journalism breeds dull, irrelevant newspapers
that few people want to read,'' he said.
   The law allows newspapers in the same city to merge business
operations when one of the papers is in danger of failing. News
gathering operations remain separate.
   ``In 1970, the act was hailed as a necessary means of preventing
daily newspapers from falling victim to fierce market forces,''
said subcommittee chairman Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas. ``Yet, since
passage of the act, some estimate that over 200 papers have ceased
operation.''
   Jerry Friedheim, president of the American Newspaper Publishers
Association, testified that the act ``helped the marketplace evolve
and prosper.''
   ANPA is an international trade association of more than 1,400
newspapers, which represent 90 percent of the total daily and
Sunday newspaper circulation in the United States.
   ``No newspaper executives I know of would roll back either the
law or the decisions made in good faith during its existence,''
Friedheim said.
   W. Edward Wendover, editor and publisher of the weekly Community
Crier in Plymouth-Canton, Mich., said the act has ``encouraged
concentration of newspaper ownership, peculiar competitive
practices and lessened the vigor and quality of newspapering.''
   ``The principle of a free press cannot be maintained when the
biggest newspaper chains enjoy unregulated monopoly status,''
Wendover said, calling on Congress to repeal the law.
   Wendover testified for Michigan Citizens for an Independent
Press, a group of 1,400 readers, advertisers and employees of The
Detroit News and Detroit Free Press. The group filed a lawsuit in
August to block a joint operating agreement between the two papers.
   Gannett Co. Inc., which owns The Detroit News, and Knight-Ridder
Inc., owner of the Detroit Free Press, say the agreement is needed
to allow the Free Press to survive.
   The U.S. Supreme Court is scheduled to hear arguments on the
case this fall. There are 18 active joint operating agreements in
the United States.
   Brooks said his economic and commercial law subcommittee will
study the testimony and decide whether further hearings are needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
