<FIRST>r w PM-DC-Abortion     07-21 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Abortion,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel's Decision Angers Abortion Foes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion forces in Congress are preparing
to battle a House panel's decision to lift abortion funding
restrictions for the District of Columbia.
   The House Appropriations District of Columbia subcommittee voted
Thursday to allow the city to use its own money to pay for
Medicaid-funded abortions.
   The district had financed abortions from 1980 until last year,
when congressmen attached an amendment to the city budget banning
the use of federal or local money for abortions.
   Abortion opponents quickly said Thursday they will try to
restore the ban when the city's budget reaches the House floor.
   ``We have an amendment already drafted, and we are ready to go
with that again,'' said Brian Bennett, a spokesman for Rep. Robert
Dornan, R-Calif. ``We're hoping to have this one battle and move on
(to the Senate version of the budget).''
   City officials, who have called the anti-abortion measure an
intrusion on their right to self-governance, said they will fight
efforts to renew it.
   ``We will just dig in and prevail on this point of home rule
that has been restored to us,'' said Lurma Rackley, a spokeswoman
for Mayor Marion Barry Jr. ``We should be able to decide how to
spend our money.''
   Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said he favored lifting the
restriction in light of the recent Supreme Court ruling that
provides states greater latitude in drafting abortion laws.
   ``It will be interesting to see. ... We don't know what the
attitude will be on the floor of the House,'' Dixon said.
   Last year, Dornan and Reps. William Dannemeyer, R-Calif., and
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., led the fight to prevent the city from spending
public money on abortions.
   Congress, which has review power over all city laws and the city
budget, is free to attach amendments or make changes in the laws
before approving them.
   The bill is scheduled for a vote by the full committee Aug. 3,
and committee officials said it will likely reach the House floor
after the House returns from summer recess on Sept. 5.
</TEXT>
