<DOCNO> AP890721-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Pilots     07-21 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Pilots,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-10 Pilot Showed `Superior Airmanship'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot who guided a crippled jetliner
to a crash landing showed superior airmanship and ``ought to be
elected to the aviation hall of fame,'' according to a flight
engineer familiar with DC-10s.
   ``If he lost all three hydraulic systems, then the world ought
to be thankful that as many people survived that did,'' said Joe
Sullivan of Richardson, Texas, retired flight engineer for American
Airlines. ``Without hydraulic, you're out of business.''
   A United Airlines DC-10 bound from Denver to Chicago crash
landed at Sioux Gateway Airport on Wednesday after pilot A.C.
Haynes, a 33-year United veteran, radioed that he had a ``complete
hydraulic failure.''
   At least 76 people died, but 174 or more survived the crash.
Haynes was hospitalized, but he and the other two cockpit crew
members were among the survivors.
   ``If all the hydraulics were out, he ought to be elected to the
aviation hall of fame,'' Sullivan said. ``He had to call on every
bit of his airmanship, and it had to be superior, not just good. I
think it was a major miracle.''
   Jim Burnett, a National Transportation Safety Board member, told
a news conference Thursday night that the DC-10's hydraulic system,
which allow pilots to manipulate wing and tail controls, contained
no fluid as Haynes tried to land the plane.
   Earlier, Bob Raynesford, a spokesman for the FAA regional office
in Kansas City, said the aircraft may have lost some hydraulic
power but some must have remained.
   ``We were in constant contact with the crew for about 40
minutes, and the aircraft became more and more difficult to control
as it got closer to Sioux City,'' Raynesford said. ``We are hearing
about total hydraulic failure, but it is way too premature to say
for sure.''
   John Nance, a pilot and aviation writer in Seattle interviewed
by the AP News Network, agreed the jumbo jet had to have some
hydraulic pressure to stay airborne.
   ``I think we can say that we have a flight control problem but
we did not, repeat, did not, have an airplane that was totally out
of hydraulics, or he wouldn't have been flying at all.''
   The pilot probably relied on a backup source of hydraulic power
called the ram air turbine that would have made it increasingly
difficult to control the aircraft as it approached the airport,
Nance said.
   The ram air turbine operates some control surfaces by directing
the rushing outside air. As the airplane slows for a landing, the
forced air pressure would be reduced, thus making the surfaces
harder to control.
   ``If all you've got powering your hydraulic systems is a ram air
turbine, then as you slow down it will slow down, and then there
will be less hydraulic pressure available and thus less control
over the airplane,'' Nance said.
   ``I'll tell you what, I'll bet that damn thing hasn't been used
twice,'' in the history of the aircraft, said Sullivan. ``It's an
absolute last resort. It's not going to save you.''
   Ken Plunkett, a researcher for the Aviation Safety Institute of
Columbus, Ohio, said the DC-10 has three separate hydraulic systems
that control virtually every function of the airplane.
   ``It controls the wing flaps, the tail elevators, the rudders,
the brakes, the steering _ everything,'' he said. ``If you lose it,
you lose most of your control over the plane. That seems to be what
happened here.''
   On small planes, control surfaces are small and can be operated
by direct linkages from the control panel. But on large planes, the
hydraulic system provides a power assist. If it fails, there are no
alternative manual controls.
   ``The DC-10 has redundant hydraulics,'' said Maury Seitz, a
retired Delta Airlines pilot who now lives in Hurst, Texas. ``It's
set up so that if you lose one, you won't lose all of your
hydraulic fluid. And if you lose one system, you still have other
systems.
   Seitz speculated that the pilot lost rudder control just as he
approached the runway.
   ``From the looks of it, he had that baby under control, but then
he got into a roll situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
