<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Sequence     07-21 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Sequence,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Minutes on Flight 232: `Someday Finally Came'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At noon, the Sioux City fire department received a call from
Gateway Airport. It was a false alarm.
   Three and a half hours later, the call was genuine.
   United Airlines Flight 232, crippled by a loss of hydraulic
power, was attempting an emergency landing Wednesday afternoon on a
closed runway at the airport. The jet rolled to its right a few
feet from the ground, scraped its right wing, cartwheeled and burst
into flame.
   ``We've been talking for years that we've been awfully lucky
that we haven't had a severe accident down there, and that someday
it would happen,'' Fire Capt. Mike Kyle said.
   ``Someday finally came.''
   Here is the sequence of events, based on reports from officials
of the National Transportation Safety Board and the Federal
Aviation Administration and press accounts. Times are Eastern
Daylight Time.
   _ 2:45 p.m. The plane left Denver with 282 passengers, including
three infants, a cockpit crew of three and eight flight attendants
en route to Chicago.
   _ More than an hour into the flight. An explosion rocked the
plane over western Iowa, severe enough to knock ``the flight
attendants to the floor,'' the chief attendant told the NTSB. The
flight crew had to struggle to keep control of the plane.
   _ 4:16 p.m. The pilot reported to air traffic control in
Minneapolis that the jet had lost one of its three engines and that
he was losing altitude and having difficulty controlling the
15-year-old aircraft.
   _ 4:17 p.m. Flying at 31,000 feet, the pilot reported ``complete
hydraulic failure.'' The hydraulic system powers vital control
surfaces on the wings and tail that direct an aircraft in flight,
as well as brakes on the ground.
   Air traffic control directed him to Dubuque, on Iowa's eastern
edge.
   _ 4:20 p.m. The pilot declared an emergency and controllers
rerouted him to Sioux City, about 400 miles west of Dubuque.
   _ 4:24 p.m. Air traffic received an ``Alert 2'' from the pilot,
an indication of major problems with an inbound aircraft.
   ``There was a report of almost no control ability. The aircraft
could only be turned to the right. They made three 360-degree
turns,'' NTSB member Jim Burnett told a news conference Thursday.
   _ 4:30 p.m. Field workers returning from a coffee break at Alta,
60 miles east of Sioux City, discovered an 8-by-12 section of the
plane in a field and notified local authorities.
   _ 4:32 p.m. ``The crew told the tower they had serious doubts of
making the airport'' and starting talking about small airports in
the area and four-lane highways, Burnett said.
   _ 4:40 p.m. The pilot informed his passengers the tail section
was damaged and the plane was en route to Sioux City for an
emergency landing.
   ``The plane was rocking from side to side. I think the pilot was
trying to control it with the engines,'' said passenger David
Landsberger.
   ``The stewardesses ran us through a practice drill. They told us
to keep our seatbelts fastened tightly and to put our heads between
our legs. About four minutes before we crashed, they told us to
brace ourselves.''
   _ 4:58 p.m. Flight 232 crashed into a cornfield just short of a
runway, burst into flames and skidded into an adjoining cornfield,
scattering wreckage over an area the size of three football fields.
   With the advance warning, emergency medical and rescue crews
were already at the scene.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StateIncomes     07-21 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-State Incomes,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada, Far West Lead Nation in Income Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada's booming gambling industry is helping
the state lead the nation in the growth of non-farm income, the
government says.
   The Commerce Department, reporting non-farm income growth during
the 12 months ending March 30, said Thursday that Nevada led the
nation with a 15 percent increase.
   Wyoming trailed the other states, showing the only income growth
that was below the 5.9 percent rate of inflation for the 12-month
period, the department said.
   Nationwide, non-farm income increased 9.4 percent, although
there were wide differences between the states.
   Construction of more hotels and casinos, as well as the mining
industry, helped push Nevada ahead of the rest of the nation,
according to department analyst Rudolph E. DePass.
   Also showing sharp increases were Florida, whose non-farm income
was up 12.1 percent; Nevada's neighbor California, 10.7 percent;
Vermont, 10.5 percent; and Virginia, 10.5 percent.
   DePass said Wyoming's poor 5.7 percent increase was partly due
to declines in the construction and services industries.
   Other states at the low end of the rankings were: West Virginia,
up 6.3 percent; North Dakota, 6.4 percent; Oklahoma, 6.9 percent;
and Alaska, 7.2 percent.
   By region, the Far West, with Nevada and California, led the
nation with non-farm income growth of 10.5 percent. This was
followed by the Southeast, up 9.9 percent, and New England, up 9.6
percent.
   Other regions and their income growth rates were: Great Lakes, 9
percent; Mideast, 8.9 percent; Plains, 8.8 percent; Southwest, 8.6
percent; and Rocky Mountains, 8.2 percent.
   Differences between coastal and interior regions in non-farm
growth continued to narrow from the first quarter of 1988 to the
first quarter of 1989, DePass said, although coastal growth did
continue to outpace the inland areas.
   The Commerce Department focuses on changes in non-farm income as
a better indication of a region's prosperity because of the often
erratic nature of farm incomes.
</TEXT>
