<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-21 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down slightly against the Japanese
yen Friday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 234.56
points, or 0.69 percent, ending the week at 33,899.43. The index
rose 107.70 points on Thursday.
   The dollar closed at 142.15 yen, down 0.08 yen from Thursday's
close of 142.23 yen. After opening lower at 141.60 yen, the
currency ranged between 141.53 yen and 142.25 yen.
   Currency traders attributed the dollar's lower opening to its
decline in New York, following comments by Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   In testimony before Congress on Thursday, Greenspan acknowledged
that ``signs of softness'' in the American economy have shown up
and said the Fed must closely monitor the slowing economy.
   ``Everyone is reluctant to take long positions for the dollar,
nearing the weekend and Sunday's parliamentary elections,'' said
Norio Takeda, a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   Takeda said investors are concerned over a possible early
election for the nation's powerful House of Representatives if the
governing Liberal Democratic Party suffers a major setback Sunday.
   Numerous newspaper surveys forecast a heavy loss for the LDP,
which may cause the yen to lose value.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index shed its earlier gains on
profit-taking selling, with many investors foreseeing a defeat for
ruling party candidates in the election, Kazuyuki Suzuki of Daiwa
Securities said.
   Factors contribuing to a gloomy outlook for the LDP are the
influence-buying Recruit scandal, an unpopular 3-percent
consumption tax imposed April 1, and allegations that Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno has kept paid mistresses.
