<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0408 07-21 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0408,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Case Mirrors Israeli Debate on the PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CORRECT that appeal held Thursday, SUB grafs 5, 12, 18.
^By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assciated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court is hearing an appeal by
four peace activists convicted of meeting with PLO officials, a
politically charged case that mirrors the debate over a possible
PLO role in any peace settlement.
   The court arguments are legal ones, but they focus on the wider
issue of whether dealing with the PLO can hasten peace or only give
credibility to what the government considers a terrorist
organization bent on Israel's destruction.
   Attorney Avigdor Feldman says his clients, the first people
convicted under an amendment to Israel's anti-terrorist law, met
with PLO officials to help end the long Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``They were trying to stop the bloodshed in the (occupied)
territories,'' Feldman said. ``Their meeting was for the purpose of
peace.''
   On Thursday, prosecutor Ariyeh Romanoff argued that the peace
activists's meeting with 15 PLO representatives, held in Romania in
1986, was a dangerous act of protest.
   ``We are talking about a demonstration against the law and not
activities on behalf of peace,'' Romanoff said.
   He added they commited an ``ideological crime ... as serious as
murder and other criminal violations'' in the context of the
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   The 19-month revolt, in which 572 Palestinians and 37 Israelis
have died, is also at the heart of the national debate.
   The rebellion is widely credited with leading to PLO Chief
Yasser Arafat's recognition of Israel, and some leftist Israeli
politicians and dovish members of the mainstream Labor Party see
Arafat's moderation as an opening for Israel to talk to the PLO.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister Moshe Arens
argue that any contact with the PLO hinders attempts to reach a
settlement with non-PLO Palestinians in the occupied territories.
   Abba Eban, a senior statesman of the center-left Labor Party,
ridiculed that stand in Sunday's Jerusalem Post. ``We refuse to
negotiate with those who are willing and are ready to negotiate
with those who don't exist,'' he wrote.
   The arguments are likely to rage on longer than the Supreme
Court case. But after hearing the appeal Thursday the judges gave
one of the defendants permission to take a month's trip abroad,
hinting their judgment may take a while.
   The four defendants _ Latif Dori, Yael Lotan, Eliezer Feiler and
Reuven Kaminer _ were convicted last year of violating a 1986 law
that made contacts with the PLO a misdemeanor.
   They were sentenced to six months in jail each, along with
one-year suspended sentences, but the jail terms later were
commuted to community service. Each was also ordered to pay a
$2,000 fine.
   The outcome of their appeal is likely to affect several other
cases.
   Peace activist Abie Nathan also has been charged with violating
the anti-terrorist law by meeting last year with Arafat, but his
trial was postponed until September pending the outcome of the
court appeal.
   Last month, right-wing members of the Knesset, or parliament,
demanded that Attorney General Yosef Harish press charges against
four left-wing legislators for also meeting with Arafat. Harish
said he intended to press charges.
   During a recess in Thursday's appeal, one of the defendants,
Kaminer, said he would turn to the Knesset to change the law
against meeting with the PLO if the court did not overturn it.
   ``The paradox here is not only are we not guilty of this, we
opposed terrorism in our meeting,'' he said. ``The anti-terror law
was not meant to put people who oppose terrorism in jail.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
