<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-AIDSTesting     07-21 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-AIDS Testing,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Program for Drug Abusers Wins Praise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Reservoir, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. health officials say an AIDS testing and
counseling program in Boston set up to serve an estimated 14,000
intravenous drug abusers shows promise in reaching that high-risk
group.
   In its first year, Project TRUST served 688 clients,
administering tests to 635 for infection with HIV, the virus which
causes AIDS, the national Centers for Disease Control reported
Thursday. TRUST is an acronym for Teaching, Referral,
Understanding, Support and Testing.
   Project TRUST's 635 testing clients compared with just 473 who,
the CDC said, came for anomymous testing at other test sites and
clinics in the Boston area. And 79 percent, or 503 of Project
TRUST's 635 testing clients, returned to learn the results and seek
counseling.
   ``For anonymous testing, that's very high,'' said CDC researcher
Dr. Charles S. Rabkin, adding that some AIDS testing and counseling
programs have seen as few as 10 percent of clients return for
results and follow-up.
   CDC officials attributed the program's success to its location
in a heavy drug-use neighborhood, promotion through pamphlets and
word of mouth, and to the fact that several of the outreach workers
were recovering drug addicts.
   The CDC said intravenous drug abusers made up one-third of all
U.S. AIDS cases reported last year.
   ``It's worthwhile to have services directed for intravenous drug
users,'' Rabkin said. ``Services specially tailored for them can be
successful.''
   ``The high percentage ... who returned for their test results
indicates that HIV prevention measures can be effectively
provided'' to intravenous drug abusers ``if services are tailored
to the specific needs and circumstances of this high-risk group,''
the Atlanta-based CDC said in its weekly report.
   Meanwhile, the CDC said Thursday that 28 states require
reporting of HIV infections to public health authorities. Those
states account for 45 percent of the U.S. population and 24 percent
of the nearly 100,000 AIDS cases reported through last month.
   Such reporting, the CDC said, is useful in directing patient
counseling and sex-partner notification efforts. Eighteen of the 28
HIV-reporting states require reports by name, the CDC said, but
``reporting should be accompanied by appropriate safeguards for
confidentiality.''
   All states require the reporting of actual AIDS cases to public
health authorities.
</TEXT>
