<FIRST>r w PM-US-PLO     07-21 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-PLO,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Backs Administration Talks With PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's defeat of a determined effort to
curb the U.S. dialogue with the Palestine Liberation Organization
hands President Bush's Mideast policy a significant boost from
Congress.
   In a separate action on Thursday, the Senate also voted 59-39 to
open the door to possible U.S. military aid to non-communist
resistance forces in Cambodia.
   Supporters of the aid amendment offered by Sen. Charles Robb,
D-Va., called it an essential step to help the administration's
efforts to prevent a return to power of the Khmer Rouge, which was
blamed for the deaths of more than a million Cambodians during
their four-year reign in the late 1970s.
   Opponents said the United States should not aid any faction in
Southeast Asia in light of the U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War.
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said the Senate was moving too
quickly, approving the possible provision of military aid in the
middle of the night and without proper consideration and debate.
   ``I stood on this floor when we slid into the war in Vietnam,''
Byrd said. ``I think we should let history give us some guidance
before we take sudden action here and write a blank check for the
president.''
   The Senate, by voice vote early today, late approved the overall
bill authorizing $4.6 billion for the operation of the State
Department and allied agencies in the 1990 fiscal year.
   The Senate shelved, 75-23, an amendment by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., which would have halted the talks unless the president
certified none of the PLO participants had any link with an act of
terrorism that had resulted in the murder, injury or kidnapping of
an American citizen.
   Bush sent a strongly worded letter defending the talks, calling
Helms' measure a formula for ending the dialogue and damaging if
not destroying the U.S. role in the Mideast peace process. He said
it was an unconstitutional assault on his powers to conduct U.S.
foreign policy.
   The Senate approved, 97-1, a compromise that would stop the
dialogue only if the president actually knew that one of the PLO
negotiators was a direct participant in an act of terrorism and
advised the Congress.
   Helms, the only senator to vote ``no,'' called that ``nothing
but a fig leaf to permit the State Department to continue to do
what they've been doing.''
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine said: ``It is my
understanding that if the president knows of such facts he will
advise the Congress,'' thus cutting off the talks.
   Helms, however, said the Senate had a clear choice.
   ``Are we or are we not going to reward terrorists?'' he asked.
``Are we or are we not going to bestow respectability upon them?''
   Helms introduced the amendment after two unannounced meetings
between Robert Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, and
PLO representative Saleh Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad.
   Khalaf is accused of masterminding the massacre of Israeli
athletes at the 1972 Olympic Games in Munich and is a suspect in
the 1973 assassination of the U.S. ambassador to the Sudan, Cleo
Noel Jr.
   The United States opened talks with the PLO in December after
Chairman Yasser Arafat publicly renounced terrorism and accepted
Israel's right to exist.
   The Senate also voted 56-42 to adopt another Helms amendment
which could make it difficult or impossible for the Soviet Union
ever to occupy its new embassy here.
   The new U.S. Embassy in Moscow cannot be occupied because it is
riddled with Soviet eavesdropping devices. No decision has been
made on how to replace it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
