<HEAD>Leftists Detonate Bombs, Four Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas exploded bombs
containing propaganda leaflets in the capital and two other cities,
wounding four people, Honduran news reports said.
   The leaflets said the six bombs that exploded Thursday were
planted by the May 9 Popular Liberation Forces, a leftist groups
not previously known, according to reports by radio station HRN and
Radio America.
   The leaflets said an internal struggle had developed in
Honduras' small guerrilla movement.
   Three bombs exploded in Tegucigalpa, with one wounding a
20-year-old student and a child as both walked through the city's
main plaza, the stations said. Two students suffered minor injuries
when another device went off in a garbage container at teacher's
college just outside the city, they said.
   Two others exploded at the National University in Tegucigalpa
and the coastal city of La Ceiba, 217 miles north of the capital.
   The other two went off at the teacher's college in San Pedro
Sula, 120 miles north of Tegucigalpa, according to the reports.
   The guerrilla communiques said that a ``fight to the death'' had
begun with the guerrilla movement and that the May 9 Popular
Liberation Forces had emerged from the division in the movement.
   It said it took its name from the day Cristobal Perez, 36, was
assassinated in 1986 when he was about to denounce corruption in
the Unified Workers' Federation, a leftist union of about 30,000
workers.
</TEXT>
