<DOCNO> AP890721-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0534EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Survivors     07-21 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Survivors,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Talk of Good Fortune in Flight 232 Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of United Airlines Flight 232 returned
to tearful reunions with relatives, their joy tempered by the
horrors of the fiery crash and thoughts of those who failed to
reach safety.
   ``We ordered a couple of shots of whiskey, sat there and talked
about how fortunate we are,'' said Garry Priest, 23, of Northglenn,
who returned on a flight from Sioux City, Iowa, with Bruce Benham
of Littleton.
   The pair arrived at Stapleton International Airport Thursday
holding a bottle of wine they had been given by United flight
attendants.
   At least 174 of the 293 people aboard survived when the DC-10 on
a flight from Denver to Chicago on Wednesday went out of control
during an emergency landing at Sioux Gateway Airport and crashed in
a twisting, flaming mass of wreckage.
   Benham and Priest had been flying to Chicago on business for
VICORP Restaurants in Denver, sitting in a middle section of the
jet. They said everyone in their section escaped serious injury and
wandered out together through a hole in the plane and into a
cornfield.
   Priest said when he got out of the wreckage the area looked
``like a war zone. Bodies, trash, magazines, luggage, and pieces of
bodies littered the area.
   ``I feel bad for the people that I saw on the runway and that
got caught,'' he said.
   He said he and several other passengers found an injured woman
outside the plane bleeding, and carried her several hundred yards
through tall stalks of corn to the runway.
   ``It was real organized. It really was,'' he said. ``Everybody
was just saying, `OK folks, let's take our time. Let's just walk
out,' and we did.''
   Benham, who had a bandaged arm, praised the pilot and the flight
attendants for being calm, relaxed ``and honest.''
   ``The whole thing seemed very unreal,'' said Benham, adding that
he was shocked by television footage he saw later of the plane
cartwheeling, because he did not remember such violence.
   Priest and Benham hugged crying family members after their
arrival.
   ``He looks terrific,'' Deborah Benham said of her husband. She
said the family planned to ``just relax. Period. We're going to go
somewhere without a phone.''
   Earlier, crash survivor Donna Treber of Westminster arrived at
Stapleton to meet her husband, Myron, who said she had not been
afraid to fly again. ``She said, `I just want to get on a plane and
come home,''' he said.
   But Dan McKelvey of Grand Junction said his family will never
fly again. He set out for Sioux City by car to pick up his wife,
Debbie; children Ryan, 7, and Devon, 5; and family friend Ruth
Pearlstein, all of whom escaped the crash without injury. Ryan was
stung by a bee as they ran through the cornfield from the plane.
   ``The plane had flipped and had broken apart in front of them
and they were hanging upside down,'' said McKelvey.
   Larry M. Hjermstad, 49, of Durango, his son, Eric, 12, and
daughter, Alisa, 8, were on their way to visit relatives in
Minnesota when the accident happened. Hjermstad's wife, Julie, flew
to Minneapolis Thursday with clothes to replace belongings
destroyed when the plane exploded.
   Alisa told her grandmother, Bobbie Ledgerwood, that she saw many
dead people and asked her mother not to fly, Ledgerwood said.
   Fred Hardman of Boulder said his wife and two children also
survived the flight without serious injury.
   Son Ryan, 14, said the family got out through a hole in the
plane's floor.
   ``It's just amazing, it was just there. If we had to go out
through a door, I don't think we would have made it,'' he said.
   His father said: ``From the time I heard the plane went down
till the time I knew they were alive was the tough part.''
</TEXT>
