<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Mood     07-21 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Mood,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Opens Arms to Crash Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN STEFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Missouri River city opened its arms
to the survivors of United Flight 232 as residents offered their
time, blood and prayers to heal the wounds left by the fiery crash.
   ``I didn't get any sleep last night, but I don't think I'm going
to have any problem tonight,'' fire Capt. Terry Schmidt said late
Thursday. He had been at Sioux Gateway Airport around the clock
since the DC-10 jumbo jet crashed while trying to make an emergency
landing the day before.
   While crews stopped searching the wreckage and began to close
off the area, more than 300 people gathered at the Cathedral of the
Epiphany to pray for the victims and the survivors.
   ``The heroism, care, the concern, of the passengers and crew of
flight 232 was harvested in this sacred field,'' the Rev. Jerry
Cosgrove said of the cornfield where the plane came to rest.
   ``A field which became a tomb for far too many was also a cradle
of new life for others. A field became a sacred place.''
   Vacationing, off-duty and former employees of the city's two
hospitals pitched in to deal with the emergency.
   At times there were two doctors to every patient as survivors
were wheeled into emergency wards a dozen at a time, said Dr. David
Greco, chief of the emergency department at Marian Health Center.
He said people turned out in such numbers to give blood Wednesday
night that less than a third of it was needed for injured
passengers.
   ``I think there was a tremendous feeling of people wanting to do
something,'' said Les Horrell Jr., chamber of commerce president.
   Sioux City, a beef, pork and grain processing center, is a town
of 82,000 that sits on the east bank of a giant bend in the
Missouri River.
   ``Our chief of staff chartered an airplane and flew home from
vacation in Minnesota,'' said Sue Conner, spokeswoman for St.
Luke's Medical Center.
   ``We had offers of help from doctors and nurses at hospitals in
three states,'' she said. ``Several hospital burn units also
offered to send nurses or treat our patients.''
   At Marian, Vice President Andrew Allen said supplies arrived
from hospitals in Sioux Falls, S.D., and Omaha, Neb. ``We probably
got five months of inventory inside of three hours,'' he said.
   Nurses were handing out emotional support along with bandages,
said Jane Morgan of St. Louis, Red Cross health services officer
for the relief operation.
   ``They need someone to listen to them,'' Ms. Morgan said.
``Someone to go through the feeling they have _ the anger, the
grief, the guilt.''
   The Rev. Bob Condon, a Roman Catholic priest and psychology
professor at Briar Cliff College, where many survivors were put up
for the night, said the school was swamped with volunteers.
   ``People want to help in any way they can, so much so that is
was almost overwhelming,'' he said.
   Pat Kosse, a recent graduate of Briar Cliff, arrived Thursday
morning when the school already had more volunteers than it could
use. She ended up giving directions to news people and others on
campus.
   ``A lot of people's hearts are going out to the victims of the
crash. I couldn't believe that something like this happened in
Sioux City,'' she said.
</TEXT>
