<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-21 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed marginally lower against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo today, while prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 234.56
points, or 0.69 percent, ending the week at 33,899.43.
   With today's gain, the index has risen a total of 555.70 points
since Wednesday, following five days of losses totaling 403.04
points.
   The dollar closed at 142.15 yen, down 0.08 yen from Thursday's
close of 142.23 yen. After opening lower at 141.60 yen, the
currency began rising, ranging between 141.53 and 142.25 yen during
the day.
   A dealer with Mitsubishi Bank said participants bought dollars
in the afternoon session to make position adjustments.
   ``But many market players were unable to see a firm upward
direction for the dollar'' because of uncertainty over the outcome
of the nation's parliamentary elections on Sunday, said the dealer,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   She said the Bank of Japan stepped into the market to support
the yen on a small scale but it did little to brake on the dollar's
upward pressure in the afternoon session. The central bank does not
customarily comment on its market interventions.
   Several newspaper surveys predicted that the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party would suffer a heavy loss in Sunday's elections
for half the seats in the 252-member House of Councillors.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index shed 45.54 points during
the morning session, but many investors changed their minds in the
afternoon, traders said.
   ``Investors became bullish that share prices would remain strong
in the longer term,'' despite predicted losses for LDP candidates
in the elections, Yozo Asai of Yamaichi Securities said.
   Yamaichi said LDP losses in the elections had ``already been
taken account of by the market to some extent'' when the Nikkei
index fell for five consecutive trading days between July 12 and
July 18.
   ``There are not likely to be any specific factors that will
adversely affect the stock market between July and September so far
as (Japan's) economy is concerned,'' he added.
   Volume traded on the first section totaled 550 million shares,
compared to 500 million shares on Thursday.
</TEXT>
