<FIRST>r a PM-RitualSlayings     07-21 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritual Slayings,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Matamoros Defendant Will Cooperate with Drug Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors arranged a plea bargain
with a man linked to a cult ring that allegedly smuggled marijuana
and killed at least 15 people in rituals intended to magically
protect its operations.
   Serafin Hernandez Rivera, 45, pleaded guilty Thursday to
possession with intent to distribute 113 pounds of marijuana seized
in May 1987.
   Prosecutors will recommend dropping four other drug-related
charges against Hernandez, along with a firearms indictment, in
exchange for Hernandez' cooperation, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
John Crews.
   Hernandez Rivera was the only person arrested in the United
States in connection with the discovery of 15 bodies, many of them
horribly mutilated, near Matamoros, Mexico, in April.
   Hernandez was never accused in any of the killings.
   His son, brother and three other men are in jail in Matamoros on
murder and drug charges. Six other people have been jailed in
Mexico City, and another of Hernandez' brothers is a fugitive.
   Prosecutors also agreed not to seize Hernandez' Brownsville
home, indict him in connection with an alleged 75-kilogram cocaine
purchase last year, or recommend that the resident alien be
deported to Mexico.
   Crews would not say how Hernandez is expected to cooperate.
   Hernandez' attorney, Richard Hoffman, could not be reached for
comment Thursday.
   Crews said prosecutors would not oppose Hernandez' release on
bond. Hernandez faces up to 20 years in prison when he is sentenced
Aug. 24.
   The firearms charge stems from the seizure of a sawed-off
shotgun during a search of Hernandez' residence after the discovery
of the bodies near Matamoros. Hernandez was arrested April 17 in
Houston.
   Ofoficials said the drug ring smuggled a ton of marijuana a week
into the United States.
