<FIRST>r a PM-HartwigLetters     07-21 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hartwig Letters,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>USS Iowa Sailor's Letters Reflect Navy Pride, `Outsider' Feeling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Their' in 3rd graf and `hear' in last graf are as in letter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man described in news reports as the sailor
who may have set off the USS Iowa blast in which he and 46
shipmates were killed said in letters to his girlfriend that the
Navy was his life.
   In a Dec. 1 letter to Charlene Meter, Gunner's Mate Clayton
Hartwig, 25, said he was not seeking a commitment from her because
of their different lifestyles and because he planned to re-enlist.
   ``I feel like an outsider, a visitor when I come `home,''' he
wrote. ``I don't know anyone but my family. I have no friends in
Cleveland, their all in the Navy.''
   Copies of 11 of Hartwig's letters were made available to The
Associated Press by his sister, Kathy Kubicina, of Cleveland. Ten
of the letters were to Ms. Meter and one was to Hartwig's parents.
   An unreleased Navy report says Hartwig, 25, may have set off the
April 19 gun turret blast that killed him and 46 others on the
battleship, NBC News and The New York Times reported this week.
   NBC reported Tuesday that a Navy investigation has ruled out
mechanical problems, accidental detonation or other technical
causes for the explosion.
   The investigators based their findings on an FBI psychological
profile of Hartwig and 228 other exhibits, including a three-hour
videotaped statement from an Iowa sailor who said he rejected
Hartwig's sexual advances, NBC said.
   A psychiatric study done by the FBI Center for Analysis of
Violent Crimes found that Hartwig was disturbed and under a lot of
stress, ``virtually insuring some type of reaction. In this
instance, it is suicide,'' according to the report.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the Navy's report is in
Norfolk, Va., on the desk of Vice Adm. Joseph S. Donnell III, the
commander of the Naval Surface Forces. The spokesman said the
report must go up the chain of command for review before being
submitted to Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   Navy sources said Thursday the report is expected to take
several more weeks to complete.
   Ms. Kubicina has rejected suggestions that the blast may have
been caused by sabotage by a suicidal Hartwig. Their father, Earl
V. Hartwig of Cleveland, said there was ``no way, definitely'' that
his son was suicidal.
   Ms. Kubicina said the letters she released show he was a normal
serviceman. She said that she earlier gave the originals to the
Navy in hopes of clearing his name.
   In letters to Ms. Meter, Hartwig wrote about their different
lifestyles and mentioned feelings of loneliness.
   ``For the last 6 yrs, all I've known is the Navy. I'm military
through and through and at times it's hard for me to get along with
civilians,'' he wrote in a Nov. 8 letter written from a ship off
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
   ``I guess it's like this. I have no idea what goes on in your
life in college,'' he continued. ``Your problems from day to day,
your frustrations, the people you can't stand, what you do. It's
the same for you with me. There's no way you could understand what
it's like to live in a cramped ship and be at sea for months at a
time.''
   Three days before the explosion, Hartwig again wrote to Ms.
Meter, from the Iowa in the Caribbean.
   ``I spent a lot of time outside today just watching the water go
by and thinking. It's really quite beautiful out hear if you stop
to notice,'' he wrote. ``We saw some whales swimming along in front
of the ship. The water is a bright royal blue and the sky was
crystal clear.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
