<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0731EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Glance     07-21 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Glance,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Crash Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Thursday in the crash of
United Airlines Flight 232 at the Sioux Gateway Airport in Sioux
City, Iowa:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   At least 76 people were killed, and up to 43 others were missing
and believed dead.
   Rescuers said many of those unaccounted for probably were
trapped in a section of the charred fuselage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SURVIVORS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   United said at least 183 survived among 293 people aboard the
aircraft. Jim Burnett, board member of the National Transportation
Safety Board, said there were 186 survivors and 295 passengers,
including a fourth person in the cockpit. City Manager Hank Sinda
put the number of survivors at 174, including the three working
cockpit crew members.
   Some survivors walked away from the wreckage.
   Dr. David Greco, one of the first physicians on the scene, said
the first-class section was devastated. Passengers in rows nine
through 19 suffered no injuries or minor ones, he added, but
``there was nothing left of the rear half of the aircraft.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PILOT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad visited Capt A.C. Haynes, the pilot, at
his bedside and told reporters: ``He was quite emotional about the
situation and tears came to his eyes when he talked about the
number of people who lost their lives. ... I told him he did a
valiant job.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CRASH SITE SEARCH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators painstakingly searched the crash site, roughly the
length of three football fields.
   National Guardsman collected pieces of wreckage and carried body
bags to ambulances and refrigerated trailers.
   The flight voice and data recorders were recovered, taken to
Washington and found to be in good condition, said NTSB
aeronautical engineer Thomas Jacky. Their contents are unlikely to
be made public for several weeks.
   A piece of the plane roughly 8-by-12 feet was discovered in a
cornfield 55 miles east of Sioux City.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POSSIBLE CAUSE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Aviation Administration authorities said the pilot first
reported ``uncontained engine failure,'' which means parts shot out
of the engine, possibly damaging other systems and causing what the
pilot later described as ``complete hydraulic failure.'' Spokesman
Bob Raynesford said the failure was in the tail engine, one of
three on the aircraft. The hydraulic system is routed through the
tail.
   Burnett said an entire fan-rotor system was missing from an
engine. ``That's the first time for this type of engine that we've
ever seen,'' he said. The jet's hydraulic system, which controls
wing and tail flaps and other key controls, contained no fluid at
landing, he said. The pilot had almost no control of the aircraft
during the last 34 minutes of the flight, he said.
   Investigators found several ``projectile penetrations,''
including a 10-inch-by-12-inch hole, in the horizontal stabilizer,
the small wing on the plane's tail, NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz
said. The rear engine sits just above the stabilizer.
   A McDonnell Douglas spokesman said the DC-10 is ``as fit as any
other'' airliner and has flown 745 million passengers safely more
than 7 billion miles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PLANE'S HISTORY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An FAA spokeswoman said records on problems with the jet show a
fairly good history, with two engine flameouts and some minor
problems with the landing gear.
   The 15-year-old plane had no accidents or reports of serious
incidents during the past five years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SIOUX CITY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sioux City residents mobilized to help crash survivors while
volunteers and supplies poured into the town of 82,000.
   Vacationing, off-duty and former employees of the city's two
hospitals pitched in and local businesses and residents donated
food, clothing and toiletries.
   One man reported standing in a block-and-a-half line Wednesday
night to give blood. The Siouxland Blood Bank reported that 305
units of blood were available at the two hospitals, although less
than a third of that blood was needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghan-Journalist 1stLd-Writethru a0491 07-21 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-Journalist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freelance News Photographer Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with U.S. officials providing letter asking
O'Brien's release, background. No pickup. ADDS byline. ^By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today released American
photojournalist Tony O'Brien six weeks after he was arrested in
Kabul in the company of anti-government guerrillas who brought him
into the country.
   ``I want to walk on the street,'' O'Brien, 43, of Santa Fe,
N.M., said moments after he was formally handed over to U.S.
consular officer Renny Smith, who had flown to Kabul from New Delhi.
   ``I want to thank the people of Afghanistan, the government of
the United States and (President) Najibullah,'' said O'Brien, who
had been on assignment for Time-Life Inc., covering the war from
the Pakistan border city of Peshawar.
   The photographer was arrested at a rebel hideout in the capital
on June 8 after entering the country without a visa.
   But he was never formally charged and the Soviet-backed
government agreed to release him after a personal appeal by PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   He is to fly home via New Delhi on Saturday.
   The Afghan government had demanded a formal letter from the
State Department requesting O'Brien's release and authorizing Ms.
Smith to escort him out of the country. Ms. Smith said she
delivered a letter and another one was sent by telex from
Washington direct to the Afghan government.
   The contents of the letters were not disclosed.
   ``They got what they wanted,'' she said without elaborating.
   Diplomatic sources said the government appeared to be using
O'Brien as a pawn in an effort to force the United States, which
backs the rebels, into issuing a statement that could be construed
as recognizing Najib's government as legitimate.
   A French photographer and an Italian photojournalist captured by
government forces were freed last year, but only after their
governments formally requested their release and dispatched senior
officials to Kabul.
   The clemency pleas by the French and Italian governments were
widely publicized by Kabul as a show of official international
recognition.
   The guerrillas, backed by the United States and based in
Pakistan, have been fighting to overthrow the Soviet-supported
government for 11 years.
   The United States and other Western nations closed their
embassies in Kabul in late January and early February, shortly
before Soviet troops withdrew from Afghanistan, ending a nine-year
military intervention.
</TEXT>
