<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-ServiceHistory     07-21 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Service History,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Records Show Minor Problems in Jet's History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government records on the United DC-10 that
crashed in Iowa ``are pretty clean'' with no major problems
reported in recent years, a spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation
Administration said.
   The 15-year-old jumbo jet had no accidents or reports of serious
incidents during the past five years, the amount of time covered in
the agency's current records, according to Bobbie Mardis in the
FAA's Oklahoma City office.
   A separate FAA service difficulty report, covering 1980 to 1989,
showed two occasions when an engine on the jet flamed out, or quit,
during flight. No structural damage was evident in either case, Ms.
Mardis said Thursday.
   Connections cannot be immediately made between those engines and
the ones now on the plane because officials haven't identified the
serial numbers of the engines in Iowa, Ms. Mardis said.
   But she said the engines on the jet most likely are different
from those that experienced flameouts in 1980 and 1984, because
``they are replacing engines all the time.''
   She also said it is not uncommon for jets to experience engine
flameouts, and engines do not have to be replaced because of them.
   ``The report looks pretty clean,'' Ms. Mardis said.
   Officials in Sioux City reported late Thursday that the plane's
tail engine failed and an engine fan-rotor system was lost. The
plane's tail wing also sustained several ``projectile
penetrations,'' including one hole 10-by-12 inches, they said.
   Roland Herwig, a spokesman for the FAA center in Oklahoma City,
said it is ``complete hearsay at this point'' that the plane that
crashed had problems during an earlier flight Wednesday.
   A New Jersey woman said she took the same DC-10 from
Philadelphia to Denver Wednesday morning, and that as the plane
began to leave the terminal at Philadelphia International Airport
shortly after 10 a.m. ``everything sort of shut off.''
   The plane taxied back to the terminal, where it sat about 15
minutes for repairs before taking off, said Ruth Dinsmore of Mount
Laurel, N.J. Flight 232 was making the return trip from Denver.
   Herwig said no official has said there was a problem. ``We don't
even know if it was the same airplane,'' he said.
   United spokeswoman Kim Thomas in Chicago said she could not
confirm that the DC-10 had difficulty earlier in the day and would
not comment on maintenance records because they are ``material'' to
official investigations.
   The FAA's service difficulty records on the jet show problems
United has reported to the FAA. Airlines are required to submit
certain information about failures but sometimes submit more data
than is required so that the information can be used by others in
the aviation industry.
   The last engine flameout reported was in September 1984 when an
engine quit with 5,500 pounds of fuel in a tank and the aft boost
light on. The report said the problem could not be duplicated in
subsequent tests.
   In November 1980, an engine flamed out at 33,500 feet when the
drive shaft failed. The FAA records do not indicate how repairs
were made.
   The records also cite some minor landing gear problems,
including a July 1988 incident in which the crew reported the left
gear red light was on with the gear handle up. Some landing gear
position indicator parts had to be replaced, the report said.
   In January 1987, the flight crew reported it had no indication
that the landing gear was locked down, but the jet landed without
incident. Maintenance crews found the landing gear handle sticking
and lubricated the handle. The system checked out after that, the
FAA report shows.
   In June 1987, a right gear door cable was replaced after the
right main gear showed both a green and red light.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0813EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China     07-21 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says It Won't Tolerate Democracy Campaign in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said today it will not tolerate continued
support by Hong Kong residents for the mainland's crushed democracy
movement and that Hong Kong will be allowed to remain capitalist
only if it stops interfering.
   The warning was made in a strongly worded commentary in the
Communist Party newspaper, the People's Daily, that apparently was
written by a high-level official. It immediately triggered
widespread publicity in the tiny British colony, scheduled to
return to Chinese rule in 1997.
   ``We will not allow people to use Hong Kong as a base for
subverting the central people's government, this has been the
Chinese government's consistent policy,'' it declared.
   The commentary noted that China has promised the enclave can
remain capitalist for at least 50 years, but said: ``Not engaging
in activities to overthrow (the Chinese government) is a
precondition for allowing (Hong Kong) to retain its capitalist
system.''
   It also said any participation by Hong Kong residents in affairs
of the mainland would have to be in keeping with mainland laws.
   Hundreds of thousands of usually apolitical Hong Kong residents
joined in protest marches and petition drives after the June 3-4
army attack on pro-democracy student protesters in Beijing and
other Chinese cities.
   Many said the attack, followed by thousands of arrests, would
accelerate emigration from the colony.
   Chinese leaders have said they want to restore confidence among
Hong Kong residents. They assured prominent Hong Kong residents
invited to Beijing that China had not changed its policy of ``one
country, two systems'' after 1997.
   But the tone of the commentary, with its declaration that true
democracy can only be found under the socialist system, was likely
to have the opposite effect.
   ``This is the time to see how strong our backbone is,''
democracy activisit Szeto Wah, who was criticized in the
commentary, said on Hong Kong radio.
   The commentary singled out Szeto's group, the newly formed Hong
Kong Alliance in Support of the Patriotic Democratic Movement in
China, which has pledged $156,000 to help fugitives from the
mainland movement.
   Without mentioning them by name, the commentary accused Szeto
and the vice chairman of the group, Martin Lee, of supporting
independence for Hong Kong and plotting to overthrow the Communist
government.
   Szeto denied the charge, saying he opposed China's current
leaders but not socialism. He and Lee are members of a joint Hong
Kong-Chinese committee that is drafting a basic law to govern Hong
Kong after 1997.
   ``(The Chinese leaders) know that we have popular support, and
this is their way, their devious way ... of persuading people not
to join us out of fear,'' Lee said on Hong Kong radio.
   Another alliance leader, Lee Wing-tat, said the commentary would
not deter his group from sending funds to Chinese fugitives in
France who have announced plans to form a democratic coalition.
   The People's Daily essay was signed by a pseudonym, Ai Zhong,
that sounds the same as the words ``love China.''
   Several major commentaries have appeared in the People's Daily
in recent days under pen names, apparently the word of top-level
officials.
   Such a practice has not been common since the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, a violent far-leftist campaign that has had eerie
echoes in the current crackdown on dissent.
   Another similarity is in the emphasis on ideology over economic
development, which had been the main concern of the past decade.
   At a meeting of propaganda officials from around the country,
party General Secretary Jiang Zemin called for ``100 percent
emphasis'' on ideological work.
   Other officials called for ``strict adherence to party
propaganda discipline.'' Speeches from the meeting were blazoned on
front pages today.
   Other commentaries emphasized that class struggle has not ended,
and said advocates of Western-style liberalism are class enemies.
   In another development, China's leading dissident, Fang Lizhi,
who is hiding in the U.S. Embassy, has been expelled from his posts
in the Dialectics Research Society, the official Xinhua News Agency
said.
   Fang, an astrophysicist, worked in the Beijing Observatory, but
repeated phone calls to determine if he had been fired as well were
not answered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
