<DOCNO> AP890721-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     07-21 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Opposition Leaders Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two leaders of Burma's major
opposition party are under house arrest for trying to ``revive
anarchy'' and destroy the military, the government announced today.
   The confinements of Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo could last one
year and then be renewed, officials told a news conference. They
also indicated that opposition parties could be disqualified from
participating in elections next year.
   ``They will be held as long as the dangers of disruption of
peace and tranquility by them exist,'' said Col. Aung Thein, when
asked if Ms. Suu Kyi and Tin Oo will be able to run in the
elections.
   The government of Gen. Saw Maung promised the elections not long
after crushing a nationwide pro-democracy movement in September.
   During those protests, Ms. Suu Kyi, the daughter of national
independence hero Aung San, sided with students and others
demanding an end to authoritarian rule. She is now secretary of the
National League for Democracy, and Tin Oo, a retired general, is
the chairman.
   Both have been outspoken in their criticism of the military
government and martial law.
   Aung Thein, a member of the government's Information Committee,
said the government may prohibit the National League for Democracy
or any other group from participating in the general election. ``We
will consider it if the party or parties continue the excesses,''
he said.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann said Ms. Suu Kyi and Tin Oo are
prohibited from having contact with people outside their homes.
Family members of the two may leave their residences ``under
surveillance'' but may not contact foreign embassies, political
parties or people connected with the parties, he said.
   ``Action has to be taken for their repeated attempts to divide
the military and the people and also to cause disunity among the
military,'' Kyaw Sann said. ``Both of them mounted their incitement
in the last two months, finally using confrontational strategy to
destroy the military and revive anarchy in the country.''
   The government did not say when the two were arrested, but
reports from a Western embassy in Rangoon said on Thursday that
troops had surrounded Ms. Suu Kyi's house in a suburb of the
capital, Rangoon. When she tried to surrender to the soldiers, they
forced her back inside her residence, the embassy said.
   Later that day, the State Department said in Washington that the
arrests of opposition activists ``cast serious doubts'' on the
government's intention to hold free elections. It called on Burmese
authorities to release all political prisoners and allow the
opposition to campaign for the election.
   The government has threatened violators of martial law decrees
with death sentences.
   On Wednesday, hundreds of students defied martial law to hold
anti-government demonstrations. Ms. Suu Kyi canceled her planned
rally to avoid clashes with soldiers who filled the streets. State
radio reported 44 arrests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
