<DOCNO> AP890721-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0918EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpyTrial     07-21 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy Trial,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mechanic Faces Sentencing For Conspiring to Sell Secrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Turkish native once employed by the U.S.
Army as a mechanic in West Berlin was could be sentenced to 30
years to life in prison for conspiring to sell secrets to the
Soviet Union and East Germany.
   Huseyin Yildirim, 61, was in jail today after being convicted by
a U.S. District Court jury Thursday of one count of conspiracy to
commit espionage.
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield ordered a pre-sentence
investigation for before he sets the prison term for Yildirim.
   The defendant, a civilian mechanic for the Army, was accused of
working with an American warrant officer to sell information from
the National Security Agency's Field Station Berlin from 1983 to
1988. The plot is said to have caused serious damage to American
intelligence work because the station conducts electronic
eavesdropping on telephone and other communications.
   Yildirim, of Belleair Beach, Fla., was charged with conspiring
with Warrant Officer James William Hall III, who pleaded guilty in
a court-martial and was sentenced to 40 years in prison.
   Defense attorney Lamar Walter said he would file a motion for a
new trial within a week.
   Yildirim also did not testify, and the defense presented no
evidence. In his closing statement, Walter told the jury that Hall
was solely to blame for the espionage.
   The trial was held in Savannah because Hall was stationed at
nearby Fort Stewart at the time of his arrest last December.
</TEXT>
