<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0947EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-21 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Admits Receiving Weapons from Iraq, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper today quoted army commander
Gen. Michel Aoun as saying that Iraq has provided him with weapons,
but he refused to say if Iraq has given him medium-range missiles
as alleged by Syria.
   Aoun, whose mainly Christian troops are engaged in a
long-running battle with Syrian gunners, has publicly thanked Iraq
in the past for its support, but he has never admitted receiving
weapons from Iraq.
   According to police, the casualty toll in the 18-week-old
confrontation stood at 434 dead and 1,784 wounded following
overnight fighting that killed one person and injured four.
   In south Lebanon, meanwhile, the United Nations said a U.N.
peacekeeping soldier was seriously wounded today when unidentified
assailants attacked peacekeeping troops.
   ``Brotherly Iraq supports Lebanon ... I wanted to purchase
weapons and ammunition, and Iraq donated them,'' the daily paper
An-Nahar quoted Aoun as saying in an interview.
   The Maronite general said Iraq has given his army
Soviet-designed T-55 tanks and ``other types of weapons.''
   He would not say if Iraq has provided him with medium-range,
frog-7 surface-to-surface missiles, which would be able to hit the
Syrian capital, Damascus.
   Syria claims Aoun possesses these missiles and has demanded they
be removed from the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, which is
under the control of Aoun's troops and the right-wing Christian
Lebanese Forces militia.
   ``The missiles issue is not the problem. The problem is the
Syrian presence in Lebanon,'' Aoun was quoted as saying.
   Aoun denied charges by Syria's government-run radio that Iraq
sent military personnel to help his troops.
   ``Every time, they claim that there are Iraqi soldiers or
experts in Lebanon. Where are thay? Iraq does not put strings on
our political, military and economic decision-making,'' Aoun said.
   Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, has 40,000 troops deployed in the
war-shattered nation. It supports Aoun's ``war of liberation'' to
drive out the Syrians.
   Syrian troops first entered Lebanon in 1976 as part of an Arab
League peacekeeping force. The Syrians initially sought to curb
violence among Moslem factions but later sided with Moslems against
the Christians.
   The current round of violence broke out March 8, two days after
Aoun blockaded illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of
Beirut to salvage about $100 million in customs dues lost annually.
   Police said intermittent overnight duels covered the mountainous
range southeast of the capital and the Christian-controlled
coastline to the north.
   In southern Lebanon, Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N.
peacekeeping forces, said a ``large group of armed elements'' fired
three rocket-propelled grenades at a checkpoint manned by Fijian
peacekeeping soldiers in the village of Siddiqine. He said the
attack developed into a 20-minute clash and that a Fijian soldier
lost his eye.
   The mainstream Shiite moslem Amal militia, which is the dominant
force in south Lebanon, is investigating to determine who attacked,
Goksel said.
   The 5,800-strong U.N. force, drawn fromn nine nations, has been
deployed in south Lebanon since Israel's 1978 invasion.
   France, Norway, Sweden, Italy, Ghana, Fiji, Ireland, Nepal and
Finland all have troops in the force.
</TEXT>
