<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia 2ndLd-Writethru a0486 07-21 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0486,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugee Camp Shelled; One Dead, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with relief officials saying appears
pro-Vietnamese forces shelled camp. Pickup 6th, `The camp...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cambodian refugee camp run by
communist Khmer Rouge guerrillas came under heavy shelling today
that killed one refugee and wounded 10, Western relief officials
said.
   One official said 27 shells crashed into the Site 8 camp in
Thailand near the Cambodian border. The three hours of shelling
followed overnight fighting in the area, said a Thai security
official.
   The U.N. Border Relief Operation declared the camp off limits to
relief personnel for safety reasons.
   Site 8 houses 40,000 refugees and is the main civilian camp
operated by the Khmer Rouge, the largest guerrilla group fighting
Vietnamese occupation forces and allied Cambodian government troops.
   Western relief officials said it appeared that Vietnamese-backed
government forces staged the attack.
   In the past, the Khmer Rouge has shelled its own camps in
macabre attempts to exercise strict control over the refugees or to
reduce their population. Widespread human rights violations have
been reported in the camps.
   The camp of thatched houses is in Thailand's eastern province of
Prachinburi and about a mile from the Cambodian border.
   Fighting between pro-Vietnamese forces and the Khmer Rouge has
increased along the border in recent days, as often is the case
before diplomatic events and peace talks.
   The Khmer Rouge and the other guerrilla groups are to hold talks
with the Vietnamese-installed government in Paris next week, then
attend an international conference on Cambodia starting July 30.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in 1978 and toppled the brutal Khmer
Rouge regime. The Khmer Rouge were in power from 1975-1978.
Hundreds of thousands of Cambodia's 8 million people died from
Khmer Rouge executions, famine and civil unrest.
</TEXT>
