<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Dies in Flood; Three Seen in Floating Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRENTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers with dogs scoured the
flood-washed banks of a northern Virginia creek today for a car
with up to three people seen floating away in high water that
claimed the life of a pregnant woman.
   Water in Goose Creek rose 13 feet in half an hour during heavy
rain Thursday, washing about 10 cars off a bridge on U.S. 17.
   Three people were rescued from the creek and eight others
managed to escape on their own, said Lt. Donald Flohr of the
Fauquier County Sheriff's Department.
   Tammy Woolf Conneway of Bloommerry, W.Va., died in the flood,
Flohr said.
   Several witnesses reported seeing a car with up to three people
in it floating away.
   On Thursday, more than 100 military personnel and rescuers,
including divers, searched for the car.
   More rain forced searchers to quit at 5 p.m. Thursday, but the
resumed the effort today.
   ``A trucker along Route 17 and two people stranded on the roof
of their car saw a small red car float past them with as many as
three people in it,'' Flohr said.
   Ms. Conneway, alone in a pickup truck, was on her way home from
a job with the state Department of Corrections in Fairfax County,
when the truck was washed off the bridge, Flohr said. He said she
was four months pregnant.
   The creek, which normally runs about 10 feet below the bridge,
rose an estimated 13 feet in 30 minutes, said Thompson, director of
county emergency services. The flood waters later receded, he said.
