<FIRST>r i PM-Thailand-Pirates     07-21 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thailand-Pirates,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Pirates Who Killed 56 Vietnamese Boat People Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested three Thai fishermen
who confessed they killed 56 Vietnamese boat people by attacking
them with knives, sticks and axes and throwing them into the sea,
an officer said today.
   The men were arrested Tuesday after they were identified by the
only two survivors of the March 26 attack, said Lt. Col. Prakob
Benjapong of Marine Police in the southern fishing port of Songkhla.
   Boat captain Boonrub Ruangdit, 27, and Vichoke Wongkan, 29, and
Amnuay Saenghiran, 19, then made confessions, said Prakob.
   According to Prakob, the fishermen said they robbed the
Vietnamese then transferred 10 women to their boat.
   They called the Vietnamese men onto the deck one by one, struck
them in the head and legs and threw them overboard, Prakob said.
They later killed the women in a similar fashion.
   Prakob said the fishermen towed the Vietnamese boat from the
area and sailed around for an hour to make sure all the victims
died.
   The survivors, Pham Hgoc Van, 33, and Do Hoa, 14, reached a
refugee camp in Malaysia.
   Police are seeking about six other fishermen believed involved
in the attack, said Prakob.
   Attacks on Vietnamese boat people, who sometimes flee with gold
and other valuables, have become increasingly violent in the past
year and have left scores if not hundreds dead this year.
   Last month, police said four other Thai fishermen were arrested
and confessed to killing 130 Vietnamese refugees on April 16 off
the Malaysian coast.
   The threat of pirates, prison-like refugee camps, and days at
sea without food and water have not discouraged the exodus of
Vietnamese. More than 1.5 million have left their homeland since
the communist takeover in April 1975.
   Nations such as Hong Kong that are overwhelmed by the exodus say
most of the refugees now are fleeing economic hardship, not
political persecution.
</TEXT>
