<FIRST>r i PM-Cyprus-Protest     07-21 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyprus-Protest,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Sector Police Accused Of Abusing Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch reporter detained with more than
100 Greek Cypriot women protesting the 15-year Turkish occupation
of northern Cyprus said today that riot police beat demonstrators
and poked them with electric prods.
   ``It was such a madhouse there with the horrible Turkish army
hordes charging at us with their batons and rifles,'' said Hetty
Lubberding, a correspondent for Dutch radio. ``Their behavior ...
was brutal.''
   She also said organizers of the protest by hundreds of women
were partly responsible for provoking the Turkish response
Wednesday night. She said the organizers chose a highly sensitive
area to enter the buffer zone between the war-divided sections of
the capital and that they displayed the Greek flag.
   In Ankara today, the Turkish government said the U.N.
peacekeeping force watching the zone did not do enough to prevent
protesters from knocking down barbed wire barricades and occupying
a destroyed school and church in the zone.
   ``We have difficulty understanding the failure of the
peacekeeping force to take the necessary measures and the
unprecedented tolerance shown to the violation of the buffer
zone,'' a Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said.
   Ms. Lubberding said police used electric prods on demonstrators,
beat and slapped them and pulled their hair.
   Turkish Cypriot police arrested 111 people in the protest. Three
foreign reporters, including Ms. Lubberding and an American, were
released Thursday.
   The remaining 108 people arrested, including 10 men, remained on
the Turkish side today where they were being processed through the
courts.
   Akis Fantis, spokesman for the Greek Cypriot government, said
President George Vassiliou intensified his efforts today through
diplomatic contacts for their release.
   Turkish Cypriots in 1983 declared the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus in the northern third of the island, which only
Turkey recognizes.
   The women's march was part of a series of demonstrations marking
the 15th anniversary of the Turkish invasion five days after a coup
by supporters of uniting the island with Greece. About 30,000
Turkish troops guard the area.
   The American reporter released Thursday was Katherine McElroy, a
correspondent for the Reuters news agency, who holds both Cypriot
and U.S. passports. She was not immediately availabe for comment.
</TEXT>
