<FIRST>r a PM-WanderingPlane     07-21 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mystery Pilot to Remain Hospitalized For Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of pilot Thomas Root hopes
extensive medical and psychological tests will help solve the
mystery of his 800-mile odyssey, which may be linked to a prior
blackout, Root's brother said.
   ``We would like a full medical evaluation,'' Todd Root said
Thursday. ``We want to make sure there's not more to this than just
an accident. Our family is interested in only one thing: getting to
the bottom of what may have caused this and getting my brother the
proper treatment.''
   Thomas Root, a 36-year-old communications lawyer in Washington,
D.C., blacked out in his office in March, but doctors could not
find an explanation after three days of tests, his brother said.
   ``Maybe there is some link from that incident to this one,'' he
said.
   Thomas Root has said he blacked out two hours after taking off
from Washington National Airport en route to Rocky Mount, N.C.,
July 13.
   His flight continued on autopilot, while military rescue planes
followed, until he ditched in Bahamian waters. It was then
discovered that he had been shot in the abdomen with a .32-caliber
pistol. He claims it discharged by itself from the plane's glove
box.
   ``I want to believe it's an accident,'' Todd Root told
reporters. ``Yet I know the circumstances surrounding this are so
mysterious that it's hard for the general public and anyone not to
believe there might be more to it.''
   Todd Root said his brother was running a fever and was advised
by doctors and relatives not to meet with reporters.
   Hospital spokeswoman Linda Hamlin refused to comment on
scheduled tests for Root.
   ``Tom Root's brother made statements about the test,'' said Ms.
Hamlin. ``He is an intelligent man and seemed to know what he is
talking about.''
   In Miami, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen
confirmed that Lehtinen requested reports on the FBI interrogation
of Root.
   A source close to the investigation said it probably would
examine whether Root filed false information about his flight or is
liable for search and rescue expenses.
</TEXT>
