<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     07-21 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Newspaper Employees Resign Over Publisher's Firing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen employees of a China-funded newspaper
in Hong Kong announced their resignations today to protest the
firing of a publisher who criticized the Chinese crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters.
   The resignations came the same day China said it will not
tolerate support by Hong Kong residents for the mainland's
democracy movement and that Hong Kong will be allowed to remain
capitalist only if it stops interfering.
   China is scheduled to take control of the British colony in 1997
but has pledged to let it remain capitalist for at least 50 years.
   The publisher of the Wen Wei Po newspaper, Lee Tze-chung, was
fired Saturday by the Chinese Communist government, which pays for
the paper. The government acted through its official Xinhua News
Agency.
   The newspaper had long supported China but joined other Hong
Kong publications in denouncing the June 3-4 military crackdown in
Beijing.
   ``Today, I can't be an accomplice to the murderers anymore,''
Lee said in a television interview after the crackdown.
   In a statement sent by facsimile to The Associated Press, 18
reporters and other employees of the newspaper announced their
resignation, saying they could not accept the dismissal of Lee.
   They said that ``under all sorts of pressure, the correct
position (taken by Lee) no longer can be maintained. We deeply
regret this.''
   Earlier in the week, a senior manager at the paper, who is among
those who resigned, told reporters from other news organizations it
was ``pointless to stay because we cannot do anything.''
   The manager, who spoke on condition of anonymity, claimed
reporters who sympathized with Lee were being verbally harassed and
that management was trying to ``brainwash'' the staff to back Lee's
firing.
   Wen Wei Po ``will be another People's Daily,'' the source said,
referring to the Chinese Communist Party's official newspaper
published in Beijing.
   Today's warning about Hong Kong's backing of Chinese protesters
came in a strongly worded commentary in the People's Daily. The
commentary was apparently written by a high-level government
official.
   While noting China's promise to let Hong Kong remain capitalist
for at least 50 years, the commentary said: ``Not engaging in
activities to overthrow (the Chinese government) is a precondition
for allowing (Hong Kong) to retain its capitalist system.''
   It was not immediately clear how the resignations would affect
the Hong Kong newspaper, which had about 300 employees. A woman
answering a telephone call to the paper today said there was nobody
available to comment.
</TEXT>
