<FIRST>u i PM-Asia-Alar 1stLd-Writethru a0530 07-21 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Asia-Alar, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Will Reportedly Test U.S. Beef for Alar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7 grafs for 5-8 pvs `A ministry...U.S. market.' to ADD
U.S. study finding Alar in meat. Pickup 9th graf pvs, `Alar is...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government plans to test beef from
the United States and other countries for Alar and other suspected
cancer-causing substances, a news report said today.
   Meanwhile, consumers remained wary of U.S. grapefruit after an
Alar scare based on a false interpretation of a chemical test.
   In Taiwan, consumers were shunning U.S. cherries, even though
health officials say the fears of Alar in that fruit are unfounded,
importers said.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said this country's
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry will oversee meat
testing and return beef imports if the tests ``turn up the smallest
traces'' of daminozide, known commercially as Alar, or other
chemicals.
   South Korea imports beef from the United States, Canada,
Australia and New Zealand.
   A ministry spokesman said he could not confirm the news report,
but he said the matter was under study. The spokesman said
officials were concerned about a U.S. report published May 24 that
found Alar residues in meat.
   The study, by Alar's manufacturer Uniroyal Chemical Co., found
.20 parts per million of Alar in unspecified meat. The
Environmental Protection Agency said, however, it found no reason
to restrict the use of Alar in any food except apples, where it
found Alar levels of 1.0 parts per million.
   EPA's mention of the study in the Federal Register did not
explicitly say where the Alar in meat came from. However, it
suggested the chemical came from animals feeding on fruit or other
products treated with Alar.
   Alar leaped into the international picture in February when a
U.S. consumer group, the Natural Resources Defense Council, said in
a report that eating apples treated with Alar increased cancer risk
in children.
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the Food and Drug
Administration disputed the group's report as a major exaggeration
of the risk, but apple sales fell immediately.
   Despite its criticism of the report, the EPA plans to ban the
use of Alar next spring. The manufacturer has withdrawn Alar from
the U.S. market.
   Alar is used to make apples redder and enhance their shelf life.
   Korean consumers began boycotting U.S. grapefruit last month
after a government laboratory appeared to have detected traces of
Alar in Florida grapefruit. The report later proved to be mistaken,
but consumers remained skeptical and a campaign to ban Alar and
other chemicals from food products has grown. South Korea about a
dozen consumer groups claiming 2 million members.
   In Washington on Thursday, lawmakers from grapefruit-growing
states blamed the chemical scare on the Seoul government and said
unfair trade charges should be filed against South Korea for using
``scare tactics for protectionism.''
   Washington has pushed Seoul to open its markets to more U.S.
farm products. South Korean farmers have protested, claiming the
imports undercut domestic prices. However, consumer groups in South
Korea say their worries center on harmful chemicals, not trade
issues.
   U.S. Rep. Tom Lewis, R-Fla., said the boycott has left 60,000
boxes of American citrus rotting in South Korea. A spokesman for
the citrus industry in Seoul said he was unaware of any losses, but
he conceded that if the fruit is left in cold storage will not last
long.
   In Taipei, Taiwan, the government's Health Department announced
Thursday that cherries were safe to eat after laboratory tests
showed the imported U.S. fruit carried no residue of Alar.
   The tests were conducted following reports from South Korea that
Alar was found in cherries imported from the United States.
   One importer, Hsieh Chien-chih, said people were still shying
away from the cherries. ``People are confused by the contradictory
reports, and they feel it is safer to eat Taiwan watermelons or
guavas instead,'' the importer said.
   ``People say they can be killed after eating the fruit. The
market is over for cherries this year,'' the importer said.
   Taipei Fruit Trade Association officials said cherry sales had
dropped more than 60 percent since the South Korean test results
were published this month.
   In Yakima, Wash., Brent Heinemann of the Washington state
Department of Agriculture said two 1,700-box containers of
Washington cherries were sitting at the port of Inchon, west of
Seoul, unable to clear customs.
   Trade industry officials in Seoul confirmed a cherry shipment
was stalled at customs but said it was held up over a claim of
improper handling by the shipper.
</TEXT>
