<HEAD>Abortion to Be Focus of NOW Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Opening news conference not until midafternoon EDT; should stand
for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN WALZER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A battle plan for a national abortion-rights
campaign is expected to emerge from the National Organization for
Women's national convention, scheduled to begin today.
   This is the first meeting of NOW since the U.S. Supreme Court's
July 3 ruling in Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services Inc.,
which allows states to enact certain restrictions on abortions. The
convention is expected to draw about 1,500 people through Sunday at
the Cincinnati Convention Center.
   NOW officials said the campaign will work on both the national
and state levels.
   ``We feel very strongly that we have to have a national focus,''
said Patricia Ireland, NOW executive vice president. ``We don't
think states' rights have ever been good for individual women.''
   In the new ruling, the Supreme Court allowed states a greater
role in regulating abortion than had been allowed under its
landmark 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision, which established a woman's
right to choose abortion.
   On the state level, NOW plans to help launch ballot initiatives
for abortion rights, Ms. Ireland said.
   NOW hopes to begin a ``Freedom Caravan for Women's Lives'' by
the end of August, said NOW spokeswoman Julie Nobel. The caravan
would travel from state to state, taking NOW members to train local
teams to carry out initiative or legislative campaigns.
   NOW planned to hold an abortion rights march in downtown
Cincinnati on Saturday afternoon. The group will travel from the
convention center to the Hamilton County Courthouse.
   Anti-abortion activists have announced plans to hold a
counterdemonstration across the street, despite being denied a
parade permit. Other topics of discussion at the NOW convention
include lesbian rights, sexual harassment, feminism and the
homeless.
</TEXT>
