<DOCNO> AP890721-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     07-21 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Dissatisfied With Response on Police Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said today that South African officials have rejected his
request for the dismissal of more than 2,000 Namibian police
associated with a notorious paramilitary unit.
   However, the U.N. chief predicted that Namibia will hold
elections as scheduled Nov. 6 to establish an independent
government and end 74 years of South African rule.
   Perez de Cuellar said the main threat to free and fair elections
concerned charges of intimidation by Namibian police who belonged
to the disbanded paramilitary unit known as Koevoet, the
Afrikaans-language word for ``crowbar.''
   ``I want to totally remove the shadow of Koevoet,'' he told a
news conference at the end of his three-day visit to Namibia.
   Perez de Cuellar said former members of Koevoet, known for its
often brutal tactics in the territory's 23-year bush war, had
created ``an atmosphere of mistrust'' in northern Namibia, where
most of the fighting took place.
   He said Namibia's South African administrator, Louis Pienaar,
rejected his request to dismiss all former Koevoet members from the
police force, which is responsible for law and order during the
transition to independence.
   Pienaar met with Perez de Cuellar on Wednesday and announced
that former Koevoet members would be moved away from north-central
Namibia into less tense regions. He said he will dismiss policemen
only if it can be proved they engaged in misconduct.
   ``I'm sorry to say I'm not totally satisfied,'' the U.N. chief
said. ``Elimination (of Koevoet) would create a better situation.''
   He indicated he would discuss the matter further with South
Africa's foreign affairs minister, Pik Botha.
   Koevoet was officially disbanded this year, but more than 2,000
of its members were integrated into the regular police force.
Koevoet's founder and former leader, Gen. Hans Dreyer, is the
police commander in northern Namibia.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, which waged the war
against South African rule and is favored in the November
elections, alleges that former Koevoet members continue to harass
its supporters.
   During Namibia's war, Koevoet members traditionally went on
weeklong patrols through isolated villages and bush territory in
armored vehicles mounted with machine guns. They were accused of
dozens of atrocities against both civilians and guerrillas.
</TEXT>
