<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0460 07-21 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with Justice Department to
file affidavit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department will file an
affidavit which could kill at least one criminal charge against a
former CIA station chief in the Iran-Contra case and might even
scuttle the trial, a prosecutor said today.
   Associate independent counsel Laurence Shtasel told a court
hearing the affidavit will bar the use of classified information
concerning various CIA programs in the trial of Joseph Fernandez on
four criminal charges.
   Fernandez, the former CIA station chief in Costa Rica, is
scheduled to go on trial Monday on two counts of obstruction and
two counts of making false statements.
   The Justice Department notified the independent counsel's office
Thursday night that it would file an affidavit addressing
classified information that Fernandez ``would be prohibited from
using,'' Shtasel told U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton.
   Shtasel said the classified information at issue concerns CIA
programs and may also include data about various CIA stations.
   Shtasel, who will prosecute the case against Fernandez, said if
the affidavit is limited to information concerning CIA programs,
the case could be saved by dropping one of the false statement
counts.
   If the affidavit is more broadly worded, however, it ``would
have more drastic consequences,'' Shtasel said. A broadly worded
affidavit ``leaves greater doubt'' whether the case against
Fernandez can go to trial, he said.
   Officials from various federal agencies were meeting late today
to discuss the scope of the affidavit, expected to be filed Monday,
Shtasel said.
   The Justice Department's action will mark the first time the
government has taken the step of filing an affidavit to bar the use
of classified information in a criminal case. Under federal law,
once the judge receives such an affidavit, he has no choice but to
prohibit the use of the classified information in a trial. If that
information is critical to a defendant's case, the judge must
dismiss the case.
   By now, ``everybody should have a clear idea of what information
they want released,'' said the judge, who was clearly unhappy with
the last-minute intervention by the U.S. intelligence community.
   Shtasel suggested that Fernandez' Iran-Contra trial be delayed
but the judge said he will not reschedule the case again. He
already has granted one two-week delay in the case.
   Fernandez' attorney, Thomas Wilson, said the filing of a Justice
Department affidavit leaves the court little choice but to drop the
charges.
   ``This defendant is on a rack,'' Wilson said. The lawyer
suggested that the case be thrown out, but Hilton denied that
request.
   ``There are various options that are being debated,'' Justice
Department spokesman David Runkel said Thursday when asked about
the Fernandez case.
   Asked if the options include a move by the department that would
scrap the case, Runkel said, ``That's not a decision that we would
ever make.''
   Mary Belcher, a spokeswoman for independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh's office, said only, ``There are very serious matters being
discussed with respect to the Fernandez case and the discussions
are ongoing.''
   Fernandez is charged with two counts of obstruction and two
counts of making false statements to Iran-Contra investigators from
the CIA and the Tower Commission in 1987.
   The indictment says he falsely told the CIA inspector general's
office a secret airstrip construction project that was to be part
of the Contra supply network was initiated by the Costa Rican
government.
   In congressional testimony that cannot be used against him at
his trial, Fernandez admitted that former National Security Council
aide Oliver North and others in the U.S. government initiated the
project.
   Fernandez falsely told the Tower Commission he did not know for
a fact that North was assisting the Contra resupply operation,
according to the indictment.
   Fernandez is accused in a bill of particulars filed by
prosecutors of making 19 additional statements that were so
misleading they obstructed the Tower Commission and CIA inspector
general office's inquiries into the Iran-Contra scandal.
</TEXT>
