<SECOND>PM-Kraft Contest,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Of Four Van Winners In Kraft's Alternate Drawing Opt for Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of four people who won vans in a drawing
held by Kraft USA as an alternative to a botched contest have opted
to take $17,000 each in cash instead of vehicles, the company says.
   Only a 35-year-old mother of two from suburban Norridge decided
to take a van in the rerun of the Kraft Singles cheese contest that
last month mistakenly produced thousands of winners instead of only
one, the Glenview-based company said.
   ``It's good timing,'' Mary Braun, the only winner who opted for
a Dodge van, said Thursday. ``My car just broke down the Sunday
before the drawing. My car's almost nine years old and we were
looking at vans anyway.''
   Kraft's ``Ready to Roll'' contest, offered through Chicago and
Houston area newspapers on June 11, was canceled the next day when
the company learned a printing error had produced nearly 10,000
winners of vans.
   To compensate for the foul-up, Kraft sent $250 to would-be van
winners who mailed in the faulty winning game pieces by June 16,
and the company said it would give away four vans in a drawing from
a pool of vehicle winners in the first game. The company also gave
cash awards to winners of lesser prizes such as bicycles and
skateboards.
   Kraft still faces a class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of
thousands of would-be winners.
   In the drawing held Friday, Kraft gave away 400 bicyles, 2,000
skateboards and 32,000 coupons for free packages of Kraft Singles,
in addition to the vans. Each category contained four times as many
prizes as originally planned.
</TEXT>
