<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     07-21 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Gets Permission To Start Interim Repairs To Valdez</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interim repairs to the disabled Exxon Valdez
will begin offshore as soon as ocean conditions allow divers to
assess the task of removing damaged hull plates under water,
officials said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. received permission Thursday to begin
removing the plates from the ship that struck a reef in Alaska's
Prince William Sound March 24, dumping 11 million gallons of crude
oil in the nations worst spill.
   It was towed to San Diego for repairs this month at the shipyard
where it was built, but can't navigate the shallow San Diego Harbor
channel until the hanging plates are cut off.
   The Coast Guard granted permission to begin repairs after repair
crews conducted a pollution containment drill at sea, said a
spokeswoman, Petty Officer Elizabeth Neely.
   ``As far as we're concerned, it was a satisfactory drill and the
Coast Guard has no objections to letting Exxon begin plate removal
operations,'' Neely said.
   At least six plates that peeled away from the ship's hull during
its 2,500-mile journey from Alaska must be removed so the vessel
can navigate the shallow San Diego Harbor channel without scraping
the bottom.
   Ocean swells of three feet to four feet so far have kept divers
from starting the work. They will begin cutting off the plates when
the swells subside, said Exxon spokeswoman Jan Cool.
   The work, described as dangerous because it is being conducted
in open waters, is expected to take about a week. A barge carrying
a crane and a salvage vessel will help retrieve the multiton steel
plates after they are removed.
   Exxon plans to use a 110-foot-deep, sheltered anchorage just off
Navy-owned San Clemente Island to do some of the work once company
officials receive state permission to move the Valdez into
California waters.
   The ship is in a holding pattern about 10 miles northeast of San
Clemente Island and 50 miles off San Diego.
   State officials demand that Exxon meet stringent environmental
conditions before they will allow the ship to enter California
waters, which extend three miles from shore.
   The two sides are getting closer to an agreement but none has
been reached yet, Cool said.
   Meanwhile, a Coast Guard observer aboard the Valdez reported no
signs of oil leakage or other discharges for a fourth straight day,
Neely said. The ship was described as completely cleaned out before
it left Alaska, but it unexpectedly leaked a small amount of oil as
it approached the San Diego area.
</TEXT>
