<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     07-21 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audit Alleges Falsified Records For City Deposits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city treasurer put $2 million in
taxpayers' money in a bank that employed Mayor Tom Bradley as an
adviser without seeking competitive bids for the deposit, an audit
found.
   City Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg then tried to cover up the
transaction by creating documents showing other banks competing for
the deposits put in Far East National Bank, according to the audit
report released Thursday.
   The audit is the latest in a series of blows to Bradley, who
recently was elected to his fifth term in office despite criticism
of his financial dealings.
   A secretary in Rittenberg's city office said he wasn't in early
Friday to comment. His home telephone number isn't listed in the
Los Angeles directory.
   Bradley refused to comment, but sent a letter to City Attorney
James K. Hahn and personnel chief John J. Driscoll requesting an
investigation to determine if any city ordinances were broken.
   Rittenberg told the City Council the deposit had been subject to
competitive bids, the audit said. City law requires such bids on
many transactions to avoid preferential treatment of businesses and
to ensure taxpayers get the best deal.
   The deposits in Far East were made a day after Bradley asked
Rittenberg about the city's relationship with the bank, the audit
showed.
   The treasurer's office also violated the bidding procedure in
depositing hundreds of millions of dollars in several other banks,
according to the audit. More than $200,000 in deposits went to
Gibraltar Savings and Loan after Bradley invested $100,000 of his
own money through the ailing thrift in bonds unavailable to the
public, the audit said.
   City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, who chairs the council's
Finance and Review Committee, and Council President John Ferraro
called for immediate hearings for Rittenberg and his senior aides.
   Comrie said copies of the audit were given to the police
department and city attorney's office, both of which are
investigating the mayor's financial dealings.
</TEXT>
