<FIRST>u a PM-InterstateDrugs 1stLd-Writethru a0485 07-21 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interstate Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Coast Troopers Stage Drug Sweep, Issue Mostly Traffic Tickets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with few drug arrests reported; other detail.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMILY BENTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troopers in 15 East Coast states issued hundreds
of traffic citations and seized stolen car parts but made few drug
arrests in a crackdown along Interstate 95, one of the nation's
busiest drug trafficking corridors.
   In the 24-hour sweep that ended at 8 a.m. today, a Jacksonville,
Fla., man was jailed on drug trafficking charges and Virginia state
troopers seized 140 pounds of marijuana from one traveler.
   Arrest totals were still being compiled, said Chuck Peltier, a
spokesman for the Washington, D.C.-based International Association
of Chiefs of Police.
   The effort was called Operation CoFlaMe, representing
cooperation among agencies from Florida to Maine.
   In Georgia, officers arrested five people and recovered a
truckload of luxury car parts at a rural weigh station. Georgia
State Patrol spokesman J.D. Coleman said the truck apparently was
hauling the items up the East Coast from a Florida ``chop shop''
where stolen cars are dismantled.
   South Carolina highway patrolmen reported more than 300 traffic
citations on their 200-mile stretch of I-95, said spokesman Brian
Ellison.
   ``The message is: You better be toeing the line. If you are
carrying drugs, we do stop people in South Carolina for traffic
violations and vehicle violations and we will check your car,''
Ellison said.
   Coleman said during the first 10 hours of the operation, Georgia
patrolmen stopped 5,408 cars and issued 266 citations, including
174 speeding tickets and three drunken driving arrests.
   In Florida, Darien Cedric Wright, 23, of Jacksonville, Fla., was
being held without bail today after being arrested about eight
miles north of Cocoa Beach. Troopers said they found two kilograms
of cocaine and 263 grams of crack cocaine in his car.
   Florida Highway Patrol Trooper Chris Roper said he stopped
Wright for failing to drive within a single lane on the interstate.
Wright consented to have the car searched and a dog sniffed
cocaine, police said.
   ``We're concentrating on highway safety violations, but anytime
you're out there in such a mass effort _ we're hoping the criminals
using the highways are aware we're out there,'' said Florida
Highway Patrol Lt. Randy Brown in Jacksonville. ``Maybe this will
have an adverse affect on criminals using our highways.''
   In Massachusetts, about 10 people were arrested on drug charges
Thursday, State Trooper Francis Poiterast said.
   In Rhode Island, three people were arrested on charges of
possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, one just on
possession and one trucker on a charge of possession of a sawed-off
shotgun, said Lt. Norman Pineau.
   Pineau said 1,148 people were stopped and 213 were issued
traffic citations, including 43 for speeding.
   At least 70 traffic citations were issued in Pennsylvania on
Thursday. There were no drug arrests or seizures of contraband or
weapons, said Pennsylvania trooper Roger Hoffman.
   Truckers who had been stopped in several states were complaining
by the time they reached Pennsylvania, Hoffman said.
   ``We had one trucker stopped, and he was already stopped in
North Carolina and Virginia before we stopped him,'' Hoffman said.
``He said, `Please, how many times I got to get stopped today?'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
