<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Worth     07-21 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Worth,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comedian Harry Worth Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKHAMSTED, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Harry Worth, who had his
own popular BBC-TV series in the 1960s and made a comeback on BBC
radio last year, has died at the age of 71.
   Worth, who died Thursday, suffered from cancer.
   He often complained humorously that he had difficulty getting
people to take him seriously in real life because of the bumbling
comedy character he played.
   Born near the coal mining town of Barnsley in northern England,
he was the youngest of 11 children. His father, a miner, was killed
in a mine accident when he was 5 months old. The comedy star
himself began work in the mines at age 14, but decided it was not
for him.
   He broke into show business as a ventriloquist but soon got rid
of the dummy to switch to a one-man comedy routine.
   He made 104 situation comedy TV shows, starting with a series
called ``Here's Harry.''
   But his gentle, self-mocking humor was later overtaken by a
switch in public taste for the wilder comedy of such shows as
``Monty Python's Flying Circus.''
   ``His comedy was so gentle, it was like an oasis in a desert of
aggressive, rude and outrageous comedy,'' said comedian Roy Hudd.
``I think Harry's success was due to his style of underplaying
everything. He never used jokes as such. He was just a very funny
man.''
   Worth is survived by his wife, Kay.
</TEXT>
