<DOCNO> AP890721-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TeacherSalaries     07-21 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Salaries,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Salaries Up, But Buying Power About the Same</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers' salaries have been on the rise since
the early 1980s but their purchasing power is only slightly higher
than in 1972, the American Federation of Teachers said Friday.
   The average 1988-89 salary of $29,629 _ an all-time high _ is
$737 higher than the average 1972 salary when adjusted for
inflation, the union said in releasing its annual earnings survey.
   Salaries have risen considerably in the 1980s, including 5.5
percent since last year. But ``trying to recover the salary high
water mark is as motivating as trying to get ahead on a
treadmill,'' AFT President Albert Shanker said in a statement.
   He calculated that all raises teachers have received since 1972
average out to $41 a year.
   ``That's obviously not enough to pay a mortgage or provide for
one's family, and it's certainly not enough of an incentive to
enter teaching,'' Shanker said.
   The union's 50-state survey is based on information from state
education departments. It said the 1972 average teacher salary was
$9,702 _ amounting to $28,892 in 1988 dollars or only slightly less
than current earnings.
   Salaries across the country range from Alaska at $41,832 to
South Dakota at the bottom with $20,525, the AFT said.
   Fourteen states reported starting salaries exceeding $20,000 and
four _ Idaho, North Dakota, South Dakota and West Virginia _ had
starting salaries below $16,000. Five states _ Alaska, California,
Connecticut, Hawaii and New York _ reported first-year wages of
more than $22,000.
   The rival National Education Association reported similar
findings in a teacher salary study released in March. The AFT
conclusions also were consistent with the Education Department's
latest ``wall chart,'' a state-by-state comparison of education
indicators issued in May.
</TEXT>
