<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FilmPreservation     07-21 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Film Preservation,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Delays Greatest Films Announcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will be at least two months before movie
fans learn which 25 films a panel of government-appointed critics
and the Library of Congress considers the nation's best.
   The 13 motion picture experts appointed under the National Film
Preservation Act had planned to announce 25 nominated titles on
Wednesday.
   Instead, worried that public nominations might prompt studios
into premature marketing ploys and reveal panelists' personal
biases, the panelists decided to send their individual choices in
secret to Librarian James Billington.
   Billington, with input from the motion picture division of the
Library of Congress, then will make the final selection in late
September, said George Kirgo, president of the Writers Guild of
America and a member of the preservation panel.
   An attorney for the Library of Congress and several panelists
said the meeting was conducted secretly to dispel public confusion
about the panel's work.
   ``When an evaluative meeting like this one is held, it is always
closed, because that's the ethical way to conduct it,'' said Robert
Rosen, a film archivist with the University of California, Los
Angeles, and a member of the preservation panel.
   Roger Mayer, president of Turner Entertainment Co., attended the
public portions of the panel's meeting at UCLA because the
selections carry so much potential commercial value for his company.
   ``We have a library of more than 3,500 pictures, so we're
interested in what pictures are chosen,'' said Mayer. The Turner
film library includes ``Wizard of Oz,'' ``Gone With the Wind,''
``Citizen Kane,'' ``Casablanca'' and ``Singin' in the Rain.''
   The preservation act, signed into law last year, was drafted by
Congress partly in response to complaints about the practice of
adding color to old black-and-white films. Turner Entertainment has
colored a number of its films.
   The act calls for a panel to recommend 25 titles annually,
chosen according to their cultural, historical and aesthetic
interest, to be placed by the Library of Congress on a national
film register.
   The act does not forbid a movie's copyright holder from editing
movies, or from using computers to add color. But it does require
that such movies must be labeled as colored or altered ``without
the participation of the principal director, screenwriter, and
other creators of the original film.''
   Winston Tabb, the acting deputy Librarian of Congress, said the
Library of Congress was concerned that the movie studios would use
the nominations for commercial profit.
   In preliminary polling, 57 movies were nominated by at least two
members of the preservation board.
   The leader was ``The Grapes of Wrath'' with eight votes.
``Casablanca'' and ``It's a Wonderful Life'' drew seven votes each.
``The Best Years of Our Lives,'' ``Citizen Kane'' and ``On the
Waterfront'' each received six votes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
