<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     07-21 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Further Indicate Guilty Verdict in Palme Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in the Olof Palme murder trial
indicated Friday the defendant would be convicted for the 1986
slaying of the Swedish prime minister.
   The court said Thursday it had finished its deliberations and
will announced its conclusions a week later. It ordered Christer
Pettersson to remain in custody, indicating a guilty verdict was
likely.
   Had Pettersson been found innocent he would have been freed
immediately, legal experts said.
   On Friday, Judge Carl-Anton Spak gave a further indication that
a conviction was forthcoming when he said the court had reached ``a
verdict'' and not ``a decision.''
   ``It's a verdict that the court will come forward with. From
that you can draw your own conclusions,'' Spak said.
   Swedish radio said Spak's wording in legal terms virtually
eliminated the possibility Pettersson would be sent for a
psychiatric examination for possible committal to a mental
institution, which would have required ``a decision.''
   He faces a life sentence if found guilty, although such
sentences are commuted.
   Pettersson, who has a long criminal record, denied killing
Palme. His lawyer said he would appeal a guilty verdict.
   He was tried by a panel of two judges and six jurors, each with
an equal vote in deciding guilt or innocence. A tie results in
acquittal.
   Palme, a four-term prime minister who dominated Swedish politics
for two decades, was shot and killed Feb. 28, 1986 on a Stocholm
street after leaving a movie with his wife Lisbeth.
   The prosecution built a circumstantial case relying on the
testimony of Palme's widow, Lisbeth, who identified Pettersson as
the man she saw standing a few feet away after the shooting.
   Other witnesses said they saw Pettersson earlier outside the
theater where the Palme couple was seeing a movie, and following
them down the street.
   The defense questioned the memories of the witnesses more than
three years after the killing, and noted the prosecution had failed
to produce a motive, a murder weapon or other forensic evidence to
link Pettersson with the murder.
   Pettersson, 42, admitted he was in town to pick up drugs that
night, but said he was on his way home at the time of the shooting.
One defense witness, whose reliability was questioned by the
prosecution, testified seeing Pettersson 17 miles away at a
suburban train station shortly after Palme was shot.
</TEXT>
