<HEAD>Retired Philadelphia Archbishop in Serious Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT that Krol is retired archbishop
but not retired cardinal. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `He is...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John Krol was in serious condition
at a hospital today and undergoing medical tests a day after he
complained of feeling faint while playing golf.
   Krol 78, retired last year after 27 years as Roman Catholic
archbishop of Philadelphia but retains the title of cardinal. He
has remained active as a financial consultant to the church.
   ``He is resting comfortably and is under observation,'' in
serious but stable condition, said Bob Gallagher, a spokesman at
St. Agnes Hospital. The cardinal was transferred there from a
Sommers Point, N.J., hospital where he was taken after he
complained of feeling weak and faint, said Gallagher.
   Initial reports said he had suffered a stroke, but Gallagher
said this morning that doctors were uncertain what happened.
   In 1987, Krol suffered a weak spell after celebrating a Mass in
New Orleans and was hospitalized. At that time, he was brought back
to Philadelphia and underwent surgery to stop internal bleeding. He
retired in 1988.
   He was born in 1910 in Cleveland to Polish immigrant parents and
was ordained in 1937.
   Described as the only American who ever was mentioned as a
possible pope, Krol said repeatedly he never took such talk
seriously and never sought power or influence within the church
hierarchy.
