<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchanges Planned on Afghanistan, Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet officials will meet in
Stockholm, Sweden, starting July 31 to exchange views on the
situation in Afghanistan and Iran, the State Department said Friday.
   The meeting is another in a series in which the two sides
discuss regional issues.
   Afghanistan has been the subject of previous sessions but the
agenda of the upcoming. two-day meeting will be expanded for the
first time to include Iran.
   Iran apparently has been included because of the changing
situation there following the recent death of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini and the subsequent high-level contacts between Soviet and
Iranian authorities.
   Moscow and Washington have long been at odds over Afghanistan,
with each side accusing the other of prolonging the civil war in
that country.
   State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the U.S.
delegation to the talks will be headed by the assistant secretary
of state for Near East and South Asian affairs, John Kelly.
