<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Tsarouchis     07-21 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Tsarouchis,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Greek Artist Yiannis Tsarouchis Dead at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yiannis Tsarouchis, one of Greece's
leading artists and theater directors, has died after a long bout
with Parkinson's disease and chronic diabetes. He was 79.
   Tsarouchis died at Athens General State hospital Thursday, one
day after being admitted.
   Born in Piraeus in 1909, Tsarourichis was best-known for his
painting, which included portraits of Greek sailors and people in
traditional settings and clothing. He worked with oil, tempera and
watercolors and described his style of work as ``eastern
expressionism.''
   Tsarouchis' career spanned 60 years, with his first paintings
having been displayed in 1929.
   A graduate of the Athens School of Fine Arts, Tsarouchis also
directed theater. Most of his works dealt with themes from ancient
Greek theater.
   ``I don't know what to cry for first. The friend? The man? The
artist? Or the period that is extinguished with him? For the piece
of Greece that is leaving? I am very sad,'' said former Culture
Minister Melina Mercouri.
   No funeral plans were announced.
</TEXT>
