<FIRST>r w AM-FlagBurning     07-21 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Suggests Lawmakers Stick to Lawmaking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley suggested Friday
that lawmakers ``devote themselves to legislation'' instead of
staging demonstrations like the one in which several sprayed water
on the effigy of a flag burner.
   Responding to rumors of a flag burning Thursday, a dozen
Republican House members carried fire extinguishers and buckets of
water to the steps of the Supreme Court. When no flag burner
showed, they demonstrated their feelings anyway for the television
cameras, dousing a stuffed dummy representing such a culprit.
   ``I think it is probably better for members of the House to
devote themselves to legislation than to maintain peace and order
in the vicinity of the Capitol,'' Foley said Friday.
   ``But I certainly do not hold with flag burning, as I think you
know,'' he added.
   The GOP lawmakers support a constitutional amendment to overcome
the Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling last month that flag burning can be
a protected form of political expression. Foley, however, favors
passage of a regular statute to get around the decision, leaving
the Constitution alone.
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., told colleagues and onlookers
at Thursday's demonstration that the congessmen were setting an
example for Americans to follow if they witness flag burnings.
   ``If they don't have a bucket of water, I hope they take care of
business however they can,'' he said.
   When Foley was asked whether the image projected by the event
was the proper one for members of Congress, he replied: ``I will
leave to every member of Congress the management of his own image,
or hers.''
   ``I think your question raises the question itself about whether
that is everybody's idea of the appropriate behavior for a member
of the House of Representatives,'' he said. ``But I don't want to
try to make a judgment for the individual members involved.''
</TEXT>
