<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-21 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Considers Lifting Censorship on Foreign Press</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This report was submitted to a government censor
who made no changes.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday it would
consider removing recently imposed censorship restrictions from
foreign journalists.
   ``Censoring the press has never helped,'' Agriculture Minister
Lalith Athulathmudali said. ``If it is extended, it becomes
counterproductive because it helps fuel rumors.''
   Opposition members of Parliament said the government's move had
backfired.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said officials will reconsider
the censorship and ``probably lift it where the foreign media is
concerned.''
   Wijeratne announced the censorship regulations July 6 as part of
a campaign against Sinhalese militants trying to overthrow the
government. He also announced security forces had orders to shoot
anyone putting up anti-government posters or instigating strikes.
   Despite members' criticism of censorship, Parliament on Friday
approved a government proposal to extend strict emergency laws in
the country for another month.
   The laws were in effect from 1983 until President Ransinghe
Premadasa took office and lifted them in January. Killings
continued in this Indian Ocean island's ethnic conflicts, however,
and the laws were reimposed on June 20.
   Minority Tamil rebels have been fighting for a separate homeland
since 1983.
   In 1987, the Sinhalese-dominated government offered the rebels
limited autonomy in exchange for a surrender of arms, but the
largest Tamil militia rejected the plan.
   The Tamil group then began fighting Indian soldiers who were
sent to enforce the agreement.
   The accord also touched off the backlash of Sinhalese militants,
who felt it made too many concessions to the Tamils.
   The two conflicts have left at least 15,000 people dead.
</TEXT>
