<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     07-21 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Calls For Quick Formation of Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party Politburo called
Friday for the quick formation of a new government and announced a
Central Committee plenum will be held July 29-30, Poland's official
news agency said.
   Naming a new prime minister is the first major task of President
Wojciech Jaruzelski. The general and party leader was elected to
the powerful new office of president on Wednesday with the bare
minimum of votes.
   The Politburo ``decided that negative economic notions and a
difficult situation in the market require formation of the new
government in the shortest possbile time,'' the agency said.
   Poland's economic crisis has taken a turn for the worse in the
past several months. Prices on such goods as sugar, gasoline,
ciagarettes and household appliances have increased sharply and the
inflation rate is over 160 percent. Many consumer goods have
disappeared from the shelves and meat is in short supply.
   The Politburo also said it favored creation of a government of
national accord, the PAP news agency reported, but did not provide
details. It congratulated Jaruzelski on his election.
   The government is subject to legislative approval. For the first
time in four decades, the communists face real opposition in the
National Assembly after June elections in which Solidarity
candidates won all but one of 261 seats the opposition was allowed
to contest.
   Jaruzelski and other top party officials have urged the
opposition to join a ``great coalition, but Solidarity lawmakers
have yet to take a final decision on the issue of the government.''
   National Assembly deputy Janusz Onyszkiewicz, who is also
national spokesman for the Solidarity trade union said Thursday
that Solidarity lawmakers would convene next week to continue
discussion on the government.
</TEXT>
