<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1610EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BogusMogul     07-21 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bogus Mogul,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phony Filmmaker Cons Businesses Out of Goods, Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He's not exactly puttin' on the Ritz, but
this phony Hollywood filmmaker is having a good time on the cuff,
leaving hotels, restaurants and night spots stuck with the bills.
   ``He's having a hell of a nice vacation is what he's having,''
said Cathy Savino, director of the Orlando office of the Economic
Development Commission of Mid-Florida.
   The bogus mogul has seen the whales at Sea World, toured the
sound stages at Universal Studios, lounged at two hotels and seen
the sights from a helicopter and the back of a burgundy-colored
stretch limousine.
   He's taken women dancing and dining at a fancy Chinese
restaurant. He's told people from Sanford to Orlando that he is
with Warner Brothers, Lorimar Studios, Spielberg Productions (which
doesn't exist), or his own JFT Productions.
   His tab has run into the thousands, but this man calling himself
John Frank has never spent a dime. He's asked businessmen to send
the bills to non-existent companies.
   Frank's victims have described him as short, dark-haired and
dumpy, dressed in a sloppy fashion.
   The Orange County Sheriff's Department is looking for him,
spokesman Jim Solomons said Friday. Ms. Savino has warned film
offices statewide to be on the lookout.
   ``This town and this community is primed for that right now
because of the two studios in town and the enthusiasm for the
(film) industry,'' Ms. Savino said. ``There are very good people in
this industry, and then there are con artists.''
   The Disney-MGM Studios theme park and Universal Studios Florida
have begun movie and television production in the Orlando area in
the last year, bringing an influx of film people, technicians,
executives and related businesses. Residents often encounter movie
and TV stars and other industry officials shopping, dining or
living among them.
   Frank told clerks and others that he was making a movie called
``Runaways,'' starring Judd Hirsch, Amy Irving, Dan Ackroyd and
River Phoenix.
   The impostor was last seen at the Holiday Inn on Interstate 4 in
Sanford, where he spent two weeks before abruptly checking out
Tuesday when Ms. Savino began trying to track him down. He had
arranged for phony corporate billing to the tune of $560.
   The film phony's Orlando-area adventures began the last week of
June, when he checked into the Red Roof Inn in a tourist area
called International Drive. Along with drinks, food and
incidentals, the tab there came to $715 plus tax.
   Before vanishing, he took desk clerk Tammy Pierson, 22, and a
girlfriend dancing.
   ``I'm from Michigan and from a small town and never knew
anybody, so when he said he was a producer, I didn't see any reason
to disbelieve him,'' said Ms. Pierson.
   Owner Randy Sprayberry of the Sandwich Gallery was out about
$150 worth of sandwiches and drinks the man supposedly bought for
his film crew.
   ``It's almost laughable that I got taken by a movie producer,
your stereotypical con man,'' said Sprayberry, who agreed to send
his bills to JFT Productions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
