<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1619EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     07-21 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Refuses to Exclude Khmer Rouge From Future Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk said
Friday he supports a role for the communist Khmer Rouge in a
Cambodian government despite their history of atrocities.
   He said that at an international conference starting July 30,
the guerrilla group will sign a guarantee accepting strict controls
when it becomes part of an interim government made of resistance
groups and the Cambodian regime.
   Khmer Rouge participation in a government is expected to be a
major sticking point at the conference, which represents the most
serious effort yet to end the 10-year-old Cambodian war.
   Speaking at a news conference, Sihanouk rejected a cease-fire
proposal supported by Vietnam and said resistance guerrillas will
keep fighting until all Vietnamese forces leave Cambodia, where a
Vietnamese-installed government is in power.
   Sihanouk also wants an international peacekeeping force and for
elections to follow the pullout.
   The promised retreat by Sept. 30 of the remainder of Vietnam's
troops, estimated to number up to 70,000, was a ruse, he said. He
said 130,000 other Vietnamese are ``hidden'' in the Cambodian army
and paramilitary.
   Sihanouk's remarks came four days before a scheduled meeting
with the head of the Cambodian government, Prime Minister Hun Sen,
to be followed by talks between Hun Sen and the three-party
resistance.
   The Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three guerrilla movements,
was responsible for the deaths of hundreds of thousands of
Cambodians during a three-year reign of terror that ended with
Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia in December 1978.
   Sihanouk said the Khmer Rouge ``will commit themselves in
writing during the international conference to accept to be
strictly controlled for several years, five years, 10 years if need
be, by an international control mechanism and a U.N. peacekeeping
force.''
   Sihanouk has said he wants controls to prevent any single party
from monopolizing power, but Hun Sen, Vietnam and the United States
oppose any Khmer Rouge role.
   Khmer Rouge representatives were not available for comment.
   The Paris conference will be attended by the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council _ France, the United States,
Britain, China and the Soviet Union _ and members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations. Canada and several other
countries also will participate.
   Two recent rounds of peace talks held in Jakarta, Indonesia,
produced a consensus that Vietnam's pullout must be linked with
measures to prevent the Khmer Rouge from returning to power.
   In addition, there is growing pressure in the United States to
provide military aid to the non-communist resistance to lessen
their reliance on the Khmer Rouge.
   ``The Khmer Rouge are seriously committed to respecting the
spirit of quadripartism,'' Sihanouk said, referring to his proposal
for a government that includes the three-tiered resistance movement
and Hun Sen. ``We cannot let this occasion slip by.''
   Sihanouk, who negotiated his country's independence from France
in 1953 and was deposed in 1970, denied he was an ``accomplice'' of
the Khmer Rouge.
   ``They killed five of my children ... I cannot pardon them
that,'' he said. ``But if I abandon the resistance ... I serve ipso
facto the cause of Vietnamese colonialism.''
   The resistance leader said he was not against the principle of a
cease-fire proposed by Thailand. Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen
Co Thach said Wednesday he supported that proposal, saying there
could be no peaceful solution without a cease-fire.
   However, Sihanouk said a cease-fire was not possible while
``Vietnamese colonialism'' continued.
   Sihanouk made public the resistance movement's plan for a
constitution. Based on the French model, it calls for a president
elected to a seven-year term, a premier and a two-chamber
parliament. The plan specifies the name of the country as Cambodia,
a new Cambodian flag, coat of arms and a national anthem _ to be
composed by Sihanouk himself.
   ASEAN, which includes Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia,
Brunei and the Philippines, supports a Khmer Rouge role in an
interim government.
</TEXT>
