<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Shelling     07-21 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Shelling,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugee Camp Shelled; 1 Dead, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cambodian refugee camp run by
communist Khmer Rouge guerrillas was hit by shelling Friday, and
one refugee was killed and 10 were wounded, Western relief
officials said.
   It appeared the shells were fired by Cambodian government forces
or their Vietnamese allies, the relief officials said.
   The three-hour attack followed overnight fighting in the area,
according to a Thai security official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The relief officials said about 27 rounds crashed into the Site
8 camp, sending most of the 40,000 residents fleeing.
   A 22-year-old man was killed and 10 refugees, including two
children, were wounded, said an official of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
   The camp in Thailand's eastern province of Prachinburi, about a
mile from the Cambodian border, is the main civilian camp run by
the Khmer Rouge, the largest guerrilla group fighting Cambodian
government forces and their Vietnamese allies.
   The Khmer Rouge sometimes has shelled its own camps to exercise
strict control over the refugees. Widespread human rights
violations have been reported in Khmer Rouge camps.
   Fighting between Cambodian government forces and the Khmer Rouge
has increased along the border in recent days.
</TEXT>
