<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     07-21 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Co-leaders of Main Opposition Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two leaders of the main opposition
party have been put under long-term house arrest for trying to
``destroy the military and revive anarchy'' in Burma, the
government said Friday.
   Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo lead the National League for
Democracy and have been increasingly outspoken in attacking the
military government. They were confined to their homes Thursday and
cut off from their supporters.
   Government spokesmen told a news conference the house arrest
could last a year and be be renewed under the Law to Protect the
State from Dangers of Disruptive and Destructive Elements.
   ``They will be held as long as the dangers of disruption of
peace and tranquility by them exist,'' said Col. Aung Thein, when
asked if the two could run in general elections next year. He said
their party or others might be barred from the elections if ``the
party or parties continue the excesses.''
   Gen. Saw Maung pledged soon after crushing a pro-democracy
movement in September that elections would be held in 1990.
   Ms. Suu Kyi, 44-year-old daughter of national independence hero
Aung San, sided with students and others demanding an end to
authoritarian rule. She became secretary of the league and Tin Oo,
a retired general, agreed to be its chairman.
   In Washington, the State Departmen the streets. State radio reported
44 arrests.
   The diplomat in Bangkok said tight government controls on
information probably would continue at least until Aug. 8, the
first anniversary of mass anti-government demonstrations that were
brutally repressed by the army.
   Telex and telephone lines to Rangoon from Asian cities have been
out of order since Wednesday evening. The diplomat said it appeared
the telex line was restored temporarily Friday only to allow
correspondents of foreign news organizations to file their stories
on the news conference.
   ``Outsiders cannot communicate with the inmates (under house
arrest) either personally or by telephone,'' said government
spokesman Kyaw Sann.
   He said members of the prisoners' families could leave the
premises ``under surveillance,'' but could not contact foreign
embassies, political parties or people connected with the parties.
   ``Action has to be taken'' against Ms. Suu Kyi and Tin Oo ``for
their repeated attempts to divide the military and the people and
also to cause disunity among the military,'' Kyaw Sann said.
   ``Both of them mounted their incitement in the last two months,
finally using confrontational strategy to destroy the military and
revive anarchy in the country.''
</TEXT>
