<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress'Days Bjt   07-21 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress' Days, Bjt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trying to Cut Congress' ``Goat Days,'' ``Jukebox Weeks''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two House members say they are making headway
in a long battle against Congress spending time and money
commemorating jukeboxes, asparagus, dairy goats and hundreds of
other things.
   Reps. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla., and Claudine Schneider, R-R.I., are
proposing to turn the time-consuming job of recognizing pet causes
over to a commission, which would pass worthy proposals on to the
president for action.
   In the 100th Congress that ended last year, lawmakers passed 258
bills designating commemorative days, weeks or months. Among them
were National Asparagus Month, National Dairy Goat Awareness Week
and National Jukebox Week. A decade ago, the 95th Congress passed
just 34 such measures.
   ``This is clearly a reform initiative that will focus members of
Congress more on substantive legislation,'' Schneider said. Not to
mention saving some $500,000 in printing costs and staff time, she
estimates.
   She said commemoratives have proliferated because groups have
seized upon them as a way of gaining instant credibility, and
members of Congress have gone along because it's an easy way to
``throw a bone'' to the home folks.
   ``Organizations feel that if you can have a congressional stamp
of approval to your `Week of the Dandelions,' or `National
Butterfly Day,' or whatever, there is more of an establishment aura
to it,'' she said.
   ``I would not be surprised if there were not many members whose
only list of accomplishments legislatively might be
commemoratives,'' she added.
   McCurdy has been introducing legislation on the subject since
1985, but it has never moved, primarily because lawmakers are
reluctant to give up a goody they can pass out to constituents.
   But this week, McCurdy and Schneider met with Rep. Tom Sawyer,
D-Ohio, chairman of the Post Office and Civil Service subcommittee
that handles commemorative bills, and won a promise that for the
first time a hearing will be held on their idea.
   McCurdy called the move ``a welcome turning point'' and said his
proposal for an 11-member commission is ``a common-sense approach.
Creating a commission does not add another layer of bureaucracy.
Rather, it thins out the layer from the involvement of 435 people
to 11.''
   The two lawmakers have enlisted a majority of House members in
support of their legislation, which in part prompted Sawyer's
decision to hold a hearing. The session will be scheduled for
September, after Congress returns from its August recess.
   In the meantime, the beat goes on. Some 268 commemorative
measures have been introduced in the first seven months of this
year; 81 have passed either the House or Senate, and 28 have been
signed into law.
   Among proposals still before Congress: National Tap Dance Day,
sponsored by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.; National Duckling Month,
proposed by Rep. Bill Hefner, D-N.C.; the Decade of the Brain,
offered by Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass.; and National Culinary Week,
pushed by Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Drought-Farmer     07-21 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Farmer,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers In North Dakota Praying For Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STERLING, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Lang's wheat field looks green and
almost lush, waving gently in a breeze that provides a momentary
respite from North Dakota's July inferno.
   But Lang's digging fingers find surface soil so dry it runs like
salt through his fingers. Deeper, where the ground in better times
would come up in moist, dark clumps, it is pale, almost as hard as
a nearby fence post.
   The wheat stalks hold little promise of developing plump,
healthy kernels in time for the August harvest.
   ``You get down here, there's nothing there,'' Lang said, his
fingers probing the parched dirt.
   This is the second straight drought year for North Dakota, and
Lang's farm about 23 miles east of Bismarck is in one of the
state's driest areas.
   The drought of 1989 is not as widespread as the previous year,
but it still covers roughly a third of the nation, said Norton
Strommen, chief meteorologist for the U.S. Agriculture Department.
The main swath cuts northwest from Illinois through the Dakotas,
parts of Kansas and Nebraska, Strommen said.
   Virtually all of North Dakota _ the nation's leading producer of
spring wheat and durum, a wheat variety used for pasta _ is
considered to be in a ``severe to extreme drought,'' he said. Parts
of neighboring South Dakota and Minnesota also have been hurt.
   ``At this time ... to get back down to near normal, it would
take from 5 to 10 inches of rain,'' Strommen said.
   But that much rain is unlikely on the 3,100-acre farm that Lang,
43, works with his 78-year-old father, Theodore.
   On Monday, storms dumped as much as 3 inches of rain on some
parts of the state. But, said Lang, ``it missed us.''
   The Lang farm has gotten only about 4{ inches of rain since
April 1, about half of what the thirsty soil needs.
   ``There isn't any subsoil moisture,'' said Theodore Lang, a
state representative since 1965 and a lifelong farmer. ``That's
where the problem is.''
   The wheat field David Lang surveys may yield three or four
bushels an acre, a sixth of its normal yield and barely enough to
make harvesting worthwhile.
   ``Last summer, it held on for so long,'' Lang said. ``I guess
that's what kept your optimism up ... because you'd look out in the
field, and it was still green. You'd think, gee, if you could just
get a half-inch of rain on this.''
   Rain was in short supply everywhere in North Dakota last year,
when about a third of the state's 6.2 million-acre spring wheat
crop was abandoned. Direct crop losses were estimated at more than
$500 million.
   North Dakota State University researchers have pegged this
year's crop losses at $661 million so far, saying the state would
lose 30 percent of its spring wheat and from 26 percent to 42
percent of its durum, barley and hay.
   The 1988 drought ruined Lang's crop. But this spring, in hopes
of plentiful rainfall and prices driven up by grain shortages, he
planted 1,500 acres.
   Now, he estimates he may be able to harvest only about 150 acres.
   There are some bright spots. Lang expects to have enough hay to
feed 150 cattle, and the cattle can graze fields that would be
useless to harvest. The farm is not in danger of foreclosure.
   Wearing jeans and a denim shirt with cut-off sleeves exposing
Popeye-size forearms, Lang maintains a sunny disposition.
   ``I guess I'm more of an optimist,'' he says.
   But he worries whether the federal government, which pumped more
than $400 million in drought aid into North Dakota last year, will
respond again in 1989, when dry conditions are not as widespread
nationwide.
   Lang received about $25,000 in federal drought aid last year.
That aid, along with crop-insurance payments ``helped keep the wolf
off our back,'' he said.
   ``I don't want to see a handout, I'm not begging for a
handout,'' Lang said. ``But you look at what disaster money did to
the economy of North Dakota last year ... Some of the areas, we're
going to need it to keep things going.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
