<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignAid     07-21 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Aid,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Easily OKs Bill, Sends It To The Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, with unusual ease, on Friday
approved a $14.3 billion foreign aid bill that sends a warning to
the Philippines to improve its management of aid dollars and begins
President Bush's initiatives in Hungary and Poland to boost private
development.
   With little debate, the lawmakers voted 329 to 69 to appove what
traditionally has been one of the most contentious pieces of
legislation Congress takes up each year. The bill, one of 13 basic
money measures that fund the full array of federal programs, now
goes to the Senate.
   The bill includes $160 million as the U.S. contribution toward
the Multilateral Assistance Initiative for the Philippines, an
effort to bolster the government of President Corazon Aquino with
an influx of development aid.
   But that amount falls below the $200 million pledged to the
program by President Bush. The cut was intended to signal concerns
that money already flowing to the Philippines is not being used or
is being wasted.
   The House Appropriations Committee report accompanying the bill
said the panel ``is deeply concerned about the management crisis in
the Philippine foreign assistance program'' and added that further
cuts will follow if improvements are not made.
   The measure includes $10 million for Poland and $5 million for
Hungary to begin a three-year, $125-million plan announced by Bush
last week to encourage private development in those two East Bloc
countries.
   The bill has substantially greater emphasis on development aid
and less on military assistance than the Bush administration had
sought. Security aid totaled $7.6 billion, a $1.6-billion cut from
the White House request. Development aid was boosted from the $5.3
billion Bush had asked to $6 billion.
   Other allocations in the bill include $3 billion for Israel and
$2.1 billion for Egypt, largely a reward for their participation in
the Camp David Middle East peace process; a maximum of $85 million
in military aid to the newly elected government of El Salvador, led
by Alfredo Cristiani of the right-wing ARENA party; $65 million for
the U.N. Children's Fund, more than double the administration's
request; and a total of $410 million for migration and refugee
assistance, $40 million more than the administration had asked.
   Also earmarked are $20 million for a program to promote peace in
Northern Ireland; $230 million in military aid to Pakistan; $12
million for the West Bank and Gaza strip for education, health and
agriculture programs; and $164 million for the Peace Corps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
