<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Party     07-21 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Officials Bemoan Confusion, Want Tamer Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders, bemoaning the ideological
confusion in the party under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms, have called for tight restrictions on the press and a
clear second-in-command.
   The party newspaper Pravda on Friday published speeches made
Tuesday by party chiefs depicting ruling Communist cadres cut loose
without a party line and drifting in a sea of contradictions.
   In answer to a speech by Gorbachev encouraging party members to
further perestroika _ his economic and political revival program _
leader after leader complained that party activists were confused
and hampered by opposition forces unleashed by the reforms.
   Leonid F. Bobykin, party chief in Sverdlovsk, told the meeting,
``Things are going not at all the way we expected and the way they
should.''
   ``We don't see a hard line on ideological questions,'' he said.
   Bobykin said the role of the Secretariat of the Central
Committee had been weakened, and ``what's needed, apparently, is a
second secretary of the Central Committee, no matter what that's
called officially.''
   Gorbachev's post as general secretary of the Central Committe
makes him head of the party, but no second-in-command has been
designated. The Politburo member in charge of ideology
traditionally has been viewed as the No. 2 party official, but
leaders have said no one fulfills that role since Yegor K. Ligachev
was replaced as ideology chief last fall.
   The 251-member Central Committee is the policy-making body of
the party. Its Secretariat is charged with day-to-day oversight of
the party apparatus.
   At Tuesday's meeting, Ligachev called for tight party control of
the press and the political arena. He did not directly criticize
Gorbachev, but implied he was taking too light a hand to counter
threats to the party's power and national law and order.
   Ligachev, who now oversees the agricultural sector, asked how
Gorbachev's July 1 speech appealing for peace among the country's
many ethnic groups was received.
   In certain areas, ``it was received with clashes, with people's
deaths,'' he answered.
   At least 17 people have been reported killed this month in
ethnic clashes in the Abkhazia region of the southern republic of
Georgia.
   Ligachev, considered a conservative force in the Politburo, said
``oppositionist, anti-perestroika political organizations with
their own publications'' were gaining strength.
   He ruled out the idea of taking control of the press away from
the party, cautioning that ``in that case, the media will turn into
the dictatorship of certain forces.''
   Bobykin echoed Ligachev's criticism of the media, as did many of
Tuesday's speakers. Bobykin said greater press freedom under
Gorbachev ``leads sometimes not to consolidation, but to
disintegration, distorts the line of perestroika.''
   ``From literature, cinema, and television, the figure of the
laborer, of the laboring workdays of perestroika, has practically
disappeared,'' he said. ``They've become filled with `legal
robbers,' prostitutes, drug addicts, hooligans and dubious
`supermen.'''
   Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said the Politburo also
appeared alienated at times from the reform process.
   At last month's Congress of People's Deputies, the legislature
that is the centerpiece of Gorbachev's political reforms, ``the
Politburo ended up over on the side, in some kind of isolated
state, as if some paralysis syndrome were at work on it,'' he said.
   ``No one from the Politburo made a speech at the Congress, as is
well known,'' he remarked. ``I think that was our strategic
miscalculation.''
   Ryzhkov also called for the division of labor in the Politburo
to be rearranged to let Gorbachev ``devote more attention to his
party duties.''
   The rank-and-file party members ``don't understand a lot these
days,'' said Moscow party chief Lev N. Zaikov. ``And that makes
them unhappy and passive.
</TEXT>
