<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     07-21 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Dissatisfied With Response on Police Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. chief Javier Perez de Cuellar
asked government officials Friday to dismiss more than 2,000
Namibia police from a unit accused of war atrocities and harassing
civilians.
   The U.N. secretary general also said he would investigate South
Africa's claims that many political prisoners remain held by the
South-West Africa People's Organization, or SWAPO.
   The independence movement began its guerrilla war against South
African rule of Namibia in 1966 but stopped fighting after an
independence plan was approved last December.
   Perez de Cuellar met with Foreign Minister Pik Botha and two
other Cabinet members Friday after arriving from a three-day trip
to Namibia. While there, he said his request for dismissal of the
controversial police officers was turned town by Louis Pienaar, the
territorial administrator installed by South Africa.
   ``I'm sorry to say I'm not totally satisfied'' with Pienaar's
decision, the U.N. chief said before leaving Namibia, also known as
South-West Africa.
   Despite the dispute, Botha and the U.N. leader predicted the
territory would have elections as scheduled Nov. 6 to establish an
independent government and end 74 years of South African control.
   Perez de Cuellar said the main threat to fair elections
concerned charges of intimidation by Namibian police who belonged
to the disbanded paramilitary unit known as Koevoet, the Afrikaans
word for ``crowbar.''
   ``I want to totally remove the shadow of Koevoet,'' he told a
news conference in Namibia.
   During that territory's war, Koevoet members often went on
weeklong patrols through isolated villages and bush territory in
armored vehicles mounted with machine guns. They were accused of
dozens of atrocities against civilians and guerrillas.
   Koevoet was officially disbanded earlier this year, but more
than 2,000 of its members were integrated into the regular police
force. SWAPO says those members are still harassing its supporters.
   In Lusaka, Zambia, SWAPO President Sam Nujoma said South
African-controlled Namibian troops killed 27 civilians near
Oshakati in northern Namibia.
   He said villagers reported seeing former Koevoet members burying
the victims' corpses after the July 15 killings.
   He called the killings a ``massacre'' but gave no details.
   ``The people were murdered. They (Koevoet) were really caught
red-handed,'' said Nujoma at a news conference.
   Territorial authorities previously acknowledged burying 11
guerrillas but dismissed the report of 27 bodies.
   Nujoma said the killings support SWAPO's demands for an increase
in the strength of U.N. forces supervising the independence plan.
About 4,650 U.N. troops now are stationed in Namibia under the plan.
   Nujoma urged the United Nations to send more troops to Namibia
so its forces ``could be in a position to prevent further South
African massacres of our people and intimidation of voters.''
   SWAPO is favored to win the elections.
   Pienaar met with Perez de Cuellar on Wednesday and announced
that former Koevoet members would be moved from north-central
Namibia into less tense regions. But he says he will dismiss
policemen only if misconduct is proved against them individually.
   Perez de Cuellar also said Friday he was ``very much concerned''
by charges that SWAPO continues to hold large numbers of prisoners
at camps in Angola. Under terms of the U.N. independence plan,
political prisoners on both sides are to be freed, and 24 SWAPO
members were released from a Namibian prison Thursday.
   SWAPO has said it released all 201 detainees it held. But
relatives and the freed detainees have said nearly 2,000 prisoners
were in SWAPO camps.
   The former detainees also say dozens of people were killed in
the camps.
   Perez de Cuellar said he plans to travel to Zambia on Saturday
to confer with President Kenneth Kaunda and Nujoma.
</TEXT>
