<FIRST>r i AM-DalaiLama     07-21 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Leader Calls China Crackdown Temporary Setback for Tibet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama said Friday that China's
crackdown on the democracy movement is only a temporary setback for
Tibet's fight for autonomy.
   The spiritual leader of Tibetans also said the June 3-4
crackdown on protesters in Beijing should help Chinese understand
the situation in Tibet.
   The Himalayan region annexed by China 40 years ago has been the
scene of numerous clashes in recent years between Tibetan monks,
independence activists and Chinese settlers, police and soldiers.
   The Dalai Lama, concluding a monthlong trip, told a news
conference that for both Tibetan and Chinese pro-democracy
activists, ``eventually things will improve. The desire for
democracy and freedom are basic human desires in the human blood.''
   But he said China's attitude toward dissent following the
Beijing protests ``is much more hard-line, so naturally the
attitude toward Tibet has become harder.
   ``But, while the recent events are very sad, I feel it is a
temporary setback.''
   Later Friday, the Dalai Lama, who fled Tibet after an abortive
1959 uprising against Chinese control, received the first Raul
Wallenberg Congressional Human Rights Award. It is named after a
Swedish diplomat who helped save tens of thousands of people from
the Holocaust.
   The Dalai Lama has visited Costa Rica, Mexico, Los Angeles and
New York.
   Rep. Thomas Lantos, D-Calif., said the Dalai Lama was honored
because ``he is the quintessential leader of the global trends
toward reconciliation, non-violence and peace.''
   The only difference between Chinese suppression of Tibetans for
40 years and its suppression of its own democracy movement in June
``is that the events in Tiananmen were carried on TV to hundreds of
millions of living rooms around the world,'' Lantos said.
   China says Tibet historically has been part of China, while
Tibetans claim that despite the region's trade, tribute and
religious links to China, it has been fundamentally independent.
   The Dalai Lama said his desire for dialogue with the Chinese
government has not changed despite the crackdown, but he said his
contacts with China through the Chinese Embassy in New Delhi have
been stalled.
   ``We have made a number of proposals through New Delhi, but
there has been no response,'' he said.
   The Dalai Lama's latest proposal calls for Tibet to be
self-governing but for China to remain responsible for its defense
and foreign affairs. China rejected the idea.
   The Dalai Lama, chosen at birth as a reincarnation of the last
Dalai Lama, is revered by Tibetans as the ``god-king'' and symbol
of their motherland.
   ``I am quite popular,'' he said, ``but the system must change.
Without change in this Dalai Lama system, democracy would be very
difficult to achieve and meaningless.''
   Authority for the Dalai Lama, he said, should not just come
naturally, but through election. He must first be qualified to be
the spiritual leader before he becomes the Dalai Lama.
   ``It is nonsense that a young boy, not well qualified, should be
chosen as Dalai Lama to become a spiritual leader.
   ``I never felt that I was the Dalai Lama,'' he said. ``I am a
monk, no more, no less. I am just a monk.''
</TEXT>
