<FIRST>r i AM-Cugat     07-21 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cugat,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xavier Cugat, Famed Band Leader, in Hospital Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Band leader Xavier Cugat has been
hospitalized after suffering more heart trouble, his doctors said
Friday.
   In a statement, doctors of the 89-year-old musician said he was
responding to treatment and remained in stable condition.
   The doctors at Quiron Hospital here said Cugat was suffering
from failure of a heart valve.
   Long troubled by heart problems, Cugat has had four heart
attacks and a stroke since 1980. He was hospitalized twice last
year for heart and lung ailments.
   Cugat became a U.S. star with his band in the early 1930s.
   They played Latin dance music for movie stars at the Coconut
Grove club in Los Angeles' Ambassador Hotel. Cugat later led his
band at the Waldorf-Astoria hotel in New York.
   He is credited for helping to introduce Latin American rhythms
into American dance music.
   He also appeared in several Hollywood movies.
   Cugat was born in 1900 in the northeastern Catalonian town of
Gerona, but immigrated with his family to Cuba when he was a child.
   In 1970, he turned over his band to Tito Puente and a decade
later returned to live in Barcelona.
   In recent years, he occasionally has appeared on Spanish
television to tell stories of his Hollywood days.
