<DOCNO> AP890721-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus     07-21 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriots Present Petition Demanding Release of Detainees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of women staged a sit-in outside
U.N. offices Friday until they were allowed to present a petition
demanding freedom for Greek Cypriots arrested while protesting the
Turkish occupation of northern Cyprus.
   The women, accompanied by a dozen priests, sat outside the
office of the U.N. Force in Cyprus after they were blocked from
marching to the home of Oscar Camilion, the U.N. special
representative in Cyprus.
   They said they would remain until Camilion met with them. Four
hours later, U.N. soldiers allowed a priest and a demonstrator
through. They walked to the U.N. official's residence, about 500
yards away, and handed him the appeal.
   The estimated 500 to 600 demonstrators then dispersed.
   The petition demanded the release of 108 Greek Cypriots detained
Wednesday, the eve of the 15th anniversary of the Turkish invasion.
   The detainees _ 10 men and 98 women _ appeared in a Turkish
Cypriot court Friday and were tried and convicted on charges of
entering a restricted military zone and violating the borders of
the breakaway Turkish Cypriot state. The state, established in
1983, is recognized only by Turkey.
   Sentencing was scheduled Saturday. They face up to 18 months in
prison.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar called for the
release of the detainees and criticized both the Greek Cypriots and
Turkish Cypriots for Wednesday's incident.
   He said that despite previous assurances from Greek Cypriot
authorities, ``events marked by violence and the destruction of
United Nations property were allowed to take place.
   ``It is also unacceptable that the Turkish Cypriot side crossed
the Turkish Force cease-fire line and forcibly took demonstrators
back to their area,'' he said.
   Turkish Cypriot riot police made the arrests after about 1,000
demonstrators broke through U.N. barricades into a buffer zone
between the Greek and Turkish sides.
   About 60 British paratroopers from the seven-nation U.N. Force
in Cyprus formed a human barricade to prevent Friday's marchers
from reaching Camilion's home, on the Green Line that divides the
island into the Turkish and Greek sectors.
   The women then sat on the ground, blocking the entance to the
U.N. office.
   Their petition, read through a bullhorn by one of the
protesters, accused Turkish forces of launching a ``brutal attack
against the unarmed women.''
   It also demanded the withdrawal of 35,000 Turkish troops and
50,000 mainland settlers from northern Cyprus, and the return of
about 200,000 Greek Cypriots who were evicted from northern Cyprus
when the Turks invaded.
   President George Vassiliou conferred with Camilion and
reiterated earlier demands for U.N. action to bring about the
release of the detainees, said government spokesman Akis Fantis.
   Vassiliou also conferred eparately with the diplomatic
representatives of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council: the United States, Britain, the Soviet Union, France and
China.
   Turkey's Foreign Ministry criticized U.N. peacekeeping troops
for failing to prevent the demonstrators Wednesday from bursting
into the buffer zone.
   The Cypriot demonstrators also criticized the U.N. troops,
saying they did nothing to protect the protesters from the Turks on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
