<FIRST>r w AM-ScienceAdviser     07-21 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Science Adviser,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominee Backs Big Projects, But Not at Smaller Ones' Expense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yale nuclear physicist D. Allan Bromley,
President Bush's nominee to be White House science adviser, said
Friday he supports several ``big science'' projects but doesn't
want to see them funded at the expense of small grants to
individual researchers.
   Testifying at his confirmation hearing, Bromley also said he
believes there are good chances for an increase in staffing at the
White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, which
sustained substantial budget cuts during the Reagan administration.
   Bromley told the Senate Commerce Committee he had been assured
by Bush that the president wants to enhance the visibility of the
White House office and to give his science adviser ready access to
the Oval Office.
   In line with this policy, Bromley said Bush was planning to
establish and have regular meetings with a new Council of Science
and Technology Advisers, intended to bring together the best
expertise from a wide range of areas.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., who chaired the hearing, said he
expects ``very speedy approval'' of Bromley's nomination by the
committee and then by the full Senate.
   Bromley said he was committed to supporting the $4.4 billion
Superconducting Super Collider, a 53-mile circumference nuclear
particle accelerator to be constructed south of Dallas, Texas.
   Bromley said he also supports a research megaproject in the life
sciences _ using advanced computer techniques to map all the genes,
which control heredity, comprising the chromosomes within each cell.
   But he expressed reservations about moving ahead immediately
with development of a hypersonic aerospace plane capable of flying
between New York and Tokyo in about two hours.
   ``I happen to believe that the national aerospace plane is an
important project, but at the moment both the (National) Space
Council and Secretary (of Defense Dick) Cheney have agreed that
that would be slowed down,'' he said.
   Bromley told the Senate panel that ``we simply cannot afford, no
matter how attractive, all these megaprojects. We can't afford to
do them all simultaneously.''
   He said that was particularly the case because it would be
``suicidal'' to fund the ``big science'' projects by significantly
cutting funds available for small grants to individual researchers.
</TEXT>
