<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Soviet     07-21 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Soviet,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims of Soviet Georgian Unrest Being Treated In West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten victims of the unrest in Soviet
Georgia are being treated in West Germany, but there were
conflicting accounts Friday as to whether they were exposed to
poison gas.
   The ARD television network reported the patients suffered from
ailments related to an April incident in Georgia when troops used
force to end a pro-reform demonstration.
   ``Preliminary results indicate that the feared chlorine gas of
World War I was also used in addition to tear and irritant gases,''
ARD said.
   But Ingwardt Tauchert, a spokesman for Saarland state's Health
Ministry, said toxicology tests had not determined the kind of gas
the victims were exposed to.
   ``The tests are still being conducted and it would be premature
to make any conclusions about what they were exposed to,'' Tauchert
said in an interview.
   ARD said treatment had been hampered because Soviet officials
have refused to say what kind of gas was used by security forces to
quell unrest in Georgia.
   Tauchert said many of the patients complained of breathing
difficulties and cramps, which he said could also be caused ``by
stress resulting from a traumatic experience.''
   The 10 Soviets arrived in West Germany on July 15 and were taken
to the Homburg University Clinic.
   They are to return home next week. The Homburg clinic agreed to
treat the victims as a humanitarian gesture, Tauchert said.
   ARD said in its report that some of the patients suffered from
depression and that others were barely conscious.
   Tauchert said he could not confirm the ARD report.
   Clinic officials could not be reached for comment on the ARD
report. Calls to the clinic were referred to the Saarland Health
Ministry.
   ARD said West German medical experts are trying to find better
ways of treating an estimated 4,500 people in Georgia who were
injured in the April unrest.
   On April 9, 20 demonstrators were killed by troops in the
Georgian capital of Tbilisi.
</TEXT>
