<FIRST>r a AM-MiamiViceEscape     07-21 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami Vice Escape,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Take TV Prison Escape to Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``Miami Vice'' television show about a
prison break wasn't even over when three young men took it to heart.
   ``It was spur of the moment,'' said Bob Cote, director of the
Guilford County Jail.
   Vincent Gager, 16, Charles Johnson, 17, and Dennis Richardson,
18, didn't wait to see how the episode turned out, escaping a few
minutes before the show ended Wednesday night, officials said.
   Gager and Johnson were captured within minutes. Richardson
surrendered Thursday.
   In the television show, inmates escaped during a prison concert
by starting a riot and then hiding in the band's equipment truck.
   The inmates at Guilford, who were awaiting trial on charges of
breaking and entering and larceny, asked a guard to bring them a
broom and mop. When she unlocked the door leading to the day room,
they allegedly jumped her, took her keys and locked her in.
   They escaped by using the keys and then jumping 20 feet to a
roof ledge and another 25 feet to the ground, officials said.
   All three are charged with assault on a custodial officer,
escape and malicious damage to county property.
</TEXT>
