<FIRST>r a AM-GEBuilding     07-21 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE Building,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Changing Signs on RCA Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the neon on top to the chiseled granite at
street level, the RCA Building is becoming the GE Building.
   For the last two weeks, workers have been changing signs on the
70-story limestone landmark in the heart of Manhattan to reflect
General Electric's purchase of RCA and its network television
division, NBC, in 1986.
   On Friday, workmen at the 50th Street entrance were removing a
slab of stone with ``RCA Building'' carved into it. Parts of the
red neon letters ``RCA'' facing south and west from the building in
Rockefeller Center have been dismantled.
   They will be replaced by the red neon letters ``GE'' by
September, officials say.
   The building, which holds NBC headquarters, is owned by
Rockefeller Center, but the change needed the approval of the city
Landmarks Preservation Commission.
   That panel also got to help pick the new signs, a design
inspired by an old General Electric logo, said Sue Gould, a partner
in the graphics company that designed the signs.
   ``I guarantee you a lot of people aren't going to notice,'' Ms.
Gould said.
</TEXT>
