<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RiceOutlook     07-21 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rice Outlook,222</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Rice Trade May Reach Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World rice trade is headed for a record this
year, fueled by huge orders from China, Indonesia and India, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   ``China has already purchased approximately 950,000 metric tons
from Thailand and is forecast to import 1.2 million from all
sources by the end of the year, triple the amount imported in
1988,'' the department's Economic Research Service said.
   ``However, it is unclear how or if the current turmoil in China
will affect its short-term rice trade,'' the agency added in its
report.
   U.S. rice exports in calendar 1989 are expected to rise more
than 10 percent from last year, but Thailand is the major
beneficiary of the larger demand. Thailand's total exports are
expected to be at a record of 5.5 million tons, up 15 percent.
   The United States is expected to account for about 19 percent of
this year's global rice trade and Thailand 41 percent, both
unchanged from last year.
   ``China is expected to be a net importer for the first time in
recent history,'' the report said. ``There have been few reports of
(Chinese) exports in the first half of 1989, and China is forecast
to export only 300,000 tons by the end of the year, less than half
the amount it exported in 1988.''
</TEXT>
