<FIRST>r a AM-WanderingPlane     07-21 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wandering Plane,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surgeon Contradicts Mystery Pilot's Theory of Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard flight surgeon who first
treated pilot Thomas Root said he found an infection in Root's
abdomen, suggesting his bullet wound occurred hours before his
plane crashed.
   Capt. James Rahman, who accompanied rescuers sent to pluck the
36-year-old lawyer from Bahamian waters following an 800-mile
flight down the East Coast, said the shooting could have occurred
four to eight hours before the July 13 crash.
   Rahman based the opinion on the extent of peritonitis, an
infection that can be caused by a ruptured intestine.
   Root, who claims he passed out at the controls and rode on
autopilot for nearly four hours until the single-engine Cessna ran
out of fuel, has not been able to explain how he received the
bullet wound.
   ``I do not believe that the ... peritonitis that I observed
could have developed in less than two hours and most likely has
been present for somewhat longer, say four to eight hours,'' Rahman
wrote in a report to the National Transportation Safety Board,
which is investigating the incident.
   Root was treated for shock and blood loss by Rahman, but the
bullet wound was not detected until he was transferred to Memorial
Hospital in Hollywood. Root was listed in satisfactory condition on
Friday.
   Root is expected to remain hospitalized for at least a week to
undergo medical and psychological tests requested by his family,
said his brother, Todd Root.
   Thomas Root claims he blacked out about two hours after leaving
Washington National Airport en route to Rocky Mount, N.C. He
theorizes that a .32-caliber Smith &amp; Wesson revolver in the cabin
fired when he crashed.
   In Miami, safety board regional director Jorge Prellezo said
investigators are reviewing radar data to account for every
movement of Root's plane from takeoff until his final radio
transmission in which he reported trouble breathing.
   Prellezo said there are no plans to salvage the plane, which
sank in mile-deep water.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. attorney's office in Miami is reviewing
reports on an FBI interrogation of Root.
   A source close to the investigation said it probably would
examine whether Root filed false information about his flight or is
liable for search and rescue expenses.
   Todd Root said his brother was distressed by reports of possible
drug links.
   Members of a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration-led task force
collected information about Root after an April 24 seizure at his
airport hangar of a can of ether and about three dozen guns, all
but one legally registered. No investigation was launched based on
the facts gathered, said DEA spokesman Mario Perez.
</TEXT>
