<SECOND>AM-People-Wilson,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Early Plays By August Wilson Will Premiere At St. Paul Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two early one-act plays by August Wilson,
winner of the 1987 Pulitzer Prize for Drama, will debut at the
World Theater in September.
   ``The Coldest Day of the Year'' and ``The Homecoming'' will be
produced by Judy Oliver, Wilson's wife, and directed by Claude
Purdy.
   Both plays date from about 1976, when Wilson was living in
Pittsburgh and beginning to change his focus from poetry to writing
plays. Purdy described The ``Coldest Day of the Year'' as a
transitional piece.
   ``Many of his concerns as a poet are in this one,'' Purdy said.
   ``The Homecoming,'' he said, deals with the same themes as ``Ma
Rainey's Black Bottom,'' the 1984 drama that catapulted Wilson to
national prominence.
   Wilson also is the author of ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,''
``The Piano Lesson,'' and ``Fences.''
