<FIRST>r w AM-US-ArmsLoan     07-21 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arms Loan,274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress to Consider Arms Loan to Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress will decide the fate of a proposed
$170 million government guarantee for a loan to help Colombia buy
arms to fight drug traffickers, the U.S. Export-Import Bank said
Friday.
   Ann Frey, a press officer for the bank, said the loan would be
the first with the bank's support. The usual purpose of its loans
and guarantees is to encourage the sale of U.S. goods in other
countries.
   She said the proposal went to Congress on Wednesday. If no
objection is raised in 25 days it will go through automatically,
she added.
   The bank's announcement said that on July 13 the State
Department decided that the arms sought by Colombia are primarily
for use against narcotics and their sale would be in the interest
of the United States.
   The bank used to be barred from helping the sale of arms. The
Anti-Drug Abuse Act passed last year lifted that ban on sales to
Third World countries. This would be the first loan under the new
law.
   Colombia is a major source of cocaine and marijuana used in this
country. Guerrilla groups fighting the government sometimes ally
themselves with the drug lords and sometimes oppose them. The U.S.
law authorizes help to the sale of arms if they are to be used
primarily against the narcotics trade.
   A guarantee by the government bank would enable commercial banks
to provide Colombia's Ministry of Defense with a lower interest
rate to buy $200 million worth of helicopters, river patrol boats,
aeronautical, transport and communications equipment, arms,
ammunition and other military items.
</TEXT>
