<FIRST>r w AM-Hunts-Taxes     07-21 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunts-Taxes,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bunker Hunt Blames Banks For Partnership At Heart of Tax Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ALso on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oilman Nelson Bunker Hunt blamed his
bank creditors Friday for forcing on him and his brothers a
partnership to handle the repayment of his enormous silver debts, a
deal now at the heart of a $300 million dispute with the Internal
Revenue Service.
   The IRS contends the partnership was a sham.
   Hunt said the banks ``pretty much took over for a while and
dictated'' his affairs after Silver Thursday, the day in late March
1980 when silver prices tumbled from a high of $50 an ounce to $10
an ounce.
   ``The net effect was we didn't have have control over our
business. That's why I'm sitting here in court because the
structure the banks put us in,'' Hunt told U.S. Tax Court Judge
Jules G. Korner III.
   ``You ought to get the money from them,'' Hunt told government
attorney Deborah Butler.
   Hunt is contesting $155 million in 1982 taxes the IRS claims are
due from the dissolution of the partnership he and his brothers set
up after Silver Thursday to repay as much as $2 billion on their
soured silver investments.
   Brother William Herbert Hunt is contesting more than $158
million in 1982 taxes, while Lamar, owner of the Kansas City Chiefs
football team, is contesting $505,377.
   Bunker, the first of the brothers to testify in the non-jury
trial, said he could not recall whether the partnership agreement
between the brothers and the family's flagship firm, Placid Oil
Co., was five or 5,000 pages long.
   ``If it was 5,000 pages, I didn't read it in great detail,'' he
said. ``I won't say I blindly signed it. The deal was explained to
me by the lawyers.''
   But he does remember Walter Fraker, Placid's vice president and
chief financial officer, telling him that the banks ``were calling
all the shots, it was pretty much their party.''
   He also complained that Elvis Mason, then chairman of the board
and chief executive officer of what was then First National Bank of
Dallas, ``was carrying a heavy stroke. He was very dictatorial in
his actions with regard to the loan.''
   Under a March 14, 1980, Federal Reserve directive, banks were
not allowed to make loans on silver investments.
   Placid, however, was able to borrow $1.1 billion from a
consortium of banks in a deal that Mason helped broker. Placid
kicked in $824 million of that loan into the partnership with the
brothers. The Hunts in turn contributed their silver holdings, 2
billion tons of North Dakota coal reserves, gold stocks and other
assets.
   Hunt said he thought the silver contributed to the partnersip
was undervalued at $14.05 an ounce, but said that while he did the
best he could ``I was not in a very strong position.''
   ``I felt it was an unfair deal. I felt it was loaded in favor of
Placid to my detriment,'' Hunt said.
   However, Hunt said his debts were ultimately repaid.
   The IRS contends the partnership was a sham, and that the value
of the coal was only about $16 million in 1980, compared with the
Hunts' claim that it was worth $294 million. When the partnership
dissolved in 1982, the Hunts said was worth $262 million; the IRS
says it was only worth $6.7 million.
</TEXT>
