<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz     07-21 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carmelite Leader Sees 8-Year Delay in Building Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Polish Carmelite nuns said the entire
nation opposes moving a convent from the edge of the wartime
Auschwitz death camp, despite an agreement with Jewish groups to do
so, a magazine reported Friday.
   In Paris, a Jewish religious leader involved in negotiating the
agreement more than two years ago said talks with Roman Catholic
leaders about the convent would be suspended because, he said,
promises had not been kept.
   Under an agreement signed in February 1987, the nuns were to be
moved from their convent to an interfaith center to be built
farther from the camp. Catholic authorities in Poland say there has
been a delay in constructing a new home for the nuns.
   In Warsaw, the official Polish news agency PAP said Friday that
work would begin next year on a convent more than one-third of a
mile from the camp.
   The Rev. Dominik Wider, provincial superior of the Carmelites,
said building a new convent might take eight years.
   He said in a interview with the Catholic monthly 30 Giorni (30
Days) that his order had accepted the church decision to move the
convent, but ``it is evident that whoever wants to move the nuns
must construct another convent adequate for the needs of their
life.''
   In Poland, Wider said, such a project ``could take around eight
years.''
   ``The idea of transferring the nuns from the cloistered convent
of Auschwitz faces the opposition of the entire Polish society,
which is convinced that the convent doesn't harm anyone and that it
is in the correct place: It is outside the walls of the camp but at
the same time borders it,'' he said.
   The magazine, which is to publish the interview in its next
issue, released excerpts Friday.
   Jews consider locating the convent at the former Nazi
concentration camp an intrusion of Christian symbols on a site
where an estimated 2.5 million Jews were put to death.
   Last week, workers beat an American rabbi and six students who
protested on the ground of the convent, where 14 Carmelite nuns
live.
   Theo Klein, former president of the Representative Council of
Jewish Institutions of France, told reporters in Paris he had
notified Cardinal Albert Decourtray, head of the French Conference
of Bishops, of the decision to cease talks on the convent.
   In the letter, Klein said he considered it ``impossible to
pursue the Judeo-Catholic dialogue at the desirable level, while
the concrete facts with which we are confronted are in such
contradiction with the words.''
   Klein and Decourtray played leading roles in negotiating the
agreement to move the nuns.
   Church leaders have said the delay was due to difficulties in
buying land and arranging for construction. Decourtray issued a
statement Friday apologizing for the delay and saying the church
remained committed to moving the convent as soon as possible.
   In its report Friday, PAP said the first part of the land had
been bought in early July, ``so that, having submitted plans and
having received permission, work can start in the beginning of next
year.''
</TEXT>
