<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas 1stLd-Writethru a0638 07-21 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Says Lucas' Opponents Risk Relationship with Department</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 1 graf new from Conyers' spokesman after 3rd graf pvs,
``The pressure; inserts 2 grafs further after 18th graf pvs, Lucas' views.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The civil rights movement risks losing its
``cordial relationship'' with Attorney General Dick Thornburgh by
opposing William Lucas's nomination to head the Justice
Department's anti-discrimination unit, the agency's chief spokesman
said Friday.
   Thornburgh's spokesman, David Runkel, also charged that Rep.
John Conyers, D-Mich., buckled under the pressure of civil rights
lobbyists when he withdrew his endorsement of Lucas to be assistant
attorney general for civil rights.
   ``The pressure on Mr. Conyers from the civil rights community
was enormous,'' Runkel said, a day after Conyers announced he no
longer supported Lucas, a 61-year-old black Republican from
Michigan.
   Not so, said a Conyers spokesman, who told a reporter his boss
had made his decision ``in the loneliness of his own conscience.''
   Despite the loss of a key Lucas supporter and the prospect of a
close vote on the Judiciary Committee, Runkel said, ``I feel
comfortable we have the votes to get the guy confirmed.''
   Asked if winning a possibly tough Senate fight was worth the
political bloodshed, Runkel said:
   ``I think you should address it to the civil rights groups. They
are the ones who have the most to lose.''
   ``They have stated their views, what they have to lose, it seems
to me, is a cordial relationship with the attorney general and with
the head of the civil rights division,'' Runkel said when asked if
his statement could be interpreted as a threat to Lucas' opponents.
   The White House continued to express its support for Lucas.
   ``We think he's an excellent candidate,'' said presidential
press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Thornburgh, vacationing in New England, said in a statement
issued by his office that during his testimony, ``Bill Lucas ably
demonstated his ability to serve as assistant attorney general in
charge of the Civil Rights Division.''
   ``In keeping with President Bush's commitment in this area, Mr.
Lucas pledged to serve as the administration's lead official in the
close monitoring of the impact of recent Supreme Court decisions on
civil rights.''
   Thornburgh said Lucas ``accurately reflected my views when he
said he would `lead the charge' in seeking legislative changes if
these cases do, in fact, hamper effective civil rights
enforcement.''
   The vote on Lucas' nomination in the Judiciary Committee is
expected to be very close and along party lines. Democrats have an
8-6 margin on the panel, which has not scheduled a vote on the
nomination.
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., said
Thursday he is inclined to vote against Lucas after hearing his
testimony.
   Lucas' defense of a series of Supreme Court decisions that civil
rights activists say will make it harder to win discrimination
suits prompted Conyers to return to the Judiciary Committee on
Thursday to withdraw his support.
   Runkel said the pressure on Conyers to change his position
``began in the hallway outside the hearing room'' after the
Michigan congressman had urged Lucas' confirmation on Wednesday.
   Conyers, who had introduced Lucas as someone ``deeply committed
to the vigorous enforcement of the civil rights laws, returned to
the committee Thursday and said he was ``frankly astounded'' by
Lucas' defense of the recent Supreme Court decisions.
   Lucas' views on the civil rights policy were well known to
Conyers, Runkel said, adding that nobody could expect an
administration nominee to depart from President Bush's policies.
   But a spokesman for Conyers, Michael Hill, said that Lucas, in
his discussions with Conyers in the months before the hearing,
``had never expressed to the congressmen that he thought those
decisions were sound.''
   ``A contention that Mr. Conyers was under intensive or enormous
pressure from the civil rights community following his testimony is
just not true,'' Hill said. ``That was a decision Mr. Conyers made
in the loneliness of his own conscience without any pressure from
anyone.''
   Lucas, echoing Thornburgh, had promised to closely monitor the
impact of the Supreme Court decisions on pending discrimination
cases and press for legislative changes if those rulings hurt the
cause of civil rights.
   The defection of Conyers has buoyed Lucas' opponents.
   ``I think the nomination is in serious trouble based on the
momentum of the last 48 hours,'' said Ralph G. Neas, executive
director of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, a coalition
of groups opposing the nomination.
</TEXT>
