<FIRST>u w AM-Carter-Ethiopia     07-21 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carter-Ethiopia,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Will Mediate 28-Year-Old Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter will travel to
Ethiopia next week to serve as a mediator between the government
and Eritrean rebels, a U.S. diplomat said Friday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen said Carter had been
accepted by both the Marxist government of Haile Mengistu Mariam
and by the Eritrean rebels who have been warring against the
government for 28 years in one of Africa's longest-running civil
wars.
   Cohen told reporters a dialogue between the two sides would make
it easier for the United States to improve relations with
Mengistu's government.
   Cohen said he himself would be traveling to Addis Ababa in the
near future to discuss improving relations, which have been
strained since the early 1908s, when Mengistu shifted his country's
alliances to the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets have been pressing Mengistu to negotiate with the
rebels and end the costly war in an effort to cut Soviet aid to
Ethiopia. The Soviets have said that further military assistance
will not be forthcoming, Western diplomats have said.
   Soviet officials met in London last week with Eritrean leaders
to urge them to negotiate with Mengistu's government, Cohen said.
   Carter visited Ethiopia earlier this year and met with Mengistu.
In recent years, the former president has been a mediator and
observer in foreign conflicts, most recently heading a U.S.
delegation that observed the disputed elections in Panama.
</TEXT>
