<FIRST>u w AM-Shanker     07-21 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shanker,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shanker: Only the Strong Schools Should Survive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public schools should be forced to compete in
a free market-type system, with losers closing down and winners
taking over their facilities, teachers union leader Albert Shanker
said Friday.
   Shanker, president of the 710,000-member American Federation of
Teachers, laid out his vision in a speech to 3,000 AFT members
attending a conference on education reform.
   He depicted a competitive model in which teachers play a large
role in running schools as the only alternative to a host of
options even less attractive to teachers _ among them tuition tax
credits and state and private takeovers of weak schools, such as
Boston University's oversight of the Chelsea, Mass., district.
   ``We do not have a choice of keeping what we have now,'' Shanker
said. ``We're either going to jump while we feel the water getting
warm or we're going to end up getting boiled.''
   Shanker proposed a high-stakes national education competition
with substantial financial rewards for schools and teachers that
make marked improvements and shutdowns of schools that can't do the
job.
   Integral to the plan would be incentives, flexibility,
accountability, federal assessments, parental freedom to choose
their child's school and a transfer of money from administrative to
instructional functions.
   Shanker suggested that President Bush invest $500 million for
five years to earn interest, then offer the money to teachers at
the schools that have made the most progress.
   ``The goal is to make each school a team, trying to bring about
the maximum possible improvement,'' Shanker said. He said winners
would include the same percentage of schools from every level of
achievement so weaker schools wouldn't have to compete against top
schools.
   Shanker also said Bush should create an assessment board to
determine whether students at a school could ``read a decent book,
write something worthwhile, solve a math problem or engage in
discussion of an important national issue.''
   Bush and Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos have been promoting
competition in education, saying it can be achieved by letting
parents choose their children's public schools. Cavazos has said
repeatedly that bad schools should close down if they can't do the
job.
   But neither has gone as far as Shanker, who on Friday compared
the current system to the Soviet Union's planned, top-down economy.
   Any competitive plan would have to be ratified by the local
union and board of education, Shanker said, and ``there's no point
in doing it if the same rules and regulations are in effect. You
have to set the schools free to do it their own way.''
   ``Ideally, this should also have losers,'' Shanker added, with
schools that fail shut down and turned over to more successful
schools.
   Shanker also proposed a national certificate for students who
want recognition for academic excellence, saying it would help
educators determine national guidelines for what students ought to
know in various subject areas.
   And he said he will urge employers to consider courses, grades,
attendance and teacher recommendations rather than a simple diploma
when they hire kids out of high school.
   ``We should have a system in which every student who is not
bound for college knows that his effort, habits of work and actual
accomplishments in school will mean the difference between being
the first or last to get the job and ... getting a job that pays
more and leads to something,'' Shanker said.
   Shanker predicted that if the administration does not entirely
embrace his competitive plan, there will be members of Congress,
private foundations, school districts, governors and businesses who
will pick up on it.
   ``I very strongly believe that in one form or another, in one
place or another, this is going to happen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
