<DOCNO> AP890721-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Disability     07-21 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disability,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Disability Income Limits Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, in a move to promote
self-sufficiency for the disabled, on Friday proposed increasing by
two-thirds the amount a person can earn and still receive federal
disability benefits.
   The change, proposed by the Department of Health and Human
Services, would take effect in January 1990.
   ``Federal programs should not perpetuate dependency,'' said a
statement issued by President Bush's press secretary, Marlin
Fitzwater.
   The change would ``provide an incentive for the 5.2 million
workers on the disability rolls to take significant steps toward
work and economic independence,'' Fitzwater said.
   The regulation would increase from $300 to $500 per month the
amount that could be earned by individuals receiving Social
Security Disability Insurance or Supplemental Security Income (SSI)
benefits and who are not blind.
   The allowed earnings level for blind beneficiaries is set by law
and is now $740 per month. This would not be changed by the
regulation.
   The proposed regulation also would change the trigger for the
``trial work period,'' during which a disability insurance
recipient continues to receive benefits after returning to work.
Currently, a recipient enters a ``trial work period'' when he earns
more than $75 per month or works more than 15 hours per week. That
would increase under the regulation to $200 or 40 hours.
   An SSI recipient's benefits are reduced by $1 for every $2 in
earnings over $65 per month. When the recipient's earnings reach
the current $300 per month ``substantial gainful activity'' level,
benefits can continue under certain circumstances. Under the
proposed regulation, benefits would continue at least until the
recipient's earnings reached $500 per month.
   The administration said the change would allow up to 71,000
people to retain or regain benefits under the two programs. The
cost in fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1, would be $60 million,
with the cost rising to $197 million in fiscal 1994.
   About 3 million blind and disabled workers receive SSI benefits.
The Disability Insurance program pays benefits to 2.83 million
workers and 1.24 million spouses and children of disabled workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
