<FIRST>u a AM-NOW-Convention     07-21 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NOW-Convention,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Group to Fashion Pro-Abortion Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Organization for Women President
Molly Yard pledged Friday the group will launch a nationwide
campaign to gain support for a woman's right to have an abortion.
   NOW's membership has grown in recent weeks as women, angered by
the U.S. Supreme Court's July 3 ruling on abortion, join ranks in a
surge of activism, Ms. Yard said. Membership has grown from about
160,000 last year to its current 200,000.
   The Supreme Court ruled that states could restrict access to
abortions.
   ``People are angry,'' Ms. Yard said as NOW's three-day annual
conference began at the Cincinnati Convention Center. ``They are
angry that someone would come into their lives, into so personal a
decision as when, and if, to have children.''
   Outside the convention center, a dozen abortion opponents
picketed with signs showing remains of aborted fetuses. Pam Smith
of Cincinnati, one of the pickets, also carried her 4-month-old
son, Zachariah.
   Asked why she protested NOW's meeting, Ms. Smith said, ``Because
God gave us life in our womb. It's a blessing, and they're
murdering them.''
   Ms. Yard said NOW will work to elect politicians sympathetic to
its views, and will oppose lawmakers who don't.
   ``Have you watched politicians running for cover ever since July
3?'' she said. ``We intend, on the national and state level, to
fight those who would deny women the freedom to control their
reproductive lives and who would deny us equal rights under the
Constitution. ... That is the message of the women's movement.''
   NOW lawyers are working on a proposal, which could take the form
of a bill or constitutional amendment, that would prohibit states
from interfering with women's rights to have abortions, Ms. Yard
said. The organization hopes to have the proposal introduced in
Congress in September.
   Ms. Yard said NOW will work against President Bush because the
group regards him as being an opponent of women's rights.
   ``His position denying women the right to control their
reproductive lives will be the main issue of his re-election
campaign if he chooses to run in 1992,'' Ms. Yard said. ``We will
make this the issue of the 1990s.''
   In Washington, a White House spokeswoman declined to respond to
Ms. Yard's comments.
   NOW leaders expect about 1,000 to attend the conference, which
offers workshops on issues including sexual harassment and legal
rights, lesbian rights task forces, feminist spirituality, the
Equal Rights Amendment, the homeless and eating disorders.
   Members planned a march and rally for women's rights Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
