<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Will Be First UN Election Monitoring in Sovereign Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 160 U.N. representatives will
observe the Nicaraguan elections Feb. 25 in the world
organization's first mission to monitor a vote in a sovereign
nation, officials said Friday.
   S. Iqbal Riza, head of a U.N. mission sent to the Central
American nation, said all previous U.N. monitoring projects have
been in colonial countries in transition to independence.
   The Organization of American States also will observe the
Nicaraguan election. Nicaragua requested the monitoring by both
organizations.
   Nicaragua's last presidential and legislative elections were
held Nov. 19, 1984. The leftist Sandinista National Liberation
Front overthrew the pro-American government of the late President
Anastasio Somoza in July 1979.
