<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1917EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HemingwayStamp     07-21 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hemingway Stamp,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hemingway Honored With Stamp In His Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAK PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest Hemingway once called his hometown
a place of ``broad lawns and narrow minds,'' but residents still
turned out Friday on the writer's 90th birthday for a ceremony
unveiling a new stamp in his honor.
   About 200 people gathered at the U.S. Post Office to watch color
guards whirl flags and to hear speeches as the stamp was unveiled.
   The stamp made its debut earlier in the week in Key West, Fla.,
where the novelist spent a significant portion of his life.
   Born in Oak Park in 1899, Hemingway lived in the western Chicago
suburb until he was 18. He committed suicide in 1961 at the age of
61.
   ``I've been sitting here wondering if Ernest was alive, if he
would be here today,'' said A.E. Hotchner, author of ``Papa
Hemingway'' and one of Hemingway's close friends.
   ``Yes, I think he would be here, for all that's been said about
his feelings for Oak Park,'' Hotchner said. ``It is deeply
ingrained in him. He would have made a lousy speech, but he would
have been moved.''
   The rumor that Hemingway hated his hometown is a myth, said
Scott Schwar, chairman of the Ernest Hemingway Foundation.
   ``The inner real Hemingway was shaped in Oak Park,'' Schwar said
in a telephone interview.
   In the new stamp, a bearded Hemingway standing in front of
antelopes in Africa stares out of giant posters. He is the seventh
in the literary arts series of stamps that also has featured John
Steinbeck, William Faulkner and T.S. Eliot.
   Hemingway's son, Patrick, friends and community leaders received
special books of stamps. Some 160 million Hemingway stamps were
sent this week to post offices across the country, said Jerry Lee,
regional postmaster general.
   Hemingway's early writing can be found in an Oak Park High
School literary magazine, the Tabula. He imitated famous writers of
his time, such as Ring Lardner, Hotchner said.
   ``I remember in high school Ernest took me to the third floor of
his house,'' said 91-year-old Lewis Clarahan, Hemingway's longtime
friend. ``He pulled out a sheet from his typewriter and showed me a
story he wrote. I think it was his first.''
   ``I don't remember if it was good, but Ernest sure thought it
was,'' he said, laughing.
</TEXT>
