<FIRST>r w AM-BlackCatholics     07-21 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Catholics,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breakaway Priest Says Catholic University Discriminates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black priest suspended by the Roman Catholic
Church for starting a breakaway black congregation said Friday that
a major church-run university has discriminated against blacks.
   The Rev. George A. Stallings Jr. said in a statement that there
are only 20 blacks enrolling as freshmen at Washington's Catholic
University of America next fall. In all, about 1,000 students are
expected to begin studies there.
   Stallings also criticized the university for the ``meager
representation'' of 10 blacks among its faculty of about 350 and
said it lacked courses on black literature, music or religion.
   ``Such facts not only demonstrate a record of blatant exclusion;
they are a clear example of intellectual dishonesty of the most
decided kind,'' Stallings said.
   The university is under the aegis of the Archdiocese of
Washington.
   Stallings, 41, was suspended by the archdiocese after he said
Mass in defiance of Cardinal James A. Hickey on July 2.
   Stallings has said the Catholic Church has failed its nearly two
million black parishioners and has charged the church with racism.
   Catholic University said it is an equal opportunity employer and
has established special scholarships for minority students.
   ``We are making serious efforts to recruit black faculty members
and students but, as everyone knows, applicants with appropriate
credentials are limited and in great demand by all institutions,''
the university's public affairs office said in a statement.
   The university did not dispute Stallings' figures for black
students or faculty members.
   Stallings' statement was part of a letter he sent Friday to
Bishop John Ricard of Baltimore. Ricard was one of the signers of a
call for unity issued by the nation's 13 black bishops a week ago.
   The black bishops' statement said in part, ``We sincerely hope
(Stallings' followers) are not commingling personal dissapointment,
individually felt frustrations and personal anger under the banner
of racism. Racism is a sin which the church must address. It is too
serious an issue to be used as a cover for selfish concerns.''
   Stallings responded:
   ``The glaring fact that you seem to ignore is that what
disappointment or discouragement we feel is due to the reality of
racism; and, even more importantly, is the result of the church's
apparent inability or unwillingness to take radical steps to
transform an otherwise racist institution into a church that is
truly inclusive and universal.''
   Stallings maintained that his four-week-old Imani Temple is not
separate from the Catholic church.
   ``I did not depart from the church nor its mission or mandates;
rather, the church abandoned its zeal and energies in the pursuit
of justice and the transformation of our society,'' Stallings wrote.
   Ricard was out of town and had not seen Stallings' letter, a
spokeswoman for Ricard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
