<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Plane     07-21 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Plane,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hydraulic System Fails on Pan Am Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pan Am jet carrying a flight crew but no
passengers diverted to Heathrow Airport on Friday night after the
pilot detected a fault in one of the hydraulic systems, the airline
reported.
   The Boeing 727 was traveling from Frankfurt, West Germany, to
New York via Keflavik, Iceland, on a routine flight to transport
the aircraft, said Alan Loflin, a Pan Am spokesman in New York.
   He said the pilot reported the fault over the Atlantic and
returned to London for repairs.
   Loflin said the aircraft had two other hydraulic systems that
could be used to control it, and even if they had failed it could
have been steered manually. The incident was ``nothing close to an
emergency,'' he said.
   Fire engines and emergency services lined Heathrow's main runway
as the jet touched down, but Loflin said emergency service had not
been requested.
   A United Airlines DC-10 lost its tail engine, then its hydraulic
system, and crashed Wednesday at Sioux City, Iowa, while trying to
make an emergency landing. At least 109 people were killed and 184
survived, officials said.
</TEXT>
