<FIRST>u w AM-FDA-NutritionalPowder     07-21 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Nutritional Powder,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Warns Hospitals of Damgerous Nutritional Powder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Friday
warned hospitals nationwide against using a nutritional powder that
contains a potentially fatal amount of potassium.
   The product is called Nutrex Aminex and is made by the Nutrex
Corp. of Sunnyvale, Calif. The powder is mixed with water and
administered by mouth or by gastric tube to patients who can't eat
ordinary meals.
   The FDA took the action after a report of a patient at the
Veterans Administration Medical Center in Nashville, Tenn.,
developed heart arrhythmias and was found to have high blood
potassium. The patient recovered when taken off Aminex.
   The agency said FDA and VA tests later showed the Aminex powder
contained high amounts of potassium. Too much of the nutrient can
be fatal.
   The FDA said it has not been able to obtain a list of
institutions that bought the product. The agency issued a general
warning in an effort to reach all hospitals.
   It said the packets of powder are unflavored or flavored
strawberry, vanilla or orange. They are labeled: ``Nutritionally
complete elemental diet for oral or tube feeding _ Nutrex Aminex
Nutritional Powder.''
</TEXT>
