<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-21 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Continues in Southeast</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms in the southeastern United States on
Friday hit in clusters from northwest Florida to the southern
Appalachians and flash flooding continued.
   Officials using dogs and a state police helicopter searched
along a northern Virginia creek for signs of a car, carrying as
many as three people, that washed off a bridge in a flash flood.
   At least 10 cars were swept off the bridge shortly after
midnight Thursday when Goose Creek rose an estimated 13 feet in 30
minutes. One woman was drowned and three people were rescued by
boat from the tops of their vehicles.
   Flash flood warnings were posted Friday in Nevada and North
Carolina.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also over coastal sections of the
Carolinas, southern Illinois, eastern sections of the middle
Mississippi Valley, western sections of the lower Ohio Valley, West
Texas and along a cold front crossing the northern high Plains.
   It was fair across most of the rest of the nation, with sunny
skies over much of the central third of the nation and in the
Pacific Northwest.
   Strong southerly winds boosted temperatures into the lower 90s
in the northern Plains region. Brisk northerly winds accompanied
clouds and drizzle over parts of the middle Mississippi Valley and
kept afternoon readings in the 60s.
   Temperatures in western parts of the nation varied from the 60s
in the Pacific Northwest to 100 degrees or above in the
southwestern deserts.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Fort Ord near Monterey, Calif., to 104 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   The nation's low Friday morning was 39 degrees at Houlton, Maine.
   Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Atlantic Coast states to the southern half
of the Great Plains region and over the Rocky Mountain and Plateau
region. Showers and thunderstorms were expected to be most numerous
in the lower Missouri Valley, in northern Arizona and from southern
Mississippi and southeastern Louisiana to Florida and southern
Georgia. Sunny skies were expected across most of the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures were expected to reach 90 degrees from northern
Florida to eastern Virginia and the Delmarva Peninsula.
Temperatures were expected above 90 from the northern Plains to the
Great Basin and central Plateau and from south central Texas to the
southwestern deserts. Readings above 100 degrees were predicted for
southern Arizona, southern Nevada and southern and central
California. High temperatures were expected in the 70s along the
Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
