<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-Chad 2ndLd-Writethru a0693 07-21 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Chad, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0693,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rivals Libya, Chad Meet to Settle Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with no agreement reached; pickup
8th graf pvs, `It also...' ^By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAMAKO, Mali (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi of Libya and President
Hissene Habre of Chad, who have been enemies for years, met to
settle their border dispute Friday, but the talks broke off without
an agreement.
   The presidents of four other African nations who had been
mediating the talks left the meeting without comment.
   Gadhafi and Habri also declined to comment to reporters who had
been waiting in a room decorated with banners honoring the expected
``Bamako Declaration.''
   It was not immediately known whether more talks would take place.
   The negotiations began on Thursday and marked the first meeting
between Gadhafi and Habre in seven years.
   Officials of two of the observer nations initially told
reporters Friday that the signing of the agreement was assured. By
late evening, however, when the talks continued beyong schedule, it
became clear obstacles had developed.
   The sources said Habre objected to several points in the
proposed agreement, including a section calling for immediate
return of war prisoners. He also demanded a change of language to
remove any ambiguity about plans for the International Court of
Justice to settle the question of the Aouzou border region, the
sources said.
   Habre was under pressure to accept the agreement without
changes, one official said, because ``it may be difficult to get
Gadhafi to return to a meeting like this again.'' The official's
delegation is generally favorable to Chad's position in the
conflict.
   Gadhafi, Habre and the presidents of Gabon, Algeria and Mali
went into a small room Friday afternoon, tightly guarded by
soldiers. Gen. Ibraham Babangida, the Nigerian president, joined
them later.
   Under the proposed agreement, as drafted by officials of Mali
and Algeria, Chad and Libya would try to settle the Aouzou border
issue by political means, meaning negotiations within the
Organization of African Unity, and take it to the International
Court of Justice if those attempts failed.
   It also calls for a treaty of friendship, a pledge by each not
to attack the other and creation of an OAU observer force to
stabilize a year-old truce.
   All prisoners would be repatriated. Chad is said to hold at
least 2,000 Libyans, but Libya says it has returned all captured
Chadians.
   Habre has consistently refused to return the prisoners until the
signing of a peace treaty.
   He and Gadhafi met and shook hands Thursday night, then held a
three-hour meeting that ended at about 1 a.m. Friday.
   Before talks resumed Friday afternoon, Gadhafi and presidents
Omar Bongo of Gabon, Moussa Traore of Mali and Chadli Bendjedid of
Algeria attended prayers at Bamako's main mosque. Gadhafi, waving
clenched fists, plunged into a crowd of young people who were
screaming his name.
   Since Gadhafi gained power in 1969, he has supported several
anti-government groups in Chad, Libya's southern neighbor. They
included Habre's own faction when he was a guerrilla leader.
   After a Libyan invasion, government troops and allied French
soldiers drove Libyan forces out in 1987. France, the colonial
power until independence in 1960, has about 1,500 soldiers in Chad
to support Habre.
   Libya has kept its foothold in the Aouzou Strip. The
45,600-square-mile border area, thought to be rich in uranium, has
been in dispute for decades.
   Last month, Habre accused Libya of preparing an attack from
Sudan, Chad's eastern neighbor, with Chadian dissidents. Sudan and
Libya denied the charges.
</TEXT>
