<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-United Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Disaster Unlikely to Harm United's Resurgence in Long Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `UAL stock...' to UPDATE with closing stock price,
Picks Up 7th graf pvs, `One day...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers may shun flying United Airlines
briefly, but investors are likely to stay aboard the nation's
second-largest airline, accepting accidents as a hazard of the
industry, analysts say.
   The deadly crash of United Flight 232 in an Iowa cornfield
Wednesday followed an 18-month period of aggressive recovery by
United, moving boldly to recover its long-held ranking as the
industry leader.
   The DC-10 disaster will likely have little impact on the
resurgence of UAL Corp., United's parent, analysts said.
   ``Usually for a short period of time there is customer avoidance
of a carrier that has had an incident,'' said Robert J. Joedicke,
an industry analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
``This tends to wear off fairly promptly,'' he said.
   And United shareholders will be ``more concerned with the
tragedy of the crash than about the price of their stock,'' said
analyst Robert Decker of Duff &amp; Phelps in Chicago. ``Investors
realize that a crash is part of the business risk of an airline.''
   UAL stock closed down $1.25 at $170.75 in New York Stock
Exchange trading Friday. The stock lost $1.50 on Thursday.
   One day before the accident, United Chairman Stephen Wolf
announced the airline was seeking federal approval for several
trans-Atlantic routes in a bid to make the carrier, with its
extensive Pacific coverage, ``a truly global airline.''
   That move, and Wolf's announcement in April that the airline was
placing a $15.4 billion order with Boeing for new planes, marked
the success of the simple battle plan he outlined when he came
aboard the troubled carrier in December 1987: Quality service would
lead to improved earnings, which would allow the airline to expand
its fleet and operations.
   The past five years brought to United's parent company a name
change that was quickly revoked, an identity crisis and a bitter,
month-long walkout by the airline's pilots and flight attendants.
   But the hectic period in United's 62-year history ended with the
company under new leadership and proudly opening its home-base
terminal at O'Hare International Airport _ a frosted
glass-and-steel showcase.
   The price of UAL stock has climbed in recent weeks, along with
that of other airlines after the announced takeover of Northwest
Airlines' parent NWA Inc. by an international investors' group.
   Analysts say United's 80 percent ownership of its 408-plane
fleet _ the highest rate among major carriers, many of whom lease
their planes _ enhances its investment appeal.
   Wolf's announcement that United had placed orders and options
for as many as 370 planes is central to the airline's bid to
reclaim its rank as the nation's largest domestic carrier, a title
recently assumed by American Airlines, said United spokeswoman Sue
Moss.
   Wolf also announced first-quarter revenues rose almost 12
percent to $2.3 billion and profits from continuing operations more
than doubled to $65.4 million _ ``our fifth consecutive quarter of
superb earnings and the best first-quarter of United's history.''
   In contrast, for 10 lean years starting in 1977, Chicago-based
UAL reported profits just four times and increased its fleet only
slightly.
   ``They certainly have done an excellent turnaround,'' Joedicke
said. ``They're moving in a positive direction under the management
of Mr. Wolf. ... in the year and a half he's been there he's
achieved great strides.''
   Wolf was brought in after UAL's brief, ill-fated run as Allegis
Corp.
   The name change came in February 1987, during the tenure of
former chairman Richard Ferris, who envisioned a travel services
conglomerate combining air travel, car rental, hotels and a
reservations system. But big losses produced pressure for change
from major shareholders.
   Ferris resigned four months after the name change, and new
management moved quickly to restore the UAL name and dump the
non-airline businesses.
   Before Ferris departed, his expansion plans prompted a $4.1
billion bid for United from the union representing its pilots.
   The offer still stands, though United's pilots are ``pleased
that the airline is independent once again,'' said Hank Krakowski
of the Air Line Pilots Association.
   United was the target of a bitter 29-day walkout by the pilots
and the Association of Flight Attendants in 1985. The carrier won
the day, imposing two-tier contracts with lower pay scales for new
hires.
   The provision is the key obstacle in United's on-again,
off-again talks with the flight attendants, whose contract expired
in 1987, and is a major issue for the pilots, whose pact expired
last year.
</TEXT>
