<FIRST>u w AM-HUDFirings 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Firings, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0714,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Officials Told They'll Be Dismissed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs background, other cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three officials of the Housing and Urban
Development Department's troubled Washington field office were told
Friday they will fired in 30 days and a fourth will be told next
Tuesday, HUD officials disclosed.
   These are the first people dismissed as part of the department's
investigation of mismanagement and cronyism during the Reagan
administration.
   The Washington field office was the base of operations of escrow
agent Marilyn Harrell, who became known as ``Robin HUD'' after she
confessed to diverting $5.5 million of the department's money to
charities.
   The four officials were placed on leave in June, then given
temporary assignments at headquarters when their leaves expired
earlier this month.
   They are Margaret White, former head of the office; Robert B.
Warner, director of housing management; Charles W. Womble, loan
specialist; and Everett Rothschild, head of property disposition.
   An audit of the office found that lax financial and management
controls allowed agents like Ms. Harrell to delay transfers of
funds or not make them at all. Auditors have estimated the office
is missin a total of $10 million.
   The officials, who made known the dismissal notices on condition
they not be identified, said all but Rothschild were given letters
informing them they will be dismissed in 30 days unless they can
refute charges of mismanagement against them.
   Rothschild is out of town and will be given his letter on
Tuesday, the officials said.
   Ms. White had wide support among Washington politicians and many
protested when she was placed on leave. The District Urban League
also wrote Kemp a protest letter.
   In a speech Friday to agency workers at the swearing in of HUD's
new general counsel, Francis Keating, Secretary Jack Kemp repeated
his pledge to root out fraud and mismanagement.
   Kemp told the workers he would have ``zero tolerance'' for
mismanagement and said any employees who felt they could not live
up to higher standards should quit.
   Still pending is a decision on the fate of the head of HUD's New
York regional office, Geraldine McGann, who is on leave pending an
investigation of her performance.
   The Commerce Department last week also said R. Hunter Cushing, a
former ranking HUD official, had taken a leave pending the outcome
of the various investigations of HUD.
</TEXT>
