<FIRST>u w AM-DC-10Crash-Engines 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Engines, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0680,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-10 Engine Attachement Had Repair Work Day Before Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 12: `Early Friday,'' with hydraulic line report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attachment to the engine that may have
exploded in flight aboard United Airlines Flight 232 was repaired a
day before the plane crashed in Iowa, but the head investigator
said Friday he had no indication the work was related the engine's
failure.
   Government records show that DC-10s with CF6-6 engines have had
six previous engine failures in which damage extended beyond the
engine.
   The builder, General Electric Co., and a Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman said the CF6-6, which is used only on
tri-jet DC-10s, has a good performance record.
   The rear engine that investigators say may have exploded in
flight and disabled hydraulic flight control systems before the
United DC-10 crashed Wednesday at Sioux City had been on the
15-year-old plane for about nine months, said a spokesman for Rep.
James Oberstar, D-Minn, who heads a House aviation subcommittee.
   Oberstar obtained information about the plane from a United
Airlines vice president.
   Airline spokesman Herb Gardner in Chicago said all maintenance
records concerning the aircraft, one of 56 DC-10s in United's
fleet, had been turned over to the National Transportation Safety
Board. ``We just simply do not provide any of that information once
its been given to the board,'' he said.
   A spokesman for Oberstar said the congressman had not learned
whether the repair work done on the engine had anything to do with
the system that failed.
   Safety board member Jim Burnett, who is supervising
investigators in Sioux City, confirmed that unspecified repairs
were performed on the aircraft's tail engine on Tuesday. ``We have
no indication at this time that that was something that could have
affected the course of the accident,'' he said.
   He said the work was on the plane's pneumatic system, which uses
excess air pressure generated by the giant jet engine to power the
aircraft's air-conditioning system. The pneumatic system is
attached to the engine.
   Burnett acknowledged Friday that pieces of metal spewing from a
disintegrating rear engine could have caused the small holes found
in the horizontal stabilizer and could have severed hydraulic lines
in the tail, but he said investigators were far from concluding
what caused the crash.
   Burnett said preliminary findings showed that the horizontal
stabilizer, the small wing-like structures on each side of the
tail, had several holes and the hydraulic system had lost all
fluid. The hydraulic system is routed through the tail and allows
the pilot to manipulate wing and tail controls.
   Early Friday evening, Burnett said examination of the hydraulic
lines showed two were severed cleanly and the third suffered such
impact damage it was impossible to tell whether it had been cut.
   The rear engine was either brand new or newly rebuilt when it
was installed last October, said Jim Berard, Oberstar's spokesman.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said CF6-6 engines have been the
subject of seven ``airworthiness directives'' since they went into
service in 1972. ``This doesn't mean there is a problem but that a
problem was solved and corrected,'' he said. Such directives
ordinarily order airliners to make modifications on the engines or
in procedures for maintaining them.
   The most recent order was in late 1988 and involved replacement
of an engine shaft after 17,600 flights, Farrar said.
   The GE engine originally was built lighter than engines made by
competitors, with relatively thin fan blades, but the design was
changed because the blades tended to break up, a United Airlines
official disclosed after a 1979 Chicago DC-10 crash that killed 274
people. That crash was blamed on faulty maintenance procedures.
   Farrar said the CF6-6 engines have a good shutdown record, with
one automatic or pilot-directed shutdown for about every 30,000
flying hours, a normal record for such an engine.
   Airliners must be able to fly with one engine out. Farrar said
the three-engined DC-10 also could fly with two engine failures but
if that were necessary, the strain on the third engine might damage
it.
   David Lane, spokesman for General Electric's aircraft engine
division, said 469 of the CF6-6 engines are in service. Only one
flight in 2,000 has been delayed or cancelled because of a CF6-6
problem, he said.
   ``That's an admirable record,'' he said.
   Lane said the company would have no comment on specifics
involved in the Souix City crash investigation.
</TEXT>
