<DOCNO> AP890721-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Spy-Article     07-21 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy-Article,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloch Warned of Little U.S. Influence on Common Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix S. Bloch, the diplomat being
investigated by the FBI and the State Department as a possible
Soviet spy, wrote a recent article warning fellow diplomats that
the United States has little ability to influence the European
Common Market.
   Bloch's article appears in the July-August edition of the
Foreign Service Journal, the magazine of the Foreign Service
Association, the professional organization for American diplomats.
   His contribution, entitled ``The European Community,'' sketches
what he called the ``intricate and enigmatic'' relationships,
emphasizing trade, of the United States with the institutions of
the Common Market.
   He said Americans had three common misconceptions about Europe:
that trade barriers within Europe will be removed in 1992, that the
community is just a place where member countries meet and has no
power itself, and that the community has no political dimension.
   In trade, he said, ``both sides seem trapped by their threats,''
unable to negotiate without deadlines for carrying out threats.
Since it is difficult to get a multi-member body to agree on an
initiative, ``both sides have come to expect the United States
always to be the initiator of trade negotiations, the first to make
a proposal and the one expected to make the last concession.''
   ``It must be recognized that the nature of our relations is to a
large extent dictated by the state of the evolving community,''
Bloch wrote.
   ``We can neither force nor delay the pace of European
unification and can deal with (Common Market) institutions only to
the extent that the community agrees that they should deal with us.
Decisions being made in Europe are very important to the United
States, but our ability to influence them is small.''
</TEXT>
