<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0948</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chairman Alan Greenspan said the Federal
Reserve has shifted its emphasis from fighting inflation to
avoiding a recession, a signal that the central bank likely will
continue to cautiously push down interest rates.
   ``Recent developments suggest that the balance of risks may have
shifted somewhat away from greater inflation,'' Greenspan told a
House Banking subcommittee Thursday. `` ... What we seek to avoid
is an unnecessary and destructive recession.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meeting deficit-reduction targets in fiscal
1991 without a tax increase or a cutback in Social Security
benefits would require a 10 percent across-the-board cut in federal
spending, the Congressional Budget Office said.
   The $74 billion to $88 billion in spending cuts needed to meet
the fiscal 1991 defict target of $64 billion without raising taxes
would likely force the economy into a recession unless the Federal
Reserve Board further loosens its reins on inflation substantially,
the House Budget Committee was told Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should not ban the controversial
practice of dual trading _ where brokers trade for themselves and
their customers _ from the nation's futures exchanges, a House
subcommittee was told.
   Critics say dual trading allows brokers to take care of their
own needs first, but banning it outright ``would be dangerous,''
said Leo Melamed, chairman of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's
executive committee.
   The chairman of the Chicago Board of Trade, the world's oldest
and largest futures exchange, also opposed a ban on dual trading
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm-state senators asked for federal
regulators to investigate a recent emergency order by the Chicago
Board of Trade to avoid a squeeze in the soybean futures market.
   The lawmakers sought the review by the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, which regulates the futures markets, of a soybean
sell-off order issued last week by the CBOT.
   ``We are extremely concerned about the effects which recent
events have had on agricultural producers and small investors,''
the senators wrote in a letter Thursday to CFTC chairman Wendy
Gramm. ``Furthermore, these events raise important questions about
whether adequate safeguards are in place to prevent unwarranted
emergency actions.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers' earnings roll is
slowing down.
   After setting earnings records in three of the last four
quarters, analysts said Thursday they expect General Motors Corp.,
Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. will announce second-quarter
earnings slightly lower than a year ago, reflecting a softening
U.S. car and truck market.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bankruptcy judge approved the release of $75
million from an escrow fund to help strikebound Eastern Airlines
with its financial needs in coming months.
   Eastern initially had asked U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland for the release of $100 million from creditors, while a
committee representing Eastern's major creditors asked for only $40
million to be released.
   However, the parties agreed to the $75 million figure and the
judge approved it Thursday with the understanding Eastern could
request additional money from the fund, which contains money from
asset sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of a United wide-bodied jet in Sioux
City, Iowa, demonstrates a problem already highlighted in two other
major DC-10 accidents: the lack of an effective backup when the
hydraulic system fails.
   Other incidents prior to Wednesday's DC-10 crash have a common
thread in the loss of pilot control after a failure that would not
ordinarily affect flight controls, such as loss of an engine or a
cargo door.
   Each has added to concern among government and aviation
authorities over design of the DC-10, which the government grounded
for more than a month in 1979.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California company previously spurned in
its effort to buy all of Prime Computer Inc. offered to purchase
Prime's minicomputer business for $450 million in cash and $150
million of MAI securities.
   Prime Chairman David J. Dunn said Thursday its board of
directors would meet to consider the offer from MAI Basic Four Inc.
of Tustin, Calif.
   MAI, a computer maker controlled by investor Bennett S. LeBow,
had pursued Prime for seven months before the Natick-based company
agreed last month to a merger with J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., a New York
venture capital firm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major electronic network linking more than
60,000 computers remains vulnerable to potentially crippling attack
by computer ``viruses,'' the General Accounting Office said.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said Thursday the
White House science adviser should oversee efforts to help protect
the network, Internet, from sabotage.
   The agency said lax security procedures on Internet contributed
to the severity of problems that resulted when a software virus
``infected'' the system last November, crippling thousands of
computers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A selloff near the close pushed stock prices lower Thursday,
wiping out an early gain that carried the Dow Jones industrial
average briefly past 2,600 for the first time since the fall of
1987. The average closed with an 8.92 loss at 2,575.49.
   The dollar lost ground in quiet domestic trading after closing
mixed overseas as dealers digested comments from Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan on the interest rate climate.
   Bond traders welcomed a hint of lower interest rates from
Greenspan and sent bond prices modestly higher.
   Pork belly and hog futures prices rose; cattle futures were
mixed; orange juice futures fell sharply; grains and soybeans
finished mixed; precious metals rose; and energy futures advanced.
