<FIRST>r f PM-Revlon-Kissinger     07-21 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Revlon-Kissinger,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Joins Cosmetics Company's Star-Studded Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revlon Group Inc. says former Secretary of State
Henry A. Kissinger will serve on its board of directors, becoming
the latest luminary to join the cosmetics company's star-studded
board.
   Last month, Revlon announced that former first lady Nancy Reagan
had become one of its directors.
   Revlon's board, which will have 14 directors including
Kissinger, also includes actress Audrey Hepburn and Ann Getty, wife
of oil heir Gordon P. Getty.
   Revlon Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Ronald O. Perelman
said Thursday that Kissinger's ``unparalleled knowledge of world
affairs and global markets will provide an invaluable perspective
to our board's oversight of Revlon's growing international
operations.''
   Kissinger, who served as secretary of state from 1973 to 1975
and won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1973, already serves on the boards
of American Express Co., Union Pacific Corp., R.J. Macy &amp; Co. and
other companies.
   He was elected to serve an indefinte term on the Revlon board.
Revlon, which said its board holds regular quarterly meetings,
doesn't disclose how much financial compensation directors receives.
   Among the privately held Revlon's businesses are the beauty
products maker Revlon Inc. and National Health Laboratories.
</TEXT>
