<DOCNO> AP890721-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Marriott-ElderlyHousing     07-21 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marriott-Elderly Housing,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotelier Plans to Develop 150 Retirement Communities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marriott Corp. has announced plans to develop
150 retirement communities over the next five years that it said
would offer housing to more than 25,000 older Americans and create
up to 18,000 new jobs.
   Marriott's Senior Living Services division already is operating
12 communities, three others are under development and it said four
more will be built in Silver Spring, Md.; Boca Raton, Fla.;
Glenview, Ill.; and Palos Verde, Calif, the company said.
   The planned rental communities announced Thursday are of two
types.
   Independent full-service facilities will feature apartments or
cottages for people who can function independently, or who want to
receive help with day-to-day activities such as dressing, grooming,
meals and housekeeping. Should they reach a point where they need
full-time care, they can move into the nursing home that is part of
the community.
   Catered-care communities are smaller facilities which feature
studio apartments for people who need regular assistance and which
also offer licensed nursing beds.
   ``These communities have been designed to not only take care of
life's necessities, but to encourage our residents to lead active
and vigorous lifestyles,'' said James Eden, vice president and
general manager for Marriott's Senior Living Services.
   Daniel Thursz, president of the National Council on the Aging,
said the facilities would help address the huge unmet need
nationally for affordable housing for senior citizens.
   ``America faces a critical and growing crisis in its ability to
provide both adequate housing and longterm healthcare for the
nation's every-growing older population,'' Thursz said.
</TEXT>
