<DOCNO> AP890721-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Senate-Futures     07-21 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Futures,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Ask For Reviews Of Soybean Futures Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CFTC Hearings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm-state senators have asked federal
regulators to investigate a recent emergency order by the Chicago
Board of Trade aimed at avoiding a squeeze in the soybean futures
market.
   The lawmakers on Thursday sought the review by the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, which regulates the futures markets, of
a soybean sell-off order issued last week by the CBOT.
   ``We are extremely concerned about the effects which recent
events have had on agricultural producers and small investors,''
the senators wrote in a letter to CFTC Chairwoman Wendy Gramm.
``Furthermore, these events raise important questions about whether
adequate safeguards are in place to prevent unwarranted emergency
actions.''
   The letter was written by Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., and
signed by several others, including Sens. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.;
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.; and Robert Kerry, D-Neb. They serve on the
Senate Agriculture Committee, which oversees the futures markets
and the regulatory agency.
   The lawmakers asked the CFTC for a full disclosure of the events
during the last several months that led up to the emergency order,
including identification of all traders holding positions larger
than 1 million bushels of soybeans during May, June and July.
   The order by the board forced some traders to sell off part of
their holdings in July soybeans, and was viewed as an effort to
break an attempt by a foreign firm to corner the market.
   Soybean futures prices dropped sharply as a result of the order.
   Ferruzzi SpA, an Italian agricultural and financial firm,
reportedly had contracts to take delivery on 23 million bushels of
soybeans this month when there were only about 12 million bushels
in locations for easy delivery to meet those commitments. A move by
the grain trader to take delivery on its contracts could have
sharply increased soybean prices. Company officials have denied any
attempt to corner the market, however.
   Kate Hathaway, a spokesman for CFTC, said the agency has a
formal review of the board's order under way. Although she had not
seen a copy of the letter, she said some of the senators' questions
appeared to be addressed by the commission's review process.
   The commission has a policy of not publicly disclosing
information about individual traders, but Hathaway said the agency
has in the past privately sharedsome of that information with
members of Congress.
   Among other things, the senators asked for an assessment of the
current delivery system for commodity contracts and ``what actions
can be taken to prevent a similar situation with the August soybean
contract?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-Taxes     07-21 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Taxes,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Adviser Denies Administration Is Inviting Tax-Increase Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's chief economic adviser has
rejected a suggestion the administration is inviting tax-increase
proposals when it says it would consider such proposals on their
merits.
   Chairman Michael Boskin of the Council of Economic Advisers was
questioned several times Thursday at a congressional Joint Economic
Committee hearing about the president's ``no new taxes'' pledge
made during last year's campaign.
   Boskin replied that he fully supports Bush's position and that
the administration does not intend to bring the issue with Congress
when both sides begin negotiations on the fiscal budget for 1991.
Then he added:
   ``We will listen and consider any proposal on its merits.''
   That prompted Sen. William Roth, R-Del., a committee member who
has raised the tax-increase question at several recent
congressional hearings, to remark:
   ``When you say you would consider a proposal, that almost
invites one.''
   Boskin denied the administration was inviting anyone to bring up
the issue.
   ``We are reasonable people,'' he said. ``We will listen, but we
don't think we need a tax increase and we don't think one is
desirable.''
   Committee Chairman Rep. Lee H. Hamilton, D-Ind., suggested the
willingness to consider tax proposals ``appears to be a shift from
a very hard line position (of) `no new taxes' to a position of
we'll sit at the table and consider proposals.''
   Boskin replied the administration does not mean to suggest it is
weakening its position.
   Hamilton also asked Boskin whether the ``no new tax'' position
applies throughout Bush's first term.
   ``So far as I know, that is the president's desire,'' Boskin
replied.
   In an appearance before the committee on Wednesday, Treasury
Secretary Nicholas H. Brady also repeated the administration's
intent oppose new taxes in the new budget talks.
   But, despite prodding by Roth, he declined to categorically rule
out the possibility of a tax increase.
   ``Certainly the 1990 budget was put together with that in mind
and that's what happened,'' Brady said. ``We would begin with that
same process in 1991. The president's position is quite clear and
that obviously is my position.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890721-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;LTakeovers     07-21 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Takeovers,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Institutions Taken Over In Six States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have seized control of
seven more savings and loan institutions in preparation for
congressional passage of President Bush's S&amp;L bailout.
   Thursday's action, which does not affect depositors, brings the
number of failed S&amp;Ls under government management to 244 in 33
states.
   The institutions in the latest batch are in California, Florida,
Illinois, Louisiana, New Mexico and Tennessee.
   They are:
   _Sierra Federal Savings and Loan Association, Beverly Hills,
Calif., with $49 million in assets.
   _American Interstate Savings, Los Angeles, with $27 million in
assets.
   _Commonwealth Savings and Loan Association of Florida, Margate,
Fla., with $1.68 billion in assets.
   _Peoples Bank for Savings, Streator, Ill., with $53 million in
assets.
   _Parrish Federal Savings Bank, Denham Springs, La., with $15
million in assets.
   _New Mexico Federal Savings and Loan Association, Albuquerque,
N.M., with $253 million in assets.
   _Home Federal Savings and Loan Association, Memphis, Tenn., with
$218 million in assets.
   All seven institutions will be managed by the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., which insures commercial banks and under proposed
bailout legislation would get new authority over the S&amp;L agency.
   The goal of the takeover program is to minimize losses and limit
risk until Congress provides the money to close the institutions or
subsidize their sale to new owners.
   Negotiators from the House and Senate are working to present
President Bush with a finished bill before Congress leaves for its
August vacation.
