<FIRST>r f PM-EEC-Soviets     07-21 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EEC-Soviets,0194</SECOND>
<UNK>EEC Opens Talks on Trade Pact with Soviet Union</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community says it
had opened talks with the Soviet Union on a trade and economic
cooperation agreement.
   The two sides discussed trade, investment and economic
cooperation, the EEC's executive commission said Thursday. A
further round of talks is expected in early October.
   Frans Andriessen, EEC commissioner for External Relations, said
in June the 12-nation trade bloc wanted to conclude a 10-year
agreement, which would not offer any trade concessions to the
Soviet Union, but would include ``most favored nation'' treatment
under international trade rules.
   The accord also would offer management training and joint
ventures as well as cooperation on the environment, energy and
nuclear safety.
   The EEC had a trade deficit of $2.9 billion with the Soviet
Union in 1988. The EEC imports mainly natural gas and petroleum
products from the Soviet Union while it exports mainly manufactured
products and machinery.
   The EEC has signed trade and cooperation agreements with
Czechoslovakia and Hungary, is close to signing a pact with Poland,
and has opened negotiations with East Germany.
</TEXT>
