<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CFTCHearing Bjt   07-21 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFTC Hearing, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Official Details Different Version of Soybean Emergency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade's efforts to erase
doubts about why it took emergency action in the soybean futures
market last week has raised even more questions about federal
regulators' actions.
   CBOT Chairman Karsten Mahlman testified before a House
subcommittee Thursday that the exchange ordered the liquidation of
large positions in the July soybean futures market last week after
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission ``took their own
independent action.''
   That statement was ``inconsistent'' with previous statements by
the CFTC Chairwoman Wendy Gramm, noted subcommittee members.
   Earlier this week, Ms. Gramm, whose agency is up for
reauthorization by Congress, testified that the CFTC only consulted
with the Chicago exchange about the emergency order and was now
reviewing it.
   But Mahlman said Ms. Gramm's agency, ``independent of the
exchange's action,'' also determined that ``one major market
participant'' wasn't meeting its obligation to liquidate futures
contracts in an orderly manner.
   ``We were led to believe that the situation took place
differently,'' said Rep. David R. Nagle, D-Iowa.
   Futures contracts are agreements to deliver a quantity of goods,
such as soybeans or gold, at a specified price at a specified time
in the future. Most futures traders never take or make delivery;
They enter into futures investments planning to close out their
positions before delivery date.
   Liquidation is the sale of futures contracts to offset an
obligation to take delivery of an equal number of futures contracts
purchased earlier for the same month.
   Mahlman would not identify the ``major market participant'' at
which the order was directed, but the action was widely perceived
as a move to prevent Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi Finanziaria
SpA from squeezing or cornering the soybean market, a charge
Ferruzzi denies.
   ``There was a real threat of potential default on the contract,
which would have had long-term damaging effects on the soybean
futures market,'' said Mahlman in a statement issued in Washington
and Chicago.
   He also said the CBOT was aware that one entity was acquiring a
large position in soybean futures because it had been granted an
exemption by the CFTC.
   Outside the hearing room, Mahlman would not comment on whether
the exemption was a good idea.
   ``We hope our strong action in July will not be necessary in
August,'' Mahlman told reporters. ``I think we have dramatically
enhanced the credibility of the board.''
   In earlier testimony, the head of another Chicago exchange, the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, said Congress should not ban the
controversial practice of dual trading, in which brokers trade for
themselves and their customers. The statement represented a
reversal of the Merc's earlier position.
   Critics say dual trading allows brokers to take care of their
own needs first, but banning it outright ``would be dangerous,''
said Leo Melamed, chairman of the Merc's executive committee.
   Mahlman concurred with that position. In a statement submitted
to the subcommittee, Mahlman, chairman of the world's oldest and
largest futures exchange, said a ban on dual trading ``will
adversely affect the liquidity of futures markets, particularly
agricultural markets, by increasing the cost of doing business.''
   Ms. Gramm exasperated committee members Tuesday with her
cautious answers to questions about the agency's consulting role in
the Chicago soybean situation.
   Ms. Gramm, who also said more study was needed before dual
trading was banned, said her agency was reviewing the CBOT's
emergency order but neither directly approved nor disapproved of
the action.
   Subcommittee Chairman Glenn English, D-Okla., alluded to his
frustration with the CFTC at the start of the Thursday session when
he said the congressmen present ``want to get complete answers
instead of the ones they got Tuesday.''
   The dual-trading bill, sponsored by English and the
subcommittee's ranking Republican, E. Thomas Coleman of Missouri,
would allow the practice only in certain circumstances, including
futures issues that have an average daily trading volume of fewer
than 7,000 contracts.
   But Melamed, the Chicago Merc official, said dual trading was
needed to maintain liquidity when there are few customer orders. He
added that pegging dual trading permissibility to volume ignores
the monthly idiosyncracies of various markets such as soybeans,
cattle, oil or gold.
   But Robert D. Josserand, president of the National Cattlemen's
Association, advocated the elimination of dual trading to restore
public confidence.
</TEXT>
