<FIRST>r f PM-Time     07-21 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Reserves Decision on Chris-Craft Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge has reserved decision on a
request by Chris-Craft Industries Inc. for more time to consider
how it will dispose of its stock in Warner Communications Inc.
under Warner's merger agreement with Time Inc.
   Chris-Craft, a major Warner stockholder, and its subsidiary BHC
Inc., have until July 30 to decide what to do with the stock.
Chris-Craft and BHC have several options involving the stock under
a May 19 agreement with Warner.
   The companies told Chancery Court Judge Jack Jacobs in
Wilmington on Thursday that they needed more time to decide what to
do because Time and Warner amended their original stock-swap merger
plan to provide for Time's pending $14 billion tender for Warner.
   Chris-Craft and BHC also have filed suit in New York in
connection with their Warner stock, trying to preserve their rights
under the tender offer for Warner.
   The Chris-Craft suits are a side issue in the court battle
emanating from the Time-Warner deal. The Delaware Supreme Court is
to hear arguments Monday on Paramount Communications Inc.'s appeal
of a lower court ruling allowing Time to proceed with its
$70-a-share tender offer for Warner.
   Paramount, which is trying to buy Time for $200 a share or $12.2
billion, says its offer would be precluded by the Time-Warner
merger.
   On Wall Street on Thursday, traders continued to square their
positions in advance of Monday's hearing. Investors and legal
scholars generally believe Paramount will lose before the Supreme
Court and give up its bid.
   Time stock fell 75 cents to $138.62{ a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading, while Warner was unchanged at $65.62{ a
share and Paramount fell 62{ cents to $58 a share.
</TEXT>
