<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-21 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar waned while gold gained today in
European trading.
   Metal traders in London said buyers had responded to the
softening of the dollar.
   The currency market wavered amid confused reaction to Thursday's
statements by Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan.
   ``Recent developments suggest that the balance of risks may have
shifted somewhat away from greater inflation,'' Greenspan told a
Congressional committee in Washington. `` ... What we seek to avoid
is an unnecessary and destructive recession.''
   In Frankfurt, the dollar had moved as high as 1.9040 marks early
in the morning, but retreated to 1.8955 marks later before
rebounding to 1.8975 marks.
   One trader at a major U.S. bank in Frankfurt predicted the
dollar would stay in a range between 1.8950 marks and 1.9150 marks.
   The dollar closed slightly lower in Tokyo Friday at 142.15 yen,
a drop of 0.08 yen from Thursday's close. Later in London, the
dollar slid to 141.60 yen.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6275 this morning, up for
buyers from Thursday's late $1.6273.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Thursday's late rates, included: 1.6360 Swiss francs, down from
1.6405; 6.4363 French francs, down from 6.4460; 2.1435 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1530; 1,377.00 Italian lire, down from
1,378.50; 1.1866 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $370.75 a troy ounce,
down from $372.45 late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers set a recommended price of $372.25 per troy
ounce.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $372.90, down from $371.75 bid at the
close Thursday. Gold rose $3.56 in Hong Kong to close today at the
equivalent of $372.67 per troy ounce.
   Silver bullion was unchanged from Thursday's late price of $5.22
a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
