<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SoybeanCorner     07-21 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBOT, For First Time, Links Soybean Order to Ferruzzi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade has, for the first
time, linked Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi Finanziaria S.p.A. to
the exchange's order requiring traders to reduce their holdings in
soybean futures contracts.
   In a statement to exchange members issued Thursday, after the
expiration of the July soybean contract, the world's largest
commodity exchange said it took the emergency action after a
Ferruzzi subsidiary failed to voluntarily reduce its large holdings
in the July soybean market.
   In the statement, the exchange said its business conduct
committee had met with Ferruzzi USA Inc. of Belle Chasse, La., in
early July and asked it to voluntarily reduce its market position
to ensure the orderly expiration of the July contract.
   ``Subsequent to that meeting, Ferruzzi failed to reduce its
position,'' the exchange said in the statement. ``As a result, the
businesss conduct committee recommended to the board of directors
that the board exercise its emergency authority to ensure the
orderly liquidation of the July soybean contract.''
   The resulting July 11 order requiring traders to reduce their
positions in the July soybean market to 1 million bushels, was
widely perceived as a move to prevent Ferruzzi from squeezing or
cornering the soybean market, a charge Ferruzzi denies.
   Ferruzzi at the time the order was issued held futures contracts
representing 23 million bushels of soybeans.
   A CBOT spokesman said Thursday that the exchange took the
emergency action to ensure that obligations to deliver soybeans did
not exceed the supply of soybeans meeting the contract's
specifications.
   The Board of Trade has been heavily criticized by farm groups
and traders who saw the value of their futures holdings drop when
soybean futures prices fell sharply on the day after the exchange
issued the directive.
   The contract for July delivery of soybeans expired on a weak
note Thursday, bringing an end to trading in the contract but not
to the controversy surrounding it.
   The July soybean contract expired at 12:01 p.m. CDT at $6.88{ a
bushel, down 39 cents from Wednesday's settlement price. That final
price is 37{ cents per bushel below the price on July 1, when the
CBOT directors issued the emergency order.
   The emergency order ``had to be a great influence on the drop in
prices,'' said grain trader Bud Frazier, executive vice president
of Balfour, Maclaine.
   Some observers said the same pressures that had prompted the
exchange to limit holdings in July soybean futures may be building
again in the August contract.
   Ferruzzi has said it was complying with the exchange's directive
but traders familiar with the firm's methods said the company may
have rolled its huge position out of the July contract and into the
August contract, potentially setting up another confrontation with
the Board of Trade next month.
   ``I have no way of proving it but a lot of people think that's
what they're doing,'' said a trader who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann alluded to the
possibility at a news conference in Washington, where he was
testifying before a congressional committee.
   ``We hope that our strong action will not be necessary in
August,'' Mahlmann said.
   Ferruzzi did not return calls inquiring about its market
position. But the company released a statement saying it supports
full disclosure of events that led to the Board of Trade's
emergency action.
   Board of Trade spokesmen would not comment on Ferruzzi's market
position or on trader response to the emergency order.
   ``If open interest is in line with deliverable supplies, that is
the idea,'' said exchange spokesman Michael O'Connell.
   O'Connell said updated figures on July open interest and
deliverable supplies of soybeans would be available today.
</TEXT>
