<FIRST>r f PM-EggheadSuit     07-21 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egghead Suit,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egghead Shareholders Accuse Software Retailer of Securities Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A class-action lawsuit has been filed by
shareholders against Egghead Discount Software, accusing the
nation's largest-volume personal computer software retailer and its
principal officers of securities fraud.
   The lawsuit, disclosed Thursday by Egghead, follows nearly $13
million in unexpected losses last quarter despite a 50 percent
increase in Egghead's sales.
   Egghead, which has denied the allegations, has blamed much of
the loss on ``shrinkage'' or missing inventory, and on poor
accounting systems.
   The suit, which seeks unspecified damages, was filed in U.S.
District Court in Seattle and alleges that the plaintiff, Egghead
stockholder Steve Goldman, and others were damaged as a result of
alleged misstatements in connection with the company's initial
public stock offering and its public statements and filings from
June 6, 1988, through April 24, 1989.
   ``The main claim is the same claim that you get in any
securities fraud cases,'' said Steve Berman, an attorney
representing shareholders.
   ``We are alleging that Egghead and its directors failed to
disclose material facts about the company's financial and
competitive condition at the time they offered the stock and
throughout the class period,'' he said.
   Egghead denied the allegations.
   ``We have reviewed the plaintiff's claims and believe they are
entirely without merit,'' said Stuart Sloan, Egghead president and
chief executive officer. ``Egghead intends to defend this caes
vigorously.''
   Egghead's stock went public in June 1988 at $17 a share. It
closed Thursday in over-the-counter trading at $11, down 50 cents.
   The Issaquah-based company reported a loss of $12.1 million or
80 cents a share on sales of $342.4 million for fiscal 1989.
   ``They had been touting the company as a good company and one
that had tight controls,'' Berman said. ``And then _ boom! You find
out that obviously they don't have those controls. ...
   ``We allege that either they knew about some of the problems or
they were reckless and negligent in not knowing about them.''
   Named as defendants were Sloan and other Egghead officers and
directors, including founder and chairman Victor Alhadeff. Also
named were the underwriters of its initial public offering,
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. and First Boston Corp.
  
</TEXT>
