<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0923EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest-Pilots     07-21 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Pilots,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Pilots Decide Not To Try To Buy Into Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union pilots at Northwest Airlines
have decided they won't try to buy into the carrier, at least not
until after new owners take over.
   Union members decided Thursday it is too late to arrange an
equity investment, with a buyout of the Eagan-based airline at hand
by a group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi and with the
pilots' labor contract still locked in a stand-off with management.
   ``Whether or not we should have proceeded with a different
strategy a year and-a-half ago is a moot point,'' said Pete
Quortrup, a spokesman for the pilots. Some 180 members at the
five-hour meeting seemed to accept that idea.
   The long-smoldering issue has divided the ranks of the Air Line
Pilots Association in recent months. Some of its 2,800 members have
insisted the union should hold a stake in the carrier being taken
over by Checchi's Wings Holdings.
   In a tender offer that expires at midnight tonight, the group
would pay $121 a share or about $3.65 billion for the airline.
   Checchi has said his group will entertain an employee
investment, but only after his buyout is complete.
   Still, frustrated advocates of an employee stock ownership plan
mailed flyers in recent weeks to 5,000 pilots at Northwest,
including a separate group of 2,200 former Republic Airlines
pilots. That group has divorced itself from the investment idea.
   ``I would much prefer to govern my own destiny as to have
someone else govern it for me,'' said Tom Beedem, a DC-10 pilot and
former chairman of the Northwest pilots Master Executive Council.
   Beedem said before the meeting he was among those urging members
to promote an employee ownership plan before settling their labor
contract with Northwest. He also said such an agreement should be
in place before a labor contract is signed.
   With the ranks alerted, advocates pitched their idea Thursday at
a Bloomington hotel, but the notion eventually was dropped without
a vote.
   Later, Quortrup said, Master Executive Council chairman Pete
Dodge recounted the history of pilot efforts to buy into Northwest,
including unsuccessfully exploring the prospect last summer.
   Both arguments were received ``thoughtfully,'' Dodge said, but
the idea was abandoned for now because ``you can't change a
strategy at this point. The company is not going to be a public
company that much longer.''
   The debate was emotional for some, said Quortrup, because
ownership appeals to pilots in a period of change and uncertainty.
   The pilots also were briefed at midday by their labor contract
negotiators, who spent the rest of the day at the bargaining table.
After 28 months, the two sides are still at odds over basic issues
such as wages.
</TEXT>
