<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposal Offered For S&amp;L Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS 5th graf, bgng: Rep. Chalmers, to show that first $25
billion borrowed this year and next, sted this year; SUBS last graf to
include first reference for Greenspan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior Republican on the House Banking
Committee is proposing a compromise intended to break a deadlock
over how to fund President Bush's proposed savings and loan bailout.
   The dispute between the House and the Senate is the most
significant hurdle to be overcome if Congress is to send savings
and loan legislation to the president's desk before leaving for its
August vacation.
   The Senate, in its bill adopted in April, favored the
administration's financing plan, which would create a new,
quasi-private agency to borrow $50 billion in S&amp;L rescue costs.
That mechanism would keep the spending from ballooning the federal
budget deficit.
   The House, in its plan passed last month, would include the $50
billion in the budget deficit in what Democrats say is more honest
accounting. The plan would be slightly cheaper than the
administration's because S&amp;L funds would be borrowed directly
through the federal government.
   Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, the senior Republican on the House
Banking Committee, said Thursday that under his plan, the first $25
billion in S&amp;L spending be borrowed this year and next. The
remaining $25 billion would go ``on-budget'' in 1991.
   By that time, the government would be selling enough property
from failed S&amp;Ls to partly offset the spending strain, he said.
   He conceded the scheme would put great strain on the ability of
the administration and Congress to reach agreement on the federal
budget as the 1992 elections approach.
   Wylie said Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's ``visceral
reaction was not very favorable.'' But, he said that Brady
nevertheless planned to raise the proposal when House and Senate
conferees next meet publicly on Tuesday. The staffs of the two
chambers have been working behind closed doors trying to resolve
most differences in preparation for the session.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, and Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee, were informed of the proposal but have so
far been noncommittal, Wylie said.
   Meanwhile, a House aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said a tentative agreement has been reached that would give the
Bush administration the authority it sought in disposing of an
estimated $300 billion in real estate and other property from
failed S&amp;Ls.
   The House has dropped its demand that L. William Seidman,
chairman of the politically independent Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., have a nonvoting seat on a five-member board overseeing
disposal of S&amp;L assets.
   Seidman still will be in charge of the day-to-day operations of
the Resolution Trust Corp., the new agency being created to handle
the property.
   But the policymaking responsibility for it will rest with the
board, chaired by Brady. Other members will be Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan, Housing and Urban Development Secretary
Jack Kemp and two private citizens with background in real estate
or finance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
