<FIRST>r f PM-Obit-Koopman     07-21 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Koopman,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Company Founder Dies In Car Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designation.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entrepreneur George A. Koopman, whose
business ventures ranged from making special effects for the hit
movie ``The Blues Brothers'' to co-founding a commercial rocket
company, died in a car accident. He was 45.
   The Malibu resident, who wanted his American Rocket Co. to carry
small commercial payloads into sub-orbital space, was pronounced
dead Wednesday morning after his car struck a dirt embankment and
flipped over.
   He was on his way to Edwards Air Force Base to watch a test of a
rocket engine, said Jim Bennett, co-founder of the company.
   The Camarillo, Calif., company had scheduled its first launch
next month. The rockets are designed to go into space, but not into
orbit.
   The California Highway Patrol said Koopman's car was going the
wrong way on a one-way street.
   Before helping found American Rocket in 1985, Koopman was
involved in a variety of enterprises, including producing the
special effects for ``The Blues Brothers,'' the 1980 movie starring
Dan Aykroyd and John Belushi. He also headed a small defense
contracting company at one time.
