<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ABC-Union     07-21 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ABC-Union,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC and NABET Negotiators Reach Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. says it has reached a
tentative agreement with negotiators for its technicians union on a
four-year contract.
   The deal was reached Thursday after the union offered to
compromise on issues relating to job security, the company said.
The two sides have been negotiating for five months and an earlier
proposal was rejected in May.
   Negotiators for the union, the National Association of Broadcast
Employees and Technicians, said they would submit the contract to a
vote without taking a position on it.
   The union's members _ 2,700 according to the union, 2,150
according to the company _ will vote by August 11. The engineers,
at 1,850, make up the largest unit withnin the union.
   ``The union came to us and offered a very constructive and
workable approach and this resulted in the agreement today,'' said
Patricia Matson, a spokeswoman for Cap Cities-ABC.
   The company told its employees in a letter that, ``The
compromise became possible earlier this week when the union
suggested to the company that the company's four-year job guarantee
to NABET was less significant to the union than the issue of
separate seniority.''
   The company had offered to make the job guarantee four years
instead of three, but John Krieger, a spokesman for the National
Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians, said it came
with so many escape clauses that it was ``like a Swiss cheese full
of holes.''
   The company withdrew the job-guarantee proposal and substituted
the seniority list compromise.
   The new rules call for employees on local and network television
seniority lists who were hired before Thursday to have a higher
priority than those hired after Thursday, who will be put on a new,
separate seniority list.
   That new list will determine who was last hired should layoffs
occur.
   A separate seniority list for radio employees will be maintained
as the company originally proposed.
   In addition, the company gave NABET assurances it would retain
some radio engineers to perform work no longer subject to NABET
jurisdiction.
   ``It's a compromise that they won't throw people out wholesale
and hire new people,'' Krieger said.
   He said 80 jobs had been at stake until the compromise and now
the union was willing to take a chance that the compromise will
work, Krieger said.
   The proposal to be voted upon calls for a signing bonus of 10
percent for the first year and pay increases of 3 percent in the
second and third years and 4 percent in the fourth year. The
original plan called for a 5 percent lump-sum bonus in the fourth
year.
   NABET also represents publicists, wardrobe people and
newswriters in certain cities, among other workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
