<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-21 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Slip On Weather, Turkish Wheat Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting improved growing conditions for corn and soybeans, and
disappointment over a Turkish wheat deal.
   Rain was falling this morning for the fourth straight day in
parts of the Midwestern Corn Belt. Analysts said the large amounts
of precipitation that have fallen this week in Iowa and Illinois
were timely and badly needed.
   Conditions are expected to turn drier and warmer next week but
temperatures are not expected to reach into the 90s, so ``that
shouldn't inhibit the silking process that is going on right now,''
said Susan Leighty, a grain-market analyst in New York with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Wheat futures prices slipped amid disappointment that Turkey
bought 450,000 metric tons of wheat from sources outside the United
States. The market had rallied Thursday on expectations for a
U.S.-Turkey wheat deal.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with
September at $3.98 a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent lower with
September at $2.39 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1} cents lower
with September at $1.50 a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents to 4}
cents lower with August at $6.79 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .22 cent higher with August
at 72.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .20 cent
lower with August at 83.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent
to .32 cent lower with August at 45.85 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .45 cent lower to .40 cent higher with July at 30.10
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
