<FIRST>r f PM-AlleghenyInternational     07-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Allegheny International,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Adopts New Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. today said its
board approved the framework of a new plan of reorganization for
the company and its subsidiaries, including Sunbeam Corp. and
Chemetron Corp.
   But the Pittsburgh-based consumer products company said it may
lack enough support among creditors to win confirmation of the plan
in federal bankruptcy court, where Allegheny International has been
trying to reorganize its businesses since February 1988.
   The latest proposal calls for full cash payment on the claims
against Sunbeam and for the payment of $400 million to Allegheny
International's secured bank creditors group.
   A $50 million note would be issued against claims by Sunbeam's
institutional lenders and the parent's senior secured bank lenders.
The note, to be paid on claims filed since the bankruptcy filing,
could be surrendered after one year to acquire two-thirds of the
common stock in the reorganized Allegheny International.
   Unsecured lenders would get bonds and preferred stock, and
shareholders would be left with 5 percent of the equity in the
reorganized company.
   Allegheny International filed a separate plan of reorganization
for Sunbeam on May 31. That would be superceded by the new plan, if
the board's framework is developed into a definitive plan.
   The company said it anticipates filing the new plan in court
some time in August.
   Chemetron is the non-operating remnants of a former chemical and
industrial gas business.
</TEXT>
