<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   07-21 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Release of $75 Million to Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 13th graf to CORRECT that Nunn is a Democrat sted Republican;
picks up 14th graf pvs bg'ng, Eastern parent ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines has received a cash
infusion of $75 million to help it with its rebuilding plan in
coming months.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland on Thursday approved the
release of the cash from an escrow fund to Eastern. The airline
initially asked Lifland for the release of $100 million from its
major creditors, while a committee representing the creditors asked
that only $40 million to be released.
   However, the parties agreed to the $75 million figure and the
judge approved it, with the understanding Eastern could request
additional money from the escrow fund, which contains money from
the sales of Eastern assets.
   Miami-based Eastern said it expected to file its reorganization
plan today, which will discuss how it plans to emerge from Chapter
11 bankruptcy at about two-thirds its prestrike size.
   Eastern's exclusivity period, during which other parties to the
case cannot file reorganization proposals under bankruptcy law, is
due to end today.
   The airline, which recently slashed fares in an effort to lure
skeptical travelers, now is raising prices on its most heavily
traveled routes. Eastern is hiking fares at least $20 on its
cheapest round-trip fares originating at several cities, including
its Miami and Atlanta hubs, marketing Vice President George Brennan
said Thursday. In some cases, round-trip fares are going up about
$40.
   The move takes pressure off Eastern's competitors to cut their
fares or keep discounts they've recently announced.
   In another development, published reports indicated Eastern was
prepared to sell its Latin American routes and most of the terminal
space they occupy to American Airlines because of continuing
difficulties in contract negotiations with striking pilots.
   A memo from Eastern Senior Vice President Tom Matthews to the
Air Line Pilots Association said the route sale idea would be
scrapped if the company reached a contract agreement with the
pilots, according to reports Thursday in the Fort Lauderdale
Sun-Sentinel and the Miami Herald.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the company would not
comment on the reports. Alton Becker, a spokesman for American,
said the Dallas-based airline unit of AMR Corp. has ``done no deals
with Eastern,'' but added: ``We are an acquirer. If any airline has
assets it wants to sell, we'll look at them.''
   Eastern pilots based in Atlanta passed a resolution late
Wednesday urging the pilots union leadership to continue supporting
a buyout bid for Eastern by Chicago businessman Joseph Ritchie. If
the bid fails, the Atlanta pilots said, the union should pursue
another bid and if that is unsuccessful, it should push for the
appointment of a special trustee to run the airline.
   If that fails, the last resort, according to the resolution,
would be to support the liquidation of Eastern's assets. The pilots
at the Atlanta hub carry considerable weight within the pilots
union's Eastern unit.
   In Washington, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., became the latest lawmaker
to express concern about the Eastern situation. In a letter sent
Wednesday to President Bush, he asked him to direct Transportation
Secretary Samuel Skinner and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to
undertake ``an immediate review'' of Eastern.
   Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. announced separately Wednesday
that it placed orders for $2.8 billion worth of Boeing 737-300
aircraft to be divided between Eastern and Continental Airlines,
another Texas Air subsidiary. The order includes 50 firm orders and
options to buy 50 more of the jets.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo and Eastern President Phil
Bakes said Wednesday in Atlanta that the transactions demonstrate
confidence that Eastern will be a thriving operation in the 1990s.
The airline is in the midst of a 4-month-old strike by Machinists,
pilots and flight attendants.
   Lorenzo and Bakes also acknowledged that the August expansion of
Eastern's flight schedule will not be as large as originally
announced. But they maintained that the smaller expansion is not a
sign that the rebuilding program is faltering.
   The airline originally promised to have 390 flights a day by
Aug. 1, but it said this week some reductions may be necessary.
Before the strike March 4, Eastern had about 1,100 daily flights.
It now has 220.
</TEXT>
