<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HearingImpaired-Phone     07-21 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hearing Impaired-Phone,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Company Offers New Phone for Hearing Impaired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California company has developed a telephone
for the hearing impaired that for the first time focuses on the
most common type of sound that some people cannot hear instead of
simply turning up the volume, an executive said Friday.
   The Walker Clarity telephone, working much like a graphic
equalizer on stereo recording equipment, boosts the high-frequency
sounds that most hearing-impaired people have difficulty hearing.
   ``There are over 20 million people (in the United States) who
have some form of hearing impairment, and roughly 95 percent have
loss in the high frequencies,'' Walker Equipment Corp. President
Marv Tseu said.
   For the hearing impaired, normal telephone conversations can
resemble the sounds made when a stereo's bass control is turned up
too much, while the treble is lowered.
   This affects recognition of consonants, and makes it difficult
for the hearing impaired to distinguish between words such as
``tomato'' or ``potato.'' Phone conversations sound muddled.
   ``When you lose the ability to hear these high-frequency sounds
you lose a lot of ability to understand the language,'' Tseu said
by telephone from his office in Santa Cruz, Calif.
   This problem is compounded by low-frequency noise on the phone
system itself. Merely turning up the volume in many cases just
increases the noise without making the high-frequency sounds more
distinct.
   ``If you take a standard telephone and amplify it, it raises all
of the sounds equally. All you get is a louder muddle,'' Tseu said.
   The new telephone has a sliding control that allows the user to
balance the volume and the treble _ the high-frequency sounds _ for
maximum clarity.
   The Walker Clarity telephone will assist anyone with mild to
severe hearing loss, but not those with profound hearing loss, Tseu
said. It works best when used without a hearing aid or with a
hearing aid that has a telephone coil for use on hearing
aid-compatible phones, he added.
   The phone also has a low-frequency, warbling-type ring; a bar
that lights up when the phone rings; enlarged keypad; and a braille
dot on the number 5 key to aid the visually impaired.
   It also features a mute button that will turn off the mouthpiece
as long as the button is depressed. This shuts off background noise
that sometimes feeds back through the earpiece, Tseu said.
   The company began shipping the phone last month to hearing aid
dispensers and audiologists, Tseu said. The phones are made in Hong
Kong and retail for $287.
   Walker is a division of Plantronics Inc., a major manufacturer
of of telephone headsets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
