<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-21 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Slide On Weather-Related Selling; Grains End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed modestly lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting improved growing
conditions in the Midwest, while corn and wheat futures finished
narrowly mixed in quiet trading.
   Analysts said four days of showers in the western Corn Belt had
revived corn and soybean crops, and forecasts for the coming week
predicted no return to the withering heat of late June and early
July.
   News that federal regulators had ordered Italian grain merchant
Ferruzzi Finanziaria S.p.A. to reduce its holdings in the
now-expired July futures contract last week also weighed on the
soybean market, analysts said.
   The news prompted worries that Ferruzzi might be ordered to
reduce its position in the August contract.
   But Ted Mao, a grain specialist in New York with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., said the Ferruzzi news was a minor factor in Friday's
market.
   ``The market in general has been responding to better weather,''
he said.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.95{ a bushel; corn was }
cent lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.39\ a bushel; oats
were 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with September at $1.50 a bushel;
and soybeans were 3 cents to 7} cents lower with August at $6.74 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
