<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-MorganGrenfell     07-21 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Morgan Grenfell,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Sells Bulk of Morgan Grenfell Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd's of London insurance broker Dewey Warren
Holdings PLC said Friday it sold the bulk of its 6 percent stake in
the British merchant bank Morgan Grenfell Group PLC for $36 million
after expenses.
   Shares in Morgan Grenfell, which long has been the target of
takeover speculation, jumped 21 pence, or 34 cents, a share to
finish at 313 pence, or $5.10, on London's Stock Exchange.
   The sale was announced a few minutes before the close of
official trading.
   Dewey Warren didn't reveal to whom it sold the shares.
   Morgan Grenfell Chief Executive John Craven said he believed the
shares were placed with institutional clients of Phillips and Drew,
Dewey Warren's stockbrokers.
   Morgan Grenfell has attracted takeover speculation because of
the substantial minority holdings in the company which could be
used as a platform for a full bid, analysts said. The British
insurance group Willis Faber PLC owns 20.7 percent of the company
and Deutsche Bank holds a 4.9 percent stake.
</TEXT>
