<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     07-21 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Announces Scheduled Meetings As MAI Offers Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. said Friday it will
proceed with a shareholders meeting this month to select directors
despite an eleventh-hour offer from a California company to buy its
mincomputer business.
   ``The meeting's subject will be which slate of directors will
run Prime,'' Prime spokesman Joe Gavaghan said. Shareholders will
choose between Prime's present directors and nominees of MAI Basic
Four, a Tustin, Calif.-based company that has been seeking to take
over Prime.
   The meeting, set for July 26, was rescheduled from an original
date of June 14. Prime pushed the meeting back to give its
shareholders the opportunity to consider a revised buyout offer by
MAI. A Delaware Chancery Court authorized the later date despite
protests from MAI.
   Meanwhile, Prime said Wednesday it had received a proposal from
MAI to purchase the Prime minicomputer business for $450 million in
cash and $150 million in debentures.
   Gavaghan said no date had been set for Prime's board of
directors to consider the latest MAI offer.
   MAI had reduced its initial bid for Prime from $20 per share in
cash to $19.50 per share, with 75 percent cash and 25 percent in
paid with bonds.
   Prime subsequently entered a merger agreement with J.H. Whitney,
a New York investment firm. Whitney has offered $21.50 per share in
cash for 79 percent of the stock. The remaining 21 percent of stock
would be exchanged for bonds with a face value of $22.
   Analysts have valued the Whitney offer at about $1.25 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
