<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     07-21 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0309</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were widely mixed today in the
aftermath of Thursday's late selloff.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which tumbled from a
gain of about 30 points to an 8.92 loss late Thursday, rebounded
16.88 to 2,592.37 by 3 p.m. today on Wall Street.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 653 up, 757
down and 523 unchanged.
   In early trading on Thursday the market climbed to new highs for
the strong rally that dates back to mid-November of last year. But
those gains failed to stand up to the pressure of afternoon selling.
   Analysts said that reversal served to dampen some of the
enthusiasm stirred up by the market's impressive advance of late.
   In addition, interest rates rose slightly in the credit markets
today as bond prices gave back a bit of their recent gains.
   The wide swings in blue chip stocks both Thursday and today were
attributed in large measure to computer-program activity by
professionals closing out positions in options and stock-index
futures due to expire after the close today.
   Bankamerica rose ] to 28~. On Thursday the company reported a
larger increase in second-quarter earnings than analysts had been
expecting.
   USAir Group climbed 1\ to 51 in active trading. An group led by
New York investor Michael Steinhardt said it owns 5.89 percent of
USAir's stock and may consider seeking control of the airline
company.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .37 to 186.48. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .14 at 371.05.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 132.78 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
