<DOCNO> AP890721-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Winchell'sBuyout     07-21 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Winchell's Buyout,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Firm Buys Winchell's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA MIRADA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winchell's Donut Houses, the nation's
second-largest chain of doughnut shops, agreed to be acquired for
$40 million by Shato Holdings Ltd., a Vancouver-based restaurant
and real estate firm.
   Shato, a privately-held firm, said Thursday it will pay $3.80
for each of Winchell's 8.8 million shares.
   The balance of the cash payment will be used to liquidate
Winchell's publicly traded partnership, settle debts and cover
transaction costs, said Nancy Larson, Winchell's director of tax
and investor services.
   The deal must be approved by a majority of Winchell's
shareholders.
   Shato owns more than 100 restaurants and catering outlets in
British Columbia and a land development company.
   Second only to Dunkin' Donuts among the nation's doughnut
chains, Winchell's has 657 stores in 14 Western states. In the late
1970s, the chain had nearly 1,000 stores.
   Winchell's has struggled since it was spun off by Denny's
restaurants in 1987. The chain lost $12.8 million in 1988 and
posted a loss of $3.4 million on $36.3 million in revenue during
the first quarter of 1989.
   Winchell's had been looking for a buyer since June 8, one day
after TW Services, which owns 42 percent of the doughnut chain,
accepted a $1.65 billion takeover bid by Coniston Partners of New
York.
   TW Services also owns Denny's and El Pollo Loco restaurants.
Coniston has said it will retain both chains.
   Ward Lendenmeyer, an analyst at Sutro &amp; Co., said poor
management, competition from grocery-owned bakeries and sluggish
demand contributed to Winchell's decline.
   In 1971, Winchell's bought out all its franchises to operate
them as company-owned stores.
   ``That was a big mistake,'' Lendenmeyer said. ``There isn't
enough (sales) volume to pay employees very much. People tend to
work harder when they have a stake as a franchisee.''
   Winchell's was founded in 1948 by Verne H. Winchell, who sold
used cars and jukeboxes before opening his first doughnut shop in
Temple City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
