<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1607EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TurnerBroadcasting     07-21 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner Broadcasting,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner Gets Grilling Over Bias at Shareholders Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Turner Broadcasting System Inc. shareholders
meeting was transformed into a debate on fairness in media Friday
as a watchdog group accused Chairman Ted Turner of using his cable
television network as a vehicle for promoting liberal political
causes.
   Reed Irvine, chairman of Washington-based Accuracy in Media,
said conservative organizations have a difficult time getting their
views aired on Turner's TBS SuperStation, though the cable station
provides much free time to liberal groups which he said Turner
supports.
   Specifically, Irvine said TBS has given nine hours of prime time
this year to shows produced or backed by the Better World Society,
a group headed by Turner that tends to support liberal causes.
   Irvine, who owns 200 shares of TBS stock, also criticized Turner
for refusing to air an anti-abortion film following the Thursday
night broadcast of ``Abortion: For Survival,'' a program that
favored the pro-choice position.
   ``If you're going to give free air time, distribute it
equitably,'' Irvine said.
   The exchange between Turner and Irvine took up nearly an hour of
the 90-minute meeting. Turner apologized to shareholders who came
to Atlanta expecting hear about the operation of TBS and instead
got ``nitpicking.''
   Turner acknowledged that his personal feelings play a part in
his decisions on which special programs to broadcast, but he said
he is not bound to show the offerings of any organization. He said
each program is evaluated on its own merits.
   He said conservative opinions are aired frequently on his Cable
News Network, but he did not want to be bound to presenting
opposing viewpoints on his entertainment station.
   ``We have to make these judgments,'' Turner said. ``Someone is
opposed to everything.''
   Irvine questioned the business wisdom of showing the abortion
program _ for which Turner said he did not try to sell advertising
_ three times on TBS.
   Turner contended that TBS will not lose money on the abortion
program because ad space was not normally sold out for those slots
anyway. He said one hour of prime time generally is worth $100,000.
   ``We couldn't do it (no ads) every night,'' he said. ``We could
easily do it once a month without any problem. You know we do
things differently from the other networks and we're growing
rapidly, and they're not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
