<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-21 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices ended mixed Friday in
extremely quiet trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil for September delivery settled 17 cents lower at $19.51
per 42-gallon barrel on the first trading day for that contract.
More distant contract months posted smaller losses.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the September
contract of unleaded gasoline rose 0.42 cent to 54.52 cents a
gallon, reversing several days of declines. Other contract months
also gained ground.
   Among other refined products, No.2 heating oil for September
delivery slipped 0.54 cent to 51.29 cents a gallon, also reversing
an earlier upward trend. Contracts for heating oil delivery in more
distant months posted similar losses.
   According to John Hill, vice president of Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, the market ``felt a little weak, but the overwhelming
feature was no volume.''
   Rumors and reports of continued labor unrest in the Soviet Union
as well as problems at a Venezuela refinery caught traders'
attention. Hill said while it was unclear how serious the refinery
problem would be, traders were looking for something to react to.
</TEXT>
