<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Caterpillar     07-21 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Caterpillar,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caterpillar Earnings Slip from 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: retransmitting to change cycle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc. on Friday reported
relatively flat second-quarter earnings despite an increase in
sales.
   During the quarter, profits totaled $141 million, or $1.39 a
share, down 3 percent from $145 million, or $1.44 a year earlier.
   Revenue during the period rose 16 percent to $2.98 billion, from
$2.56 billion in the year-ago period.
   ``The numbers speak for themselves,'' said Caterpillar spokesman
Keith Butterfield. ``They are on track with our outlook released in
January. We said we expected sales to improve and we anticipated
flat earnings this year.''
   Caterpillar said domestic sales of its tractors and heavy
machinery totaled $1.42 billion for the quarter, up 6 percent from
1988, while foreign sales jumped 28 percent to $1.56 billion.
   For the first six months, net income totaled $282 million, or
$2.78 a share, up from $263 million, or $2.60 a share in the first
half of 1988. Revenue during the period jumped to $5.61 billion
from $4.90 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
