<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     07-21 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth Plan To Reorganize Consumer Products Business Unveiled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. on Friday
introduced its sixth proposal to reorganize its consumer products
business, including its crown jewels, Sunbeam Corp. and
non-operating Chemetron Corp.
   The company acknowledged that the framework of a plan adopted by
its board may lack enough support among creditors to win adoption
in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, where Allegheny International has been
trying to reorganize since February 1988.
   Management has so far filed five reorganization plans in court,
all of which have failed.
   ``This particular version has the support of somebody other than
the management. It's different in this regard,'' said Robert Sable,
attorney for unsecured creditors. ``This has a little more momentum
than some of the others, but it's not a sure thing by any means.''
   The latest proposal calls for paying $400 million in cash to
settle claims against Sunbeam and the principal on Allegheny
International's secured bank debt.
   A $50 million note would be issued against claims by Sunbeam's
institutional lenders and the parent's senior secured bank lenders.
   The note is to be paid on claims filed since Allegheny
International sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy law. It could be surrendered after one year to
acquire two-thirds of the common stock in the reorganized company.
   Allegheny International said it had a commitment for bank
financing for the plan. Unsecured lenders would get bonds and
preferred stock, and shareholders would be left with 5 percent of
the equity in the reorganized company.
   The company said it anticipates filing the new plan in
bankruptcy court in August.
   Allegheny International's fifth plan, filed in court May 31,
called for a separate reorganization for Sunbeam. The plan did not
receive enough creditor support to win adoption.
   Chemetron is the non-operating remnant of a former chemical and
industrial gas business.
   Allegheny International's management no longer has the exclusive
right to propose reorganization plans. Various creditor groups are
drafting plans, but Sable said none expects to file in court
``within the next couple of weeks.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
