<DOCNO> AP890721-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 2155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CalFed-Exec     07-21 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CalFed-Exec,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>CalFed Chairman Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CalFed Inc. announced that John R. Torell III
resigned Friday as head of the nation's fourth-largest thrift
holding company.
   ``In stepping aside during a time of momentum and progress at
CalFed, I am accommodating the desire of the board to make a change
at the helm,'' said Torell, who served as chairman, chief executive
and president.
   ``The company is in good financial condition and has positive
expectations for the future; it is definitely on the right track,''
he added.
   Jerry St. Dennis, 46, was appointed president and chief
executive officer while director Arthur W. Schmutz, 67, was
appointed chairman of the board.
   William L. Callender will continue as president and chief
executive officer of California Federal Bank, CalFed's flagship
subsidiary.
   Torell, 50, came to CalFed in August 1988 after serving as
president of Manufacturers Hanover Corp. and Manufacturers Hanover
Trust.
   He and St. Dennis implemented a plan to boost earnings from
CalFed's savings and loan, insurance and investment management
operations, said company spokesman James F. Hurley.
   While he did not indicate what his next step would be, Torell
``feels that he'll certainly stay in the banking industry,'' Hurley
said.
   CalFed's first-quarter profits totaled $17.5 million, down from
$35.8 million a year ago. Assets totaled $28.3 billion as of March
31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
