<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks soared Friday to new post-crash
highs while the rest of the market edged upward in a session
dominated by program-trading activity.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 31.87 points to
2,607.36, its highest close since it stood at 2,640.18 on Oct. 5,
1987.
   For the week the average posted a 52.54-point gain.
   Advancing issues just barely outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 723 up, 712
down and 526 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 174.88 million
shares, down from 204.59 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 206.96 million shares.
   The upsurge in blue chips, about half of which came in the final
moments of trading, was attributed in large measure to
computer-program activity by professionals closing out positions in
expiring options and stock-index futures.
   In addition, analysts said it appeared that other traders moved
into the stocks earlier in the session, apparently anticipating
heavy demand at the close for the big-name stocks.
   In Thursday's session, program trading was also cited as a force
contributing to market volatility. Prices staged a strong advance
Thursday morning, but those gains failed to stand up to the
pressure of late selling.
   Analysts said that reversal served to dampen some of the
enthusiasm stirred up by the market's impressive advance of late.
   In addition, interest rates rose slightly in the credit markets
Friday as bond prices gave back a bit of their recent gains.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up 1 at 46};
General Electric, up 1[ at 56~; International Business Machines, up
1] at 114[; General Motors, up 1{ at 44~, and American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up \ at 37].
   McDonald's edged up \ to 31{. The company reported
second-quarter earnings of 53 cents a share, up from 47 cents in
the comparable period a year earlier.
   Bankamerica rose \ to 28}. On Thursday the company reported a
larger increase in second-quarter earnings than analysts had been
expecting.
   USAir Group climbed 1[ to 50~ in active trading. An group led by
New York investor Michael Steinhardt said it owns 5.89 percent of
USAir's stock and may consider seeking control of the airline
company.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $15.11 billion, or
0.46 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.04 to 187.15.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.35 to 385.31, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 2.39 at 335.90.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.05 to 449.29. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 371.28, up .09.
