<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-21 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in U.S.; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar wound up the week higher in U.S.
trading Friday after a mixed performance overseas amid differing
opinions about the outlook for U.S. interest rates.
   Gold prices posted modest gains in U.S. trading.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
finished at $372.40 a troy ounce, $1 higher than Thursday's
settlement. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of
$372.25 for an ounce of bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, up from Thursday's
late bid of $370.85.
   Currency dealers said the dollar withstood some early selling in
the aftermath of remarks by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan indicating that the central bank's highest priority now
is to prevent a recession.
   In his midyear report on the economy to Congress, Greenspan
implied that the Fed would push down interest rates if necessary to
prevent what he termed an ``unnecessary and destructive'' recession.
   But Greenspan's comments were open to numerous interpretations,
dealers said. According to one view, the Fed might think it already
has done enough to enliven the economy, which in recent months has
sent out sluggish signals.
   If this is true, the central bank might not want to drive down
interest rates any further until it determines whether the economy
needs extra stimulation. Falling U.S. interest rates tend to reduce
demand for dollars.
   A huge weekly increase in a broad measure of the nation's money
supply raised speculation that Fed actions in recent weeks have
provided significant economic stimulation.
   The Fed reported late Thursday that the money measure known as
M2 jumped $17.5 billion in the week ended July 10. M2 includes all
money readily available for spending, such as cash and travelers
checks, plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual
funds.
   ``Fears that the Fed is going to be easing considerably were
eased by the M2 number,'' said Brady Benson, a currency market
analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In currency trading abroad, the dollar had a mixed showing. Late
in European trading, the dollar recovered ground as traders
adjusted their currency holdings ahead of Sunday's elections for
about half of the seats in Japan's Parliament, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar eased to 142.15 Japanese yen from 142.33
yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, the dollar slipped
further to 141.90 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 141.85
yen, up from 141.40 yen late Thursday.
   The British pound came under selling pressure in anticipation of
changes in Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's cabinet. In London,
the pound fell to $1.6185 from $1.6273 late Thursday. In New York
it cost $1.6187 to buy one pound, compared to Thursday's exchange
rate of $1.6230.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates included: 1.9095 West German marks, up from 1.9065;
1.6485 Swiss francs, up from 1.6465; 6.475 French francs, up from
6.4630; 1,378.25 Italian lire, up from 1,376.50; and 1.1879
Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with late rates on
Thursday were: 1.9055 West German marks, up from 1.9010; 1.6455
Swiss francs, up from 1.6405; 6.4460 French francs, unchanged;
2.1350 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1530; 1,371.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,378.50; and, 1.1880 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1872.
   Before moving higher in U.S. trading, gold prices posted mixed
results on foreign precious metals markets.
   Gold bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $371.50 a
troy ounce, down from $372.45 bid late Thursday. The metal rose in
Zurich to a late bid price of $372 from $371.75 bid late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.56 to a closing bid of
$372.67 per troy ounce.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid of $5.21 a troy
ounce, down from $5.22 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery closed at $5.186 a troy ounce,
up from $5.181 on Thursday.
</TEXT>
