<FIRST>r f AM-Cattle-Feedlot     07-21 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle-Feedlot,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Table in body type</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle feedlot inventories in the nation's 13
leading beef states totaled 8.46 million head as of July 1, down 6
percent from a year ago and 2 percent fewer than two years ago, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Only Colorado and Idaho showed increases from a year ago, while
decreases were reported in Arizona, California, Illinois, Iowa,
Kansas, Nebraska Oklahoma, South Dakota, Texas and Washington.
Minnesota was reported as unchanged.
   Marketings of fed cattle for slaughter during April, May and
June totaled 5.99 million head, up 2 percent from the same period
of 1988 and 7 percent above 1987, the report said.
   Further, the placement of new cattle and calves on feed during
the second quarter of the year totaled 5.18 million head, down 12
percent from last year and also down 12 percent from two years ago.
   That was the smallest second-quarter placement of cattle in
feedlots since 1975, the report said.
   Cattle feeders indicated they expect to market 6.04 million head
during July, August and September, down 2 percent from last year's
second quarter and fractionally more than in 1987, the report said.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the 13
states, which account for about 85 percent of the nation's beef.
The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as of July
1, and the second number is the percentage change from a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
