<FIRST>u f AM-USAir     07-21 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir,0354</SECOND>
<UNK>USAir Stock Climbs Amid Takeover Speculation</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of USAir Group Inc. stock climbed
Friday in response to a New York investor group's disclosure that
it now owns 5.88 percent of USAir's stock and may consider seeking
control of the airline company.
   USAir, which rose $2.12{ a share on Thursday, jumped another
$1.12{ a share to close at $50.87{ Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   In a statement filed Thursday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in Washington, attorneys for Wall Street investor
Michael Steinhardt said Steinhardt's group may buy more of the
stock.
   Steinhardt ``may also consider seeking to acquire control of the
company in the future, although he has no plans or proposals to do
so at the present,'' they said.
   ``We are still reviewing the (Steinhardt) filing,'' USAir
spokeswoman Susan Young said Friday from the company's headquarters
in Alexandria, Va.
   Steinhardt, 48, recently was ranked as the 15th most successful
investor in Wall Street by Financial World Magazine, which
estimated his earnings at $40 million.
   He manages an estimated $1.3 billion in assets. One of his
companies, Steinhardt Partners, this month offered to buy bankrupt
Allegheny International Inc. for a package it valued at $700
million. Steinhardt tried to buy CNW Corp. for $1.6 billion last
year, but lost out to a higher bid.
   Steinhardt has been an investor in USAir for more than a year.
His holdings have hovered around 5 percent of the company's stock,
occasionally going over that level and then retreating.
   In previous filings, Steinhardt has said he was buying USAir
stock for investment purposes. Thursday's filing was the first
mention of a possible takeover.
   Three years ago, USAir was considered in danger of being taken
over by a larger airline. It responded by buying Pacific Southwest
Airlines and Piedmont Airlines, more than doubling its size.
   USAir last month took action to ward off potential unfriendly
suitors by strengthening its ``poison pill'' takeover defense plan.
   USAir earned $165 million last year on revenue of $5.7 billion.
</TEXT>
