<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1757EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-21 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Prices Fall; Weather Gets Blame</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell modestly Friday on the Chicago Board
of Trade while an executive of the Italian firm Ferruzzi
Finanziaria S.p.A. said the exchange had put the soybean market
``in serious trouble'' by forcing traders to liquidate their
holdings.
   Analysts attributed Friday's price decline more to improved
growing conditions than to the ongoing dispute between Ferruzzi and
the exchange.
   Corn and wheat futures finished mixed in quiet trading.
   On other markets, pork-belly futures prices fell sharply while
livestock futures were mixed, precious metals advanced and crude
oil futures declined.
   Soybeans settled 3{ cents to 7{ cents lower with the contract
for delivery in August at $6.73} a bushel; wheat was 2{ cents lower
to { cent higher with September at $3.95} a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.39{ a bushel; and oats
were 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with September at $1.50 a bushel.
   Analysts said four days of showers in the western Corn Belt had
revived corn and soybean crops, and forecasts for the coming week
predicted no return to the withering heat of late June and early
July.
   News that federal regulators had ordered Ferruzzi to reduce its
holdings in the now-expired July futures contract last week also
weighed on the soybean market, prompting worries that Ferruzzi
might be forced to reduce its reputedly sizeable position in the
August contract.
   But Ted Mao, a grain specialist in New York with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., said the Ferruzzi news was a minor factor in Friday's
market.
   ``The market in general has been responding to better weather,''
he said.
   In Des Moines, Iowa, Ferruzzi executive David Swanson urged an
audience of more than 1,700 soybean producers and traders to form a
committee to study and improve the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``Today, as we are well aware, the market is in serious
trouble,'' Swanson, president of Ferruzzi's Central Soya Co.
subsidiary, told the annual convention of the American Soybean
Association.
   The Board of Trade issued an emergency order July 11 requiring
traders to reduce their holdings in the July soybean contract to 1
million bushels prior to the contract's expiration. The contract
expired on Thursday.
   The order was widely seen as a move to prevent Ferruzzi from
cornering the soybean market, a charge the company denies.
   Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann told the soybean
growers that the exchange took the action to prevent defaults on
contracts to deliver soybeans. Without the order, the board has
said, obligations to deliver soybeans might have outnumbered the
supply of deliverable soybeans.
   Frozen pork-belly futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, erasing the previous day's gains, and a
government report released after the close of trading left analysts
divided on the market's likely future course.
   The Agriculture Department report showed 128.8 million pounds of
pork bellies in the nation's commercial freezers as of July 1, the
largest July 1 supply since the record-high 133.2 million pounds
reported in 1964.
   The hefty supply of bellies, the part of the pig from which
bacon is made, has pulled prices down to nine-year lows.
   Thomas Moragan, president of Sterling Research Corp. in
Arlington Heights, Ill., said recent indications of increased belly
usage suggest the supplies of bellies might at last be dwindling
and prices could start moving higher.
   But Charles Levitt, Shearson's chief livestock analyst, was
skeptical.
   ``When you're at a nine-year low anything is possible, but the
fact remains that we have the largest supply of pork bellies in
storage in 25 years,'' Levitt said.
   The USDA also issued its monthly and quarterly cattle-on-feed
reports. Both reports showed slightly fewer cattle being fattened
for slaughter than the market had expected, and analysts termed the
reports neutral to slightly bullish for futures prices.
   Live cattle settled .08 cent lower to .25 cent cent higher with
August at 72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to
.20 cent higher with August at 83.85 cents a pound; hogs were
unchanged to .53 cent lower with August at 45.72 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .60 cent to 1.45 cents lower with July at
29.95 cents a pound.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 80 cents higher
across the board with August at $373 a troy ounce; silver was 0.3
cent to 1.5 cents higher with July at $5.186 a troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 17 cents lower to 4 cents higher with September
at $19.51 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to .54 cent lower with
August at 51.29 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .16 cent
lower to .42 cent higher with August at 54.52 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
