<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1830EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ICHOffer     07-21 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ICH Offer,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Investment Company Makes Offer for I.C.H.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock in I.C.H. Corp. jumped nearly 60
percent Friday in response to a takeover bid even though directors
of the insurance holding company have not decided if the company is
for sale.
   A group formed by Hicks, Muse &amp; Co., a new Dallas-based
leveraged buyout partnership, late Thursday offered $425 million in
cash for I.C.H.'s common shares and said it would assume $1.69
billion in I.C.H. debt and preferred stock.
   The stock offer is $8.50 a share. I.C.H.'s stock jumped to
$6.12{ Friday on the American Stock Exchange, up sharply from
$3.87{ the previous session but still below the offering price.
That indicated investors were skeptical the deal would go through.
   Robert T. Shaw, chairman and chief executive of I.C.H., said in
a news release Friday that the company's board had not yet
determined if I.C.H. is for sale to ``any purchaser on any terms.''
   The offer is subject to a number of conditions, he said,
including the cancellation of all outstanding shares of I.C.H.'s
class B common stock, or a binding agreement with Consolidated
National Successor Corp. regarding the special voting rights those
shares have.
   Consolidated holds 100 percent of the outstanding shares of
I.C.H. class B stock. Consolidated also was reviewing the
proposition, the news release said.
   I.C.H.'s subsidiaries include Southwestern Life Insurance Co.,
Philadelphia Life Insurance Co. and Great Southern Life Insurance
Co., all of Dallas. I.C.H. also owns Bankers Life and Casualty Co.
in Chicago.
   According to the company's 1988 annual report, it employed 4,000
people. The corporation's products also are represented by about
39,000 independent agents.
   The corporation's earnings have sagged in the past two years.
I.C.H. reported a net loss of $10.7 million on revenue of $568
million for the first quarter of this year. Its second-quarter
figures have not been released yet.
   The company also has met with disappointment in its attempts at
mergers and acquisitions.
   Most recently I.C.H. had been planning to spend about $158
million to gain control of Integrated Resources. But the deal was
called off May 25 by the New York financial services company.
   Even before the collapse of that deal, analysts were saying the
corporation lacked enough capital to have room to maneuver in such
deals.
   Despite the uncertainty that has surrounded I.C.H., Thomas O.
Hicks, chief executive officer and chairman of Hicks, Muse, said
Thursday in a release:
   ``We are attracted to the niche characteristics and strong
market position of its core operating companies. It would be our
intention to follow our practice in previous acquisitions of
inviting key management to invest with us in the transaction.''
   Hicks, Muse was formed in May by Hicks and John R. Muse, a
former managing director of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Hicks was a former partner in a Dallas investment firm called
Hicks &amp; Haas, which was dissolved in May.
</TEXT>
