<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1832EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     07-21 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Pull Back; Interest Rates Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes for lower interest rates faded Friday in
the credit markets as traders reassessed remarks made a day earlier
by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   The pessimism pushed bond prices down. The Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond was off 9-32 point, or $2.81 per $1,000 in face
amount. The yield, which rises when the price falls, edged up to
8.15 percent from 8.13 percent late Thursday.
   Greenspan said Thursday in a midyear report to Congress the Fed
had shifted its top priority to avoiding a deep recession from
fighting inflation. Bond prices rallied after the remarks but then
receded late Thursday and on into Friday.
   ``By the time we heard the entire testimony it became clear that
the Fed doesn't have all the evidence it wants'' to cut interest
rates right away, said Fred N. Peck, president and chief economist
of Hillcrest Economics Group in New City, N.Y.
   Cutting rates would stimulate economic growth, but it could also
lead to a resurgence of inflation.
   A huge weekly increase in a broad measure of the nation's money
supply, announced late Thursday, indicated there may already be
plenty of money in the banking system to fuel economic growth.
   ``If they ease at all they're going to need a lot of evidence
that the economy is slowing,'' Peck said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments were down 1-32 point to 3-32 point,
intermediate maturities dropped 1-16 point to [ point and long-term
issues declined 5-32 point to 11-32 point, according to Telerate
Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, declined 1.41 to 1,185.97.
   In corporate trading, industrials also posted declines. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, fell 0.07 to 329.39.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1-16 point to 94 17-32. The average
yield to maturity was 7.20 percent, about even with late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills increased to 8.37 percent
as the discount rose 6 basis points to 8.10 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 8.21 percent as the discount rose 5 basis
points to 7.79 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8 percent
as the discount rose 2 basis points to 7.47 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 9[ percent, down from 93-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
