<FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1845EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Marion-Kauffman Bjt   07-21 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marion-Kauffman, Bjt,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kauffman Says He's Sad Marion Had to Be Sold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marion Laboratories Inc. chairman Ewing
Kauffman didn't want to relinquish control of the company he
founded almost 40 years ago, but says he knew he had to.
   The drugmaker's future depended on new products, and heavy
competition was blocking it from finding those on its own.
   ``I personally did not wish to sell. It's my baby,'' Kauffman
said in an interview on Friday.
   But he said his concern for stockholders and employees won out.
He encouraged Marion officials to look for a partner and supported
their choice of a Dow Chemical Co. subsidiary, Merrell Dow
Pharmaceuticals.
   Under a deal announced Monday, the merger will create the third
largest pharmaceutical company in the nation. Kauffman will sell a
big chunk of his 23 percent stake in Marion and accept a switch to
chairman emeritus. He says he'll leave in one year.
   ``It is emotional,'' Kauffman said. ``I originally did
everything in this company.''
   But Kauffman's reduced role at Marion won't be the end of the
hard work he loves. In the wings wait expanded roles with the
Kansas City Royals baseball team he co-owns and more charity work.
   At 72, Kauffman remains as plainspoken and practical as he was
in 1950, when he took $5,000 in card-playing earnings from the Navy
and started a business selling pills to physicians and hospitals
from the basement of his Kansas City home.
   A picture of that house hangs inside the front door of the
company's current headquarters, dubbed the ``Taj Mahal'' by
Kauffman.
   Kauffman worked 16 hours a day as Marion grew quickly, going
public in 1965. ``That was all fun, that was a lot of fun,'' he
said.
   After a dry spell in the 1970s, Marion's sales exploded in the
late 1970s on the strength of the heart drug Cardizem.
   Unlike many pharmaceutical companies, Marion doesn't do its own
basic chemical research. Instead, it licenses compounds from other
companies, develops them for medical use and sells them.
   Company officials project $1 billion in sales this year, but
analysts said those sales would dip in 1992, when other companies
can begin making generic versions of Cardizem.
   More importantly, Marion didn't have another big moneymaking
drug under development. Merrell Dow, with a strong research budget,
seemed the perfect fit.
   ``The merger guarantees growth through the 90s and past the year
2000,'' he said. ``It will make us not only stronger, but better.''
   It also will put a lot of money into the pockets of Kauffman,
his family and trusts and foundations. Kauffman will sell 39
percent of his stake in Marion under terms of the merger. His stake
is currently valued at about $1.3 billion.
   Much of that money will go into his charitable foundation and
some will be pumped into the Royals, he said. Kauffman plans a
bigger role with the team, especially in player development and
scouting.
   Despite his success, most Kansas Citians don't think of Kauffman
as the founder of a billion-dollar company. He's simply ``Mr. K,''
the man who brought major-league baseball back to the Midwest after
Charles Finley took the Athletics away in 1967.
   But the whole thing was an accident, he said. Civic leaders
recruited him almost against his will and wife Muriel encouraged
him.
   ``She said that I was working too hard and I needed some
diversion,'' Kauffman said.
   In many ways, the team has gone against his businessman
instincts.
   ``I would have made more money if I'd invested it in a savings
and loan at 5 percent,'' he says with a grimace.
   Kauffman sold part interest in the Royals to Memphis businessman
Avron Fogelman in the early 1980s. He discounts recent speculation
about Fogelman's real-estate business and says the team won't be
moved from Kansas City.
   ``It is secure now, and it will be secure in the future,'' he
said.
   Although just a ``casual fan,'' Kauffman said he has enjoyed the
Royals' winning years, including the 1985 World Series championship.
   He's also enjoyed his eighth-graders.
   Since 1988, Kauffman has offered to send nearly 700 of them to
college or vocational school, if they promise to stay in school,
keep up their grades and steer clear of teen parenthood and drugs.
   Kauffman estimates the first group of 225 students from his
inner-city high school alma mater would cost him $13 million. It's
money well-spent, both for the fun he has and the practical
benefits, he said.
   ``It's going to get more difficult as they get older, of course,
but we think we're going to turn a lot of them into tax-paying
citizens instead of welfare recipients.''
   For the future, those activities will keep him busy.
   ``I'm satisfied with all this,'' he said. ``But I'm not
fulfilled. You always have more you want to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
