<FIRST>u f AM-LIN-McCaw     07-21 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Suspends Talks with LIN, Extends Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. said
Friday that it has extended its $110 a share tender offer for LIN
Broadcasting Corp., and suspended negotiations with LIN about
offering a higher price.
   The announcement sent LIN's stock price lower in active trading.
   LIN lost $2.87{ a share to $109.62{ in national over-the-counter
trading, while McCaw rose 87{ cents a share to $36.62{.
   McCaw's tender offer, which values the New York-based LIN at
about $5.9 billion, had been scheduled to expire at midnight EDT
Friday. It now will expire three weeks later, at midnight EDT Aug.
11, unless extended further.
   To date, approximately 3.1 million LIN shares have been
tendered, McCaw said. Before McCaw launched its takeover effort
last month, it already was LIN's largest shareholder with about 5
million shares, or 9.8 percent of LIN's 53.9 million shares.
   McCaw is the nation's largest cellular telephone company with
franchises serving customers in Seattle, San Francisco, Miami,
Denver, Minneapolis and Portland, Ore.
   LIN has a number of major-market cellular interests, owns seven
television stations and publishes city guides for use in hotel
rooms.
   McCaw launched its bid for LIN at $120 a share in early June,
but LIN rejected that as inadequate. It later lowered its bid to
$110 a share, citing a recent New York court ruling that denied
LIN's claim to certain cellular interests of Metromedia Co. in New
York City and Philadelphia.
   The companies later said they were discussing a proposal in
which each share of LIN stock would be exchanged for cash and stock
having an aggregate value of $127.50 a share.
   McCaw said Friday that ``while it has been engaged in
negotiations with LIN about acquiring the company at a higher
price, the parties have been unable to resolve several significant
issues.''
   Because of that, McCaw said it had suspended the negotiations
pending further study.
</TEXT>
