<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McDonald's     07-21 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McDonald's,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fast-Food Chain Second-Quarter Profit Up 11 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp. said Friday its
second-quarter earnings rose 11 percent to $196 million from $177
million for the same period last year.
   The profit translated to 53 cents a share compared with 47 cents
a share in the 1988 period. Quarterly revenue was $1.5 billion, up
9 percent from $1.4 million in the same quarter last year.
   McDonald's sales during the second quarter jumped 5 percent to
$4.3 billion from $4.1 billion during the comparable 1988 period.
   McDonald's attributed the sales increase to new restaurants and
higher sales at existing restaurants. Several marketing and
promotion programs, including the introduction of the McChicken
sandwich, also contributed.
   ``We believe 1989 will be another good year of growth in sales
and profits,'' McDonald's Chairman Fred L. Turner said. ``Our
management team has not changed its expectations, even though we
had one of our strongest operating years in 1988, which has made
comparison difficult for the first six months of this year.''
   For the first six months of 1989, net income was $337.7 million,
or 90 cents a share, up 11 percent from $303 million during the
same 1988 period. Revenue during the period was $2.9 billion, up 10
percent from last year's $2.6 billion.
   Systemwide sales for the six months totaled $8.2 billion, a 7
percent increase from $7.7 billion reported for the period last
year.
</TEXT>
